<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>&THORN;<SUP>E</SUP> HOLY RODE. [Ashm. MS. Bodleian Lib. 43.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Collated with Harl. MS. 2277 (imperfect). </NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E holi rode &thorn;e swete tre<NOTE PLACE="marg">treo.</NOTE>; ri&yogh;t is to habbe in munde<MILESTONE N="63b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; fram stronge de&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">de&thorn;e.</NOTE> ibro&yogh;t to lyue; al mankunde</L>
<L>&THORN;oru<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;urf.</NOTE> a<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;ulke.</NOTE> tre<NOTE PLACE="marg">treo.</NOTE> we<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;at we.</NOTE> were uerst uorlore<NOTE PLACE="marg">furst ibou&yogh;t.</NOTE>; and uerst ibro&yogh;t to grounde</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;oru a tre se&thorn;&thorn;e to lyue<NOTE PLACE="marg">And si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;urf a treo to lyue.</NOTE> ibro&yogh;t&middot; ihered be &thorn;ulke stounde</L>
<L>Al [h]it com of one more; &thorn;at ous to de&thorn;e bro&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg">brou&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at ous bro&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg">brou&yogh;te.</NOTE> to lyue a&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="marg">a&yogh;e.</NOTE>; &thorn;oru&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;urf.</NOTE> ihesus &thorn;at ous bo&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg">bou&yogh;te.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e appeltre<NOTE PLACE="marg">Of &thorn;e treo.</NOTE> &thorn;at our uerste<NOTE PLACE="marg">omitted.</NOTE> fader; &thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e.</NOTE> lu&thorn;er appel nom</L>
<L N="8">In &thorn;e manere &thorn;at ichulle<NOTE PLACE="marg">ich wole.</NOTE> &yogh;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">&yogh;ou nou.</NOTE> telle; &thorn;e swete rode com</L>
<L>&THORN;o adam our<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e.</NOTE> uerste fader<NOTE PLACE="marg">man.</NOTE>; &thorn;e sunne<NOTE PLACE="marg">sinne.</NOTE> hadde ido</L>
<L>And idriue was out of parais; and eue is<NOTE PLACE="marg">his.</NOTE> wif also</L>
<L>After milse &yogh;erne<NOTE PLACE="marg">&yogh;urne.</NOTE> hi cride; &thorn;ei it<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e&yogh; hit.</NOTE> late were</L>
<L N="12">Ane<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>And</I>, H. Ane.</NOTE> bi-heste [he] hadde of our lord<NOTE PLACE="marg">louerd.</NOTE>; &thorn;o me him drof out &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">omitted.</NOTE> wen<NOTE PLACE="marg">whan.</NOTE> &thorn;e tyme were uolueld<NOTE PLACE="marg">fulfuld.</NOTE>; our lord<NOTE PLACE="marg">louerd.</NOTE> him wolde bi&thorn;enche</L>
<L>And wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">mid.</NOTE> oile of mylse smerie<NOTE PLACE="marg">smirie.</NOTE> him; and his sunne<NOTE PLACE="marg">sinne.</NOTE> quenche<NOTE PLACE="marg">aquenche.</NOTE></L>
<L>Gret hope hadde to &thorn;is biheste; adam euermo<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="16">In &thorn;e ualeie of ebron; he lyuede in tene and wo</L>
<L>Twei sone he hadde se&thorn;&thorn;e; caym and abel</L>
<L>&THORN;at on slou&yogh; &thorn;at o&thorn;er uor en-vie; as &yogh;e wite&thorn; wel
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>&THORN;o caym hadde his bro&thorn;er aslawe; iflemd he was &thorn;eruore</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;o adam isei &thorn;at he hadde; is twei sones uorlore</L>
<L>He wep and made deol Inou&yogh;; lord he sede &thorn;in ore</L>
<L>Ney womman ichabbe to muche ibe; Inele com ney hire nammore</L>
<L>&THORN;re harmes ichabbe &thorn;oru hire iheued; my-sulf uerst uorlore</L>
<L N="24">And myne sones bo&thorn;e alas; and of al womman is more</L>
<L>Nolde adam come &thorn;o ney is wif; two hondred &yogh;er ne more</L>
<L>Vor wo &thorn;at he hadde uor hire; and euere he lyuede in sore</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he hadde toknynge of our lord; &thorn;at he scholde to is wif wende</L>
<L N="28">Ne dorste he no&yogh;t be &thorn;er a&yogh;en; an sone he hadde aten|ende</L>
<L>Seth he let is name <NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>n</I> not quite clear.</NOTE>nempne; and se&thorn;&thorn;e he hadde mo</L>
<L>Al is lif &thorn;e seli mon; ladde in tene and wo</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was of nyne hondred &yogh;er; and two and &thorn;ritti old</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e streng&thorn;e him failede of is lymes; is bodi bicom al cold</L>
<L>He ne mi&yogh;te no&yogh;t swynke aboute &thorn;e er&thorn;e; &thorn;e wedus up to drawe</L>
<L>Of is lif he was anuyd; he wilnede be of dawe</L>
<L>He sat and carede of is lif; he clupede is sone seth</L>
<L N="36">Sone he sede icham weri ileued; ich wilny muche my de&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich was idryue of parais; our lord bihet me &thorn;ere</L>
<L>To smere me wi&thorn; &thorn;e oile of mylce; wen it tyme were</L>
<L>So longe ichabbe abide &thorn;<I>er</I>-after; &thorn;at I ne may libbe nammore</L>
<L N="40">To parais &thorn;ou most &thorn;<I>er</I>-after go; and bidde him mylce and ore
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>&THORN;e angel &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;er Ifynde; &thorn;at drof me out at &thorn;e &yogh;ate</L>
<L>Say ich abide &thorn;ulke biheste; me &thorn;enc&thorn; it come&thorn; to late</L>
<L>And &thorn;at elde me ha&thorn; ouercome; &thorn;at I ne may libbe longe</L>
<L N="44">Bede him &thorn;at ich deie mote; and &thorn;e oile of mylce auonge<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>auonde</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ine can nanne wei qua&thorn; is sone; &thorn;uderward ich wene</L>
<L>Leue sone qua&thorn; adam; &thorn;e wei is wel i-sene</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ou comst to &thorn;e ende of &thorn;is ualeie; a grene wei &thorn;ou schalt wende</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at ri&yogh;t euene estward ge&thorn;; to parais last &thorn;e on ende</L>
<L>&THORN;er-bi wende &thorn;i moder and ich; &thorn;o ich parais uor-let</L>
<L>Euerich stepe &thorn;at we on stepe; uorbarnde under our uet</L>
<L>Ne my&yogh;te neuereft &thorn;er gras growe; and al &thorn;e o&thorn;er wei is grene</L>
<L N="52">For &thorn;e foule sunne &thorn;at we dude; our stapes wor&thorn; isene</L>
<L>&THORN;er-by &thorn;ou my&yogh;t wi&thorn;&thorn;oute defaute; to parays euene gon<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seth nom is fader blessyng; and wende him uor&thorn; anon</L>
<L>&THORN;e stapes he vond uorwelwed; as is fader him sede</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;o he to &thorn;e &yogh;ate com; he ne dorste go ner vor drede</L>
<L>An angel com sone to &thorn;e &yogh;ate; and escte wat he so&yogh;te</L>
<L>He sede &thorn;at to him an ernde; fram his fader he bro&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was old and weri ilyued; and &thorn;at him longede sore</L>
<L N="60">After &thorn;e swete oyl of mylce; uor he ne my&yogh;te libbe nammore</L>
<L>&YOGH;e qua&thorn; &thorn;e angel is he so; he ne schal &thorn;er-of no&yogh;t doute
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>Put In &thorn;in heued at &thorn;e &yogh;ate; and stond &thorn;i-sulf wi&thorn;&thorn;oute</L>
<L>He pulte In is heued as he bed; and bi-huld al aboute</L>
<L N="64">So murie ne &thorn;o&yogh;te him neuer in no stude; &thorn;ei he stode him-sulf wi&thorn;&thorn;oute</L>
<L>So gret delit he hadde and Ioie; of &thorn;e foules murie song</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e swete med al-so; and of &thorn;e floures &thorn;er among</L>
<L>Of ech maner frut &thorn;at he sei; &thorn;at smolde also swote</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at of ech maner vuel as him &thorn;o&yogh;te; amon mi&yogh;te habbe &thorn;er-of bote</L>
<L>Him &thorn;o&yogh;te &yogh;if he moste &thorn;ere; biholde In eny stounde</L>
<L>Euermo he my&yogh;te In Ioie be; his lymes hol and sounde</L>
<L>Amydde &thorn;e place &thorn;at was so uair; he sei an vaire welle</L>
<L N="72">Of wan alle &thorn;e wateres &thorn;at be&thorn; aner&thorn;e come&thorn;; as &thorn;e &thorn;e bok de&thorn; telle</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e welle stod a tre; wi&thorn; bowes brode and lere<NOTE PLACE="marg">? sere.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ac it ne bar no&thorn;er lef ne rynde; as it uorolded were</L>
<L>A neddre it hadde biclupt aboute; al naked wi&thorn;&thorn;o&yogh;te skynne</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at was &thorn;e tre and &thorn;e addre; &thorn;at made adam uerst do sunne</L>
<L>Efsone he bihuld In ate &yogh;ate; &thorn;e tre him &thorn;o&yogh;te he sei</L>
<L>Vaire ileued and iwoxe; up to heuene an hei</L>
<L>A &yogh;ong child he sei up &thorn;e tre; in smale clo&thorn;es iwounde</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;e more of<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of to.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e tre him &thorn;o&yogh;te tilde; &thorn;oru-out helle grounde</L>
<L>His bro&thorn;er soule abel ek; him &thorn;o&yogh;te In helle he sei</L>
<L>&THORN;e angel him drof &thorn;o fram &thorn;e &yogh;ate; &thorn;at he nas nammore &thorn;er nei</L>
<L>&THORN;e child he sede &thorn;at &thorn;ou isei&yogh;; a noueward &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="84">Godes sone it was &thorn;at wole aner&thorn;e; uor &thorn;ine fader sunne be</L>
<L>And &thorn;e oile of milce wi&thorn; him bringe; wen &thorn;e tyme Iuelle is</L>
<L>And smere &thorn;er-wi&thorn; and bringe of pyne; &thorn;i fader and alle his
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>&THORN;e angel wende to &thorn;ulke tre; an appel &thorn;er-of he nom</L>
<L N="88">And tok seth &thorn;er-of &thorn;re curneles; &thorn;o he to him com</L>
<L>And bed him &thorn;ulke curneles legge; vnder is fader tonge</L>
<L>And burie him wen he were ded; and loke wat &thorn;er-of spronge</L>
<L>Seth wende a&yogh;en as he com; uor &thorn;e wei was wel isene</L>
<L N="92">Vor &thorn;e stepes were al uorbrend; and &thorn;e o&thorn;er wei al grene<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o he was hom a&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="marg">a&yogh;e.</NOTE> icome; his fader he fond ded</L>
<L>&THORN;e curneles he dude vnder is<NOTE PLACE="marg">his.</NOTE> tonge<NOTE PLACE="marg">tunge.</NOTE>; as &thorn;e angel<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;angel.</NOTE> him hadde ised</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">si&thorn;&thorn;e.</NOTE> he burede him as ri&yogh;t was; in ualeie<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e val.</NOTE> of ebron</L>
<L N="96">And of-swonke is owe<NOTE PLACE="marg">omitted.</NOTE> mete<NOTE PLACE="marg">so in H., but read <I>mede.</I></NOTE>; he nuste no betere iwon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;&thorn;ynne an<NOTE PLACE="marg">a.</NOTE> vewe &yogh;er &thorn;er-after; &thorn;is curneles gonne [ups]pringe<NOTE PLACE="marg">vpspringe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;re [faire] &yogh;erden<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;reo faire &yogh;urden.</NOTE> &thorn;er woxe of<NOTE PLACE="marg">omitted.</NOTE>; vaire &thorn;oru alle &thorn;inge<NOTE PLACE="marg">fairest of alle &thorn;inge.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o hi were iwoxe to<NOTE PLACE="marg">omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;e leng&thorn;e; of an elne<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>helue.</I></NOTE> ich wene</L>
<L N="100">In &thorn;ulke stat hi stode longe; and euermore grene<NOTE PLACE="marg">andallegate faire and grene.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vorte moyses &thorn;e prophete; aboute eode<NOTE PLACE="marg">&yogh;eode.</NOTE> in &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>To lere &thorn;at folc of israel; [and] &thorn;o vond he &thorn;e &yogh;erdon stonde</L>
<L>Lo her he sede<NOTE PLACE="marg">seide.</NOTE> gret toknynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">tokning.</NOTE>; of &thorn;e holi trinyte</L>
<L N="104">Fader and sone and holi gost; of &thorn;is &yogh;erden &thorn;re</L>
<L>Vp he hem nom<NOTE PLACE="marg">Vp hi nome.</NOTE> wi&thorn; gret honur; and in auair<NOTE PLACE="marg">fair.</NOTE> clo&thorn; hem wond<NOTE PLACE="marg">hi wounde.</NOTE></L>
<L>A swote smul &thorn;er com out of<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;er-of.</NOTE>; &thorn;at smulde<NOTE PLACE="marg">smilde.</NOTE> in-to al &thorn;at lond<NOTE PLACE="marg">londe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Te confermy [&thorn;e] bet<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e bet.</NOTE> is lawe; he ber<NOTE PLACE="marg">her bar.</NOTE> hem uor&thorn; in<NOTE PLACE="marg">on.</NOTE> is hond</L>
<L N="108">Ech sikemon<NOTE PLACE="marg">sik man.</NOTE> [&thorn;at] &thorn;erto hopede; is hele anon<NOTE PLACE="marg">sone.</NOTE> he vond.</L>
<L>To teche &thorn;at folc &thorn;e ri&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg">ri&yogh;t.</NOTE> lawe; &thorn;e &yogh;erden aboute he ber
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>And eke to hele sikemen; two and fourti &yogh;er</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e he deie scholde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;o scholde deye.</NOTE>; &thorn;e &yogh;erden he sette er</L>
<L N="112">Vnder &thorn;e hul of tabor; deide him sulf<NOTE PLACE="marg">silf.</NOTE> &thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;er stode &thorn;e &yogh;erden grene; mo &thorn;en<NOTE PLACE="marg">more &thorn;an.</NOTE> a &thorn;ousend &yogh;er</L>
<L>Vorte Seint dauid &thorn;e kyng com; &thorn;at was of gret power</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was &thorn;oru &thorn;e holi gost; ihote vorte heie<NOTE PLACE="marg">hie.</NOTE></L>
<L N="116">To &thorn;e hul of tabor; in &thorn;e lond of arabie</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;ulke &yogh;erden &thorn;re<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;reo &yogh;eorden.</NOTE>; vette and wi&thorn; him nome</L>
<L>Nye dawes<NOTE PLACE="marg">Neo&yogh;e dayes.</NOTE> he was &thorn;uderward; ar<NOTE PLACE="marg">er.</NOTE> he &thorn;uder come</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret honur he nom hem up: &thorn;o he &thorn;e &yogh;erden vond<NOTE PLACE="marg">nom.</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;e suotnesse &thorn;at &thorn;<I>er</I>-of com; velde al &thorn;at lond</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret melodie of is harpe; Seint dauid &thorn;e &yogh;erden nom<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e suotnesse .... &yogh;erden nom. These two lines are omitted in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg">omitted.</NOTE> to ierusalem hem [he] ladde; and ny&thorn;e dai<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;e neo&yogh;e&thorn;e dai.</NOTE> hom he com</L>
<L>In a derne stude<NOTE PLACE="marg">In a durne stede.</NOTE> he hem sette; uor it was in &thorn;e euen|ynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">&thorn;eueninge.</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">Vorte amorwe &thorn;at he iseie<NOTE PLACE="marg">ise&yogh;.</NOTE>; wuder<NOTE PLACE="marg">whoder.</NOTE> he&middot; my&yogh;te hem bringe</L>
<L>A morwe &thorn;o he com &thorn;erto; to one hi were alle icome</L>
