<L>Wi&thorn; Oyle of Milce smere me&middot; whonne hit tyme were;</L>
<L>So longe ichabbe &thorn;er-aftur a-bide&middot; &thorn;at ich may libbe no more:</L>
<L N="40">To Paradys &thorn;ow most &thorn;er-after go&middot; and cr en him Milce and ore;
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Aungel &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;ere fynde&middot; &thorn;at drof me out atte &yogh;ate:</L>
<L>Sey &thorn;at ich a-byde &thorn;at ilke bi-heste&middot;, ac hit come&thorn; wel late,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at Elde me ha&thorn; ouercome&middot; &thorn;at i ne may libbe not longe;</L>
<L N="44">Bidde him &thorn;at ich dye mote&middot; and &thorn;e Oyle of Milce a|fonge":</L>
<L>&para; "I&middot; con no wey," qua&thorn; his sone, "&thorn;iderward &thorn;auh ich wene":</L>
<L>"Leue sone," qua&thorn; Adam &thorn;o&middot;, "&thorn;e wei is wel i-sene,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ou comest to &thorn;e hed of &thorn;is valeye&middot;, a grene wey &thorn;ou schalt fynde,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at ge&thorn; as euene as he may&middot; to paradys &thorn;e on ende;</L>
<L>&THORN;er bi&yogh;onde &thorn;i Modur and ich&middot;, &thorn;o we Paradys forleete,</L>
<L>Euerich stude&middot; &thorn;at we on stepten&middot; for brende al wi&thorn; vre fete;</L>
<L>Ne mihte neuer eft&middot; gras &thorn;er-on grouwe&middot;, and al &thorn;e o&thorn;ur wey is grene,</L>
<L N="52">For &thorn;e foule sunne &thorn;at we duden&middot; vr fet-steppes beo&thorn; euer sene;</L>
<L>&THORN;erbi &thorn;ou miht wi&thorn;-oute defaute&middot; to Paradys euene gon&middot;":</L>
<L>Seth; nom his fadur blessynge&middot;, and &thorn;e wey &thorn;iderward nom;</L>
<L>&THORN;e steppes he fond ful wel i-wered&middot; as his fader him sede:</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;o he to &thorn;e &yogh;ate com&middot; he dorste go no ner&middot; for drede&middot;:</L>
<L>&para; An Angel &thorn;er com sone to &thorn;e &yogh;ate&middot; and asked what he souhte:</L>
<L>He seide&middot; a ti&thorn;inge to him&middot; from his fader he brouhte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was Old&middot; and weri of-liued&middot;, and &thorn;at he was alonged sore</L>
<L N="60">After &thorn;e Oyle of Milce&middot;, &thorn;at him was bi-hote&middot;, for he mi&yogh;te libbe no more:</L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;e," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Angel, "is he so&middot;? he ne schal &thorn;er-of nout doute:
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>Pult in &thorn;yn hed&middot; here atte &yogh;ate&middot;, and stond &thorn;i-self wi&thorn;-oute":</L>
<L>He pult[e] in his hed&middot;, as he bad&middot;, and bi-heold al aboute;</L>
<L N="64">So murie &thorn;ou&yogh;te him neuere in no stude&middot;; &thorn;ei&yogh; his bodi weore wi&thorn;-oute,</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>&para; Him &thorn;hou&yogh;te&middot; &yogh;if he moste &thorn;ere&middot; bi-holden eny stounde,</L>
<L>Euermore he mihte in ioye libbe&middot;, in limes hol and sounde&middot;:</L>
<L>&para; Amidde &thorn;e place&middot; &thorn;at was so feir&middot; he sauh a feir welle,</L>
<L N="72">Of whom alle &thorn;e watres on eor&thorn;e come&thorn;&middot;, as &thorn;e Bok vs dee&thorn; telle;</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e welle stod a treo&middot;, wi&thorn; bowes brode and lere<NOTE PLACE="marg">? sere.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>Ac hit ne bar. Lef&middot; ne Rynde&middot;, bote as hit for-Oldet were;</L>
<L>A&middot; Neddre hit hedde bi-clupt a-boute&middot;, al naket wi&thorn;-outen skynne;</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at was &thorn;e treo&middot; and &thorn;e Neddre&middot; &thorn;at furst made Adam do synne:</L>
<L>He bi-heold eft sone in atte &yogh;ate&middot;, &thorn;at treo eft sone he seih,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e feir hed&middot; and i-woxen&middot; vp to heuene an heih;</L>
<L>A-nowarde he sayh&middot; a &yogh;ong smal child&middot;, in smale clo&thorn;es i-wounde:</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;e Roote of &thorn;e treo him &thorn;hou&yogh;te tilde&middot; a-doun to helle grounde;</L>
<L>Abeles soule his bro&thorn;ur also&middot; him &thorn;hou&yogh;te in helle he seih;</L>
<L>&THORN;o drof &thorn;e Angel&middot; him from &thorn;e &yogh;ate&middot; &thorn;at he no more ne seih:</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;e child," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Angel&middot;, "&thorn;at &thorn;ou se&yogh;e&middot; anouwarde on &thorn;e treo,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at was Godus sone&middot; &thorn;at wolde on eor&thorn;e&middot; for &thorn;i fader sunnes beo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Oyle of Milce bringe mid him&middot; whon &thorn;e tyme i-fuld is</L>
<L>To smere &thorn;er-wi&thorn;&middot; and bringen of peyne&middot; &thorn;i fader and alle his":
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o wende &thorn;e Angel&middot; to &thorn;ulke treo&middot;, an Appel &thorn;er-of he nom;</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;reo Curnels he tok him &thorn;<I>er</I>-of se&thorn;&thorn;e&middot;, &thorn;o he to him com,</L>
<L>And bad him &thorn;ulke Curnels&middot; legge vndur his fader tonge</L>
<L>Whon he weore ded&middot; and i-buried&middot;, to loke what &thorn;er-of spronge:</L>
<L>&para; Seth&middot; wende a-&yogh;eyn as he com&middot;, &thorn;e wey was wel y-sene,</L>
<L N="92">For &thorn;e stappes weore&middot; al for-brend&middot;, and &thorn;e o&thorn;ur wey al grene:</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was hom a-&yogh;ein i-come&middot; his fader he fond ded;</L>
<L>He dude &thorn;e Curnels vndur his tonge&middot;, as &thorn;e Angel him bed,</L>
<L>And se&thorn;&thorn;e buriede him, as riht was&middot;, in &thorn;e Vaal of Ebron,</L>
<L N="96">And bi-swonk his owne mede&middot;, &thorn;o he nuste non o&thorn;er whon:</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn;-Inne a fewe &yogh;er &thorn;eraftur&middot; &thorn;is Curnels bi-gonne to springe;</L>
<L>&THORN;reo smale &yogh;erden &thorn;er woxen&middot;, feire &thorn;orwh alle &thorn;inge;</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo weoren i-woxen to &thorn;e leng&thorn;e&middot; of an Elne, ich wene,</L>
<L N="100">In &thorn;ulke stat heo stoden longe&middot; and euere-more grene,</L>
<L>&para; Forte Moyses &thorn;e prophete&middot; eode her in &thorn;is londe</L>
<L>To leren &thorn;e folk of I[s]rael&middot;, and he fond &thorn;e &yogh;erden stonde:</L>
<L>"Lo her," he seide, "gret toknynge&middot; of &thorn;e holy Trinite,</L>
<L N="104">Of Fader&middot; and Sone&middot; and Holigost&middot;: of &thorn;eose &yogh;erden &thorn;re":</L>
<L>Vp he hem nom&middot; wi&thorn; gret honour&middot;, in feir clo&thorn; he hem wond;</L>
<L>A&middot; swote smel&middot; &thorn;er com a-non out of&middot;, &thorn;at smelde in-to al &thorn;at lond:</L>
<L>To Confermen bet his lawe&middot; he bar hem for&thorn; in his hond;</L>
<L N="108">Vche seek mon&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;<I>er</I>-to hopede&middot; his hele a-non he fond:</L>
<L>To teche &thorn;at folk &thorn;e rihte lawe&middot; &thorn;e &yogh;erden wi&thorn; him he beer,
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>And helede &thorn;er-wi&thorn; seke Men&middot;, two and Fourti &yogh;eer&middot;:</L>
<L>&para; Se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;o he dyen scholde&middot; &thorn;e &yogh;erden he sette er</L>
<L N="112">Vndur &thorn;e Hul of Tabor&middot;, and dyede him-self &thorn;er:</L>
<L>&THORN;o stoden &thorn;e &yogh;erden grene&middot; More &thorn;en A &thorn;ousund &yogh;eer</L>
<L>Forte seint Dauid&middot; &thorn;e kyng com&middot; &thorn;at was of gret pouweer,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was&middot;, &thorn;orwh &thorn;e holigost&middot;, i-hote forte hei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="116">To &thorn;e Hul of Tabor&middot;, in &thorn;e lond of Arabye;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;ulke &yogh;erden fette&middot; and heom wi&thorn; him nome:</L>
<L>Nyne dayes&middot; he was &thorn;iderward&middot; er he &thorn;ider come:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret honour he nom hem vp&middot;, &thorn;o he &thorn;e &yogh;erden fond:<MILESTONE N="29:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="120">&THORN;e swotnesse &thorn;at &thorn;er-of com&middot; fulde al &thorn;at lond:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; gret Melodye of his Harpe&middot; seint Dauid &thorn;e &yogh;erden nom,</L>
<L>And heom hom to Jerusalem&middot; &thorn;e Ni&thorn;e day hom he com;</L>
<L>In a priue stude he hem sette&middot;, &thorn;o hit was in &thorn;e Euen|ynge</L>
<L N="124">Forte a Morwe &thorn;at he se&yogh;e&middot; whodere he hem mi&yogh;te bringe;</L>
<L>A Morwe&middot; &thorn;o he com hem to&middot; to one &yogh;erde heo weren alle i-come,</L>
<L>And i-Mored also faste&middot; &thorn;at heo ne mihte ben a-wey i-nome;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o heo weoren alle&middot; to on by-come&middot; what bi-tokne&thorn; &thorn;is</L>
<L N="128">But Fader&middot; and Sone&middot; and Holigost&middot; and al o god hit is?</L>
<L>&para; Seint Dauid&middot; a-boute &thorn;is &yogh;erden&middot; a strong wal he lette arere,</L>
<L>And nom good &yogh;eme&middot; hou longe he woxe&middot;, from &yogh;ere&middot; to &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; a Cercle&middot; he bond hym a-boute&middot;, &yogh;er after &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at he mihte atte laste i-wite&middot; hou old &thorn;at treo were;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at wi&thorn;-Inne &thorn;ritti &yogh;er&middot; &thorn;is treo wex wel hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Ac hit wox no more afterward&middot;, and &thorn;at he wuste&middot; bi &thorn;e seluerne by&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Ac euere in on afterward&middot; Feir and Grene hit stod;</L>
<L N="136">Seint Dauid&middot; hit honourede wel&middot;, for he wuste &thorn;at hit was good:
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seint Dauid i-sunged hedde &thorn;e sunne of lecherie,</L>
<L>And Mon slauht &thorn;o&middot; for Bersabe&middot; he lette slen Vrie,</L>
<L>Vr lord nom &thorn;er-of wreche gret&middot;, swi&thorn;e sori he bi-com;</L>
<L N="140">Vndur &thorn;e treo&middot; his penaunce he dude&middot; &thorn;at he &thorn;er-fore nom;</L>
<L>&THORN;er he made &thorn;e Sauter&middot;, his sunnes forte bete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ra&thorn;ere hit him was for-&yogh;iue&middot; for &thorn;e holy treo so swete:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o bi-gon he eke&middot; for his sunne&middot; &thorn;e holy Temple to arere,</L>
<L N="144">Swi&thorn;e noble in Jerusalem&middot;, ac he dyede in &thorn;e fourtene&thorn;e &yogh;ere:</L>
<L>&para; His sone, &thorn;e kyng Salomon&middot;, &thorn;at after him&middot; kyng was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>After him&middot; &thorn;e Temple bulde for&thorn;&middot; &thorn;at heo folliche redi were:</L>
<L>&THORN;eraboute&middot; he was &thorn;ritti &yogh;er&middot;, and his fader fourtene also;</L>
<L N="148">So &thorn;at hit was&middot; foure and fourti &yogh;er&middot; er &thorn;at werk weore i-do:</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at werk&middot; was almest redi&middot; hem faylede a feir treo&middot;:</L>
<L>&THORN;at holy treo was &thorn;e feireste &thorn;o&middot;, &thorn;at me mihte owhere i-seo;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng Salomon hit let hewen&middot;, As qweynteliche as he mihte,</L>
<L N="152">And let hit nymen and make more&middot; bi a fote &thorn;en his rihte;</L>
<L>&THORN;o hit was brouht to rihte stude&middot; and i-laced scholde beo &thorn;er,</L>
<L>&THORN;o was hit&middot; bi a foote to schort&middot;, as euene as heo meeten er;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Carpunter hit leyde a-doun&middot; in strong wra&thorn;&thorn;e and grete,</L>
<L N="156">To no &thorn;ing &thorn;at he hit euere dude&middot; he ne mihte hit maken i-meetete:</L>
<L>&para; A brugge ouer an Old dich&middot; heo maden &thorn;er-of atte laste,</L>
<L>For wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at heo ne mihten&middot; to non o&thorn;ur werk hit caste:
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>&THORN;er ouer eode mony a Mon&middot;, &thorn;e while &thorn;at hit &thorn;er lay,</L>
<L N="160">A nusten not alle&middot; hou holy hit was&middot;, &thorn;at &thorn;er ouer eoden al day:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Qween of Saba&middot; com &thorn;er for&thorn;&middot;, ac anon &thorn;o heo hit seih,</L>
<L>Honourede hit feire&middot; and sat a-kneo&middot;, and nolde not come &thorn;er neih;</L>
<L>Bi a-no&thorn;ur wey heo wende&middot;, to kyng Salomon heo com,</L>
<L N="164">For heo hym hedde wel wyde i-souht&middot;, to leorne of him wisdom;</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh grace, &thorn;at vr lord hire &yogh;af&middot;, to kyng Salomon heo sede</L>
<L>&THORN;at treo ne scholde ligge &thorn;er&middot;, &yogh;if he dude by hire rede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er scholde a mon &yogh;it dye&middot; on &thorn;at ilke treo,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;orwh whom&middot; Al &thorn;e lawe of Gywes&middot; distruy&yogh;ed scholde beo:</L>
<L>&para; Salomon hit let nyme sone&middot; and vndur eor&thorn;e hit caste,</L>
<L>Wel deope and fer from alle men&middot;, and buriede hit wel faste;</L>
<L>So longe so hit &thorn;er-afterward was&middot; a wel feir welle sprong,</L>
<L N="172">A feyr watur wi&thorn; gret <NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>? god fisch.</I></NOTE>sich&middot;, bo&thorn;e deop and long;</L>
<L>Mony seke&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;er comen&middot; and wusch heore feet &thorn;er-on,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur heore honden&middot;, o&thorn;ur ba&thorn;eden al&middot;, heore hele hedden anon:</L>
<L>&THORN;at watur heo honoureden muche&middot; and wolden &thorn;er-Inne wade,</L>
<L N="176">Ac heo nusten no &thorn;ing of &thorn;e treo&middot; &thorn;at al &thorn;e vertu Made:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e longe &thorn;er-afturward&middot; &thorn;at vr lord on eor&thorn;e com,</L>
<L>Anon&middot; &thorn;o &thorn;at folk by-speek his de&thorn;&middot; and heore Red &thorn;erof nom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at treo bi-gon to fleoten a-non&middot;, as vr lordes wille was:</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;e Gywes comen&middot; and founden &thorn;at treo&middot; fleotynde &thorn;er bi cas,</L>
<L>Heo nomen hit vp&middot; and for hit was foul&middot; and i-leye hedde &thorn;er longe,</L>
<L>And maden &thorn;er-of &thorn;e holy Roode&middot;, vr lord &thorn;er-on to honge;
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>For &thorn;at treo&middot; was for-oldet&middot; and heo heolden vr lord lu&thorn;er also;</L>
<L N="184">&YOGH;it hem &thorn;hou&yogh;te&middot; &thorn;at treo to feir&middot; &thorn;at he weore &thorn;er-on i-do:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;At Crois se&thorn;&thorn;e&middot; aftur vr lordes de&thorn;&middot; depe vndur &thorn;e eor&thorn;e heo hit caste,</L>
<L>&THORN;er as heo him to de&thorn;e dude&middot; and burieden hit swi&thorn;e faste;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e twey Croyses eke &thorn;er-bi&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;eoues hengen on &thorn;er:</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;er heo ly&yogh;en&middot; er heo weore weoren i-founde&middot;, mo &thorn;en two hundred &yogh;er,</L>
<L>&para; Forte &thorn;at Tytes&middot; and Vaspa&yogh;ian&middot; wi&thorn; al heore folk come,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e Gywes hedden distruyed&middot; and heore pouwer by-nome&middot;,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at lond was i-brouht&middot; in-to &thorn;e Emperours hond of Rome,</L>
<L N="192">And mid his Men i-fuld&middot; and bi-set&middot; to nyme &thorn;er-of Goome:</L>
<L>&para; Ac se&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;er com an Emperour&middot;, &thorn;at hihte Adrian,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e he&thorn;ene&middot; and swi&thorn;e lu&thorn;er&middot;, and werrede vche cris|tene man;</L>
<L>He wuste wher &thorn;e Rode lay&middot; &thorn;at God was onne i-do</L>
<L N="196">And cristene men &thorn;e stude honoureden&middot; whon heo mihten come &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>He lette a temple of Maumetes&middot; in &thorn;ulke stude arere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me mihte not fynde&middot; to loute to&middot; bote Maumetes &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Whon Cristene Men&middot; mihten &thorn;ider stele&middot;, heo durste nout for doute,<MILESTONE N="29b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="200">An eke a-&yogh;eyn herte hit was&middot; to eny Maumete&middot; a loute,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo bi-leueden &thorn;ulke stude&middot;, and also for fere</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn;-Inne a fewe &yogh;er &thorn;er-after&middot; no cristene mon com &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ulke stude was&middot; for let mony a day,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at no cristene mon ne Painym&middot; nuste where &thorn;e Rode lay:
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seo&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;er com an Emperour&middot; &thorn;at het Constantyn;</L>
<L>In werre and batayle he was so muche&middot;, &thorn;at &thorn;er nas no fyn;</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e comen his fon and wonnen&middot; muchedel of his londe;</L>
<L N="208">He &yogh;arkede a day his Ost&middot; a-&yogh;eyn heom forte stonde;</L>
<L>&para; As he touward &thorn;e Batayle wende&middot; he bi-heold vp an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;hou&yogh;te &thorn;at a feir Crois&middot; In heuene &thorn;at he sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Lettres he say&yogh; &thorn;er-on i-write&middot;, he hem bi-gon to Rede&middot;:</L>
<L N="212">"Wi&thorn; &thorn;is signe &thorn;ow schalt Mayster beo&middot;," &thorn;ulke lettres sede,</L>
<L>"And wite &thorn;e from &thorn;y fon&middot;, by daye&middot; and eke by nihte,</L>
<L>Whon &thorn;ow &thorn;enkest &thorn;er-vppon&middot;, spede &thorn;ou schalt in fihte":</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Emperour &thorn;is vndurstood&middot;, &thorn;eih he He&thorn;ene were,</L>
<L N="216">A&middot; Crois he lette make sone&middot; &thorn;at his Men by-foren him bere,</L>
<L>In-stude of his Baner&middot;, In Batayle a-non,</L>
<L>And &thorn;orwh &thorn;e holy Crois&middot; he ouercom alle his fon</L>
<L>And won &thorn;e Maystrie&middot;, and al his lond&middot; in a luytel stounde &thorn;ere:</L>
<L N="220">Muche he &thorn;ouhte &thorn;er-afterward&middot; what &thorn;ulke signe were;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wiseste Men of al his lond&middot; bi-fore him he lette bringe,</L>
<L>And enquerede of &thorn;e Crois&middot; what weore &thorn;e tokenynge:</L>
<L>Heo seiden him&middot; &thorn;at in Ierusalem&middot; God was don on &thorn;e Roode,</L>
<L N="224">And &thorn;e Gywes &thorn;at Crois hudden &thorn;ere&middot;, as heo hit vndur|stode:</L>
<L>"Whon ichabbe," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Emperour, "&thorn;er &thorn;orwh&middot; my fon i-brouht to grounde,</L>
<L>Ne wor&thorn; ich neuere glad of herte&middot;, er &thorn;e holy Cr[o]is beo i-founde":</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Emperour&middot; of &thorn;e holy Roode&middot; so feir Miracle i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="228">He let him Bapti&yogh;en of seint Siluestre&middot;, &thorn;e Pope &thorn;at &thorn;o was neih:
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E holy Rode&middot; I-founde was&middot;, as ich ow wolle now telle:</L>
<L>Constantin &thorn;e Emperour&middot; he&thorn;ene folk gon faste quelle,</L>
<L>For heo vr lord Ihesu crist&middot; to strong de&thorn; brouhte;</L>
<L N="232">Alle &thorn;e he&thorn;ene Men &thorn;at neih him were&middot; sone he brouhte to nouhte:</L>
<L>Eleyne &thorn;at his Modur was&middot; to Ierusalem heo sende</L>
<L>To sechen aftur &thorn;e holy Rode&middot;, And heo gladliche for&thorn; wende;</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo com &thorn;idere&middot; heo lette crie&middot;, as heo red hedde i-nome,</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at alle Gywes of &thorn;e Cit&eacute;&eacute;&middot; to-fore hire scholde come:</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Gywes i-somened were&middot; heo hedden ful gret fere;</L>
<L>Gret counseil &thorn;ei nomen &thorn;er-of&middot; what &thorn;e enchesun were;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide on&middot; &thorn;at hette Iudas&middot;, "Ich wene &thorn;at ich wot</L>
<L N="240">What &thorn;is Somouns amounti schal&middot;, &yogh;if ich telle mot:</L>
<L>Ich wene&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e Qweene enquere wole&middot;, as heo ha&thorn; i-&thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e Roode &thorn;at Ihesu crist&middot; to de&thorn;e was onne i|brouht;</L>
<L>&THORN;at non of ow&middot; ne beo so wod&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;er-of i-knowe be,</L>
<L N="244">In Counseil ich ow telle wole &thorn;at my fader tolde me:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o my Fader Symeon&middot; in his de&thorn; vuel lay,</L>
<L>In Counseil he was to me i-knowe&middot; &thorn;o he on him &thorn;e de&thorn; i-say;</L>
<L>"Iudas," he seide, "leoue sone&middot;, &yogh;if hit bi-tyde&thorn; so</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at me enquere&thorn; after &thorn;e Rode&middot; &thorn;at Ihesus was on i-do,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo a-knowe &thorn;er-of&middot; er &thorn;at me &thorn;e quelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Zach&eacute;&eacute; my Fader tolde me&middot; in Counseil ich wol &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>He seide me a luytel bi-fore his de&thorn;&middot; &thorn;at he was atte dede</L>
<L N="252">To burien hire&middot; vppe Caluarie Hul&middot;, as heo nomen alle to rede":</L>
<L>&para; "Leoue Fader," i seide, "&thorn;o&middot; what eylede ow Allas</L>
<L>Whi wolde &yogh;e hym to de&thorn;e do&middot;, whonne &thorn;at he good was":</L>
<L>&para; He seide&middot; "bi me nas hit nout&middot; ac for &thorn;at he wi&thorn;-sede
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="41"></L>
<L N="256">Mine felawes of vre lawe&middot; &thorn;erfore heo him brouhte to dede;</L>
<L>Seo&thorn;&thorn;e heo him in &thorn;e Sepulcre dude&middot;, ac he a-ros to lyue</L>
<L>Fro de&thorn;e&middot; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day&middot; mid his woundes fyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;enne &thorn;e fourti&thorn;e day &thorn;er-afterward&middot; to heuene he wende an heih,</L>
<L N="260">In &thorn;e lond of Galil&eacute;&eacute;&middot; &thorn;at al &thorn;at folk i-seih:</L>
<L>Twelf Mone&thorn; hit was&middot; &thorn;er-afterward&middot;, and half a &yogh;er&middot; and more,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Steuene&middot; &thorn;at my bro&thorn;er was&middot; preche gon of his lore;</L>
<L>Oure Gywes&middot; him hedde wi&thorn;-oute &thorn;e toun&middot; and stenede him wi&thorn; stones,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;erwi&thorn; to de&thorn;e heo him brouhte&middot; and to brusede his bones:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Morwe after Mid-wynter-day&middot; to de&thorn;e heo him brouhte,</L>
<L>And nou he is in &thorn;e Ioye of heuene&middot; and he hire a|bouhte":</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o Iudas hedde his tale i-told&middot; &thorn;e Gywes seiden, as heo stode,</L>
<L N="268">"We ne herde telle neuer er&middot; &thorn;us muche of &thorn;e Roode":</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at &thorn;e tyme was&middot; bi-fore &thorn;e Qweene heo come,</L>
<L>"Cheose&thorn; seide &thorn;e Qweene &thorn;o&middot; of &thorn;eose tweye dome;</L>
<L>Lyf&middot; and De&thorn;&middot; is ow bi-fore&middot;, chese&thorn; whe&thorn;er &yogh;e wollen,</L>
<L N="272">But &yogh;e&middot; &thorn;e Holy Roode me bringe&middot; Brenne vchone &yogh;e schullen":</L>
<L>Gret Fuir heo lette make&middot; bi-fore heore alre ei&yogh;en;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Gywes bi-gonne to crie loude&middot; &thorn;o heo &thorn;e fuir i-sei&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And seiden&middot; "&yogh;if &thorn;er-of eny wot&middot; &thorn;enne wot Iudas,</L>
<L N="276">For Zachee&middot; his Fader&middot; fader; of gret pouwer was,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke tyme &thorn;at Ihesuc was&middot; on &thorn;e Roode i-do":</L>
<L>&THORN;e Qweene&middot; &thorn;o lette nyme Iudas&middot; and &thorn;e o&thorn;ere heo lette go,</L>
<L>And bad him ben A-knowe&middot;, and &thorn;o he nolde for no|&thorn;inge<MILESTONE N="29b:2" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="43"></L>
<L N="280">&THORN;e Qweene him lette &thorn;o faste bynde&middot; and in-to strong prison bringe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn;-oute mete&middot; and drinke&middot; &thorn;er seue dayes he lay;</L>
<L>For strong hunger loude he criede&middot; &thorn;ene seue&thorn;e day,</L>
<L>And seide&middot; "bringe&thorn; me of &thorn;is wo&middot; and ich ow wole telle and lede</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;er-as ich wene&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e Roode beo&middot;, as my fader me sede":</L>
<L>&THORN;o he out of prisun com&middot; mid muche folk he wende</L>
<L>To &thorn;e place &thorn;er &thorn;e Roode was&middot;, as his fader him kende;</L>
<L>&THORN;o he to &thorn;e place com&middot; A-doun he sat on kneo,</L>
<L N="288">Lord he seide&middot;, "&yogh;if hit is so&thorn;&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ow&middot; God and Mon beo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at&middot; &thorn;ow of Marie weore i-boren&middot; send vs nou &thorn;i grace</L>
<L>Sum toknynge&middot; &thorn;at we fynde mowe&middot; &thorn;e Roode in &thorn;is place":</L>
<L>&para; Anon&middot; &thorn;o Iudas &thorn;is bone hedde&middot; to vr lord i-bede,</L>
<L N="292">&THORN;e Hul bi-gon to qwake&middot; and out of one stede;</L>
<L>A&middot; smoke sprong out&middot; and wende an hei&yogh;&middot;, and muche place fulde,</L>
<L>Swettore &thorn;ing nas neuer non&middot; &thorn;en &thorn;e smoke smulde;</L>
<L>&THORN;o Iudas &thorn;is i-sayh&middot; loude he bi-gon to crye,</L>
<L N="296">"Ihesus is one Almihti God&middot;, i-bore of Mayde Marie;</L>
<L>Wood is&middot; &thorn;at eni o&thorn;ur by-leeue&thorn;&middot; as i-chabbe mony a day,</L>
<L>Taken i-chulle to Cristendom&middot; ich forsake Gywene lay":</L>
<L>He let him cristene hastiliche&middot; and &thorn;o he i-cristened was,</L>
<L N="300">He let him nempnen Quiriak&middot; &thorn;at er&middot; he hette Iudas":</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o nomen heo spade and<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>sand.</I></NOTE> schouele&middot; and ner &thorn;e place wende,</L>
<L>Deope heo gonne to delue&middot; &thorn;er as &thorn;e smoke out wende;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo founden Roodes &thorn;reo&middot; &thorn;o heo hedden i-doluen longe,</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;e Roode &thorn;at God was on i-do&middot; and &thorn;at &thorn;e twey &thorn;eues were on an honge</L>
<L>Bi-syden vr lord&middot; him to schende&middot;, ac he nuste whuch of &thorn;e &thorn;reo
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>&THORN;e holy Crois &thorn;at heo souhten&middot; whuch of &thorn;e &thorn;reo hit mihte beo;</L>
<L>Ac no&thorn;eles heo nomen alle &thorn;reo&middot; and toward toune hem bere</L>
<L N="308">To Eleyne &thorn;e goode Qweene&middot; wi&thorn; wel glade chere;</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;at hit was hei&yogh; non&middot; me gon a&yogh;eyn hem bringe</L>
<L>A ded Monnes bodi&middot; vppon A bere&middot; to-ward buryinge;</L>
<L>Quiriak nom &thorn;is o Rode&middot; and eft-sone &thorn;e o&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="312">And leyde vppe &thorn;is dede Mon&middot;, ac he ne a-ros for nou&thorn;er;</L>
<L>He leyde &thorn;e &thorn;ridde him vppon&middot; and he a-ros wel blyue,</L>
<L>And bi-gon to &thorn;onke Godes sone&middot; &thorn;at him brouhte to lyue:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o com &thorn;e deuel &yogh;ellynde for&thorn;&middot; loude he gon crie and grede,</L>
<L N="316">"Allas nou is my power a-go&middot;," her-after more he sede;</L>
<L>"Ihesus Ihesus&middot; what &thorn;enkestou&middot;, Alle folk to &thorn;e lede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast here in Monnes warde&middot; &thorn;ing &thorn;at ich mest drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw whom&middot; ich furst was ouercome&middot; and nou I&middot; am al to grounde;</L>
<L N="320">Allas &thorn;ulke sori while&middot; &thorn;at heo was euere i-founde,</L>
<L>For ich nabbe nou&middot; power so gret&middot; on eor&thorn;e a-mong Menne;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me fourme&thorn; enes &thorn;e Crois&middot; anon ich mot go &thorn;eonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore ich wot &thorn;at eueri mon&middot; wol nou &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-se,</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;at &thorn;e Crois me ha&thorn; ouercome&middot; and al my power bi-nome me;</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;at ich &thorn;is tyme i-sayh&middot; nou ich wor&thorn; al forsake!</L>
<L>Iudas Iudas&middot; what was &thorn;e&middot; whi woldestou &thorn;us on take,</L>
<L>&THORN;orwh on Iudas &thorn;at was i-hote&middot; Ihesuc to de&thorn;e was i-brouht,</L>
<L N="328">And &thorn;orw a Iudas ich am ouercome&middot; and i-brouht to nouht;</L>
<L>Streng&thorn;e ne wor&thorn; me neuer non&middot; bote eny mon wole mid wille</L>
<L>Seruen me to payen his flesch&middot; his soule forte spille;
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>Whon my streng&thorn;e is neih by-nome&middot; fonde ich mot wi&thorn; ginne</L>
<L N="332">And mid tresun &yogh;if ich may&middot; eny Men to me winne;</L>
<L>I&middot; may here no lengore bi-leue&middot; for &thorn;is me &thorn;inke&thorn; longe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Crois &thorn;at is me bi-fore&middot; in peyne ich am wel stronge":</L>
<L>&para; Iudas seide&middot;, "go henne a-non&middot; ne cum &thorn;ou here no more,</L>
<L N="336">I-founden is &thorn;eih hit late beo&middot; &thorn;at ouercomen ha&thorn; al &thorn;i lore;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at her is&middot; &thorn;e dede mon&middot; fro de&thorn; i-brouht to lyue</L>
<L>Pult te wi&thorn; &thorn;i pouwer al&middot; in-to helle wel blyue":</L>
<L>Muche was &thorn;e Ioye of &thorn;e Crois&middot; &thorn;at me &thorn;o made &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="340">Wi&thorn; gret song&middot; and processioun&middot; &thorn;e Qweene heo hire bere;</L>
<L>&para; Iudas nom cristendom&middot; and &thorn;o he i-cristened was</L>
<L>He let him nempne Quiriac&middot; &thorn;at er heihte Iudas:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Qweene of Seluer and of Gold&middot; A gret Schrine heo wrouhte,</L>
<L N="344">And of &yogh;ymmes preciouse&middot; and &thorn;e Roode &thorn;er-Inne brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Vppe &thorn;e hul of Caluarie&middot; &thorn;er heo &thorn;e Roode founde;</L>
<L>A Feir Churche heo lette a-rere&middot; i-heried beo &thorn;ulke stounde!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e Qweene&middot; desirede muchel&middot; aftur &thorn;e nayles &thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="348">Wherwith vr lord was&middot; I-nayled to &thorn;e treo;</L>
<L>Quyriac&middot; &thorn;at er hihte Iudas&middot; wende to &thorn;e place,</L>
<L>&THORN;er as &thorn;e Crois i-founde was&middot;, and bad vr lord of grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at God, &yogh;if his wille were&middot;, &thorn;e &thorn;reo Nayles him sende;</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;e Nayles&middot; wi&thorn; lihtynge gret&middot; vp of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e wende;</L>
<L>Quiriac &thorn;onkede Ihesu crist&middot; wi&thorn; gret Ioye he hem nom,</L>
<L>And tok hem Eleyne &thorn;e goode Qweene&middot; &thorn;o he to hire com;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;us was &thorn;e holy Roode i-founde&middot; &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day of May</L>
<L N="356">&THORN;at we clepe&thorn; in holichirche&middot; &thorn;e Holy Roode day;</L>
<L>Quiriac&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e holi Roode fond&middot; Bisschop se&thorn;&thorn;e he was,</L>
<L>In heuene he is nou seint Quiriac&middot; &thorn;at furst hette Iudas;
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>By-seche we &thorn;e holy Roode&middot; &thorn;at brouhte &thorn;e deuel to grounde,<MILESTONE N="30:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="360">And seint Quiriac&middot; and seint Eleyne&middot;, &thorn;orwh whom heo was i-founde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo bi-sechen God for vs&middot;, &thorn;at on &thorn;e Roode schedde his blood,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we mote to &thorn;e ioye of heuene come&middot; &thorn;at is so swete and god. Amen&middot;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E holi Roode was i-founde&middot; as &yogh;e wite&thorn; in May,</L>
<L N="364">Honoured he was se&thorn;&thorn;e&middot; in Septembre&middot; &thorn;e holi Rode day;</L>
<L>Mony a &yogh;er &thorn;er was by-twene&middot;, ri&yogh;t is &thorn;at we telle,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;is feste was by-gonne&middot; for-so&thorn;e ly&yogh;en i nulle:</L>
<L>A kyng &thorn;er was on eor&thorn;e &thorn;o&middot;, Cosdre was his nome,</L>
<L N="368">Cristene Men &thorn;at he mihte fynde&middot; he brou&yogh;t hem alle to schome;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; his lu&thorn;er power he won also&middot; al &thorn;e londes &thorn;er-aboute,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he com to Ierusalem&middot; of &thorn;e sepulcre he hedde doute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vr lord was Inne i-leyd&middot; a-non so he &thorn;is i-seih,</L>
<L N="372">For al his power &thorn;at was so lu&thorn;er&middot; &yogh;it ne dorst he come &thorn;er neih,</L>
<L>Ac a partye of &thorn;e swete Crois&middot; &thorn;at seint Eleyne &thorn;ider brouhte</L>
<L>He tok wi&thorn; him&middot; and wende a-&yogh;ein&middot; no more &thorn;idere he ne &thorn;ouhte;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke treo&middot; he was wel proud&middot;, &thorn;eih he him-self he&thorn;ene were,</L>
<L N="376">A&middot; swi&thorn;e hei&yogh; tour of Gold and Seluer&middot; he let him sone a-rere,</L>
<L>Of &yogh;immes&middot; and of stones precious&middot; &thorn;er-aboute he lette do;</L>
<L>Fourme of Sonne&middot; and of Mone&middot; and of Sterres also</L>
<L>Schinen&middot;, as hit hem-self were&middot;, and tornen a-boute faste,</L>
<L N="380">And &thorn;undringe he made ek&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;e folk ofte a-gaste,</L>
<L>Mid smale holes &thorn;orwh queyntyse&middot; &thorn;at watur ofte &thorn;ere</L>
<L>He made hit ofte to grounde falle&middot; as &thorn;ei&yogh; hit Reyn were,</L>
<L>As ferfor&thorn; as cou&thorn;e eny mon&middot; make mid queyntyse,
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="51"></L>
<L N="384">&THORN;e fourme as hit heuene were&middot; he made on alle wyse;</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>A-nouwarde his Tour&middot; amidde al &thorn;is&middot; his sege he lette a-rere,</L>
<L N="388">In his Riht half he made a sege&middot; his o sone he sette &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>To sitten onne him-self&middot; as a God&middot; in heuene&middot; as &thorn;eih hit were:</L>
<L>In-stude as &thorn;eih hit were godes sone&middot; &thorn;at no de-faute nere;</L>
<L>In his Luft half&middot; he made a-no&thorn;ur&middot; and feir he lette fette</L>
<L N="392">In-stude of &thorn;e holi-gost&middot;, bi his Luft half&middot; he him sette,</L>
<L>And sat him-self a-midde&middot; &thorn;e Fader as &thorn;eih hit were;</L>
<L>And sone&middot; and Holi-gost&middot; bi-side&middot; gret pruyde was &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ERaclius &thorn;e Emperour&middot; &thorn;at cristene was of Rome,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is mis farinde pruyde&middot; he herde tellen ofte and i-lome;</L>
<L>In-to his lond&middot; he wende wi&thorn; his Ost&middot; and werrede wi&thorn; him wel faste;</L>
<L N="400">In his heuene he sat as a God&middot;, as &thorn;eih him no-&thorn;ing ne a-gaste,</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>Him ne deynede not ones for him&middot; of his heuene a-lihte,</L>
<L N="404">No more &thorn;en hit weore a God&middot; wi&thorn; er&thorn;liche mon to fihte;</L>
<L>His sone&middot; a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e Emperour&middot; mid his Ost he sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he to &thorn;e Batayle come&middot; er ei&thorn;er to o&thorn;er wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo bi-twene hem-selue two&middot; &thorn;e Batayle scholde do,</L>
<L N="408">And al heore Ost&middot; stonde and bi-holden&middot; and no mon come &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And whe&thorn;er of hem so a-boue were&middot; habbe scholde &thorn;e mihte</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e o&thorn;eres Men&middot; and his lond&middot; after his wille dihte;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e forward was ymad&middot; to-gedere heo smite to grounde,
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="53"></L>
<L N="412">And fou&yogh;ten as heore ri&yogh;te was&middot; and maden harde wounde,</L>
<L>Ac atte laste&middot; &thorn;e Emperour&middot; &thorn;e o&thorn;ur ouer-com</L>
<L>And al his folk&middot;, as forward was&middot;, in his baundun nom,</L>
<L>&para; He lette cristen euerichone&middot; and suwen him to his wille;</L>
<L N="416">&THORN;is lu&thorn;er kyng sat euere a-tom&middot; In his heuene wel stille,</L>
<L>As A God&middot; and nuste not&middot; &thorn;at he was bi-ne&thorn;e i-brouht,</L>
<L>And so vuel he was bi-loued of his men&middot; &thorn;at heo nolden him telle nouht;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Emperour him wende for&thorn;&middot; in-to his heuene an heih,</L>
<L N="420">He fond him sitte &thorn;ere as a god&middot; his sone him sat wel neih;</L>
<L>"Heil," he seide&middot;, "sire false god&middot; in &thorn;is false heuene i-founde,</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;y sone&middot; and mid &thorn;in hori-gost&middot;<NOTE PLACE="marg">(<I>sic</I>) hori gost&mdash;a dirty ghost? (intended as a pun.)</NOTE> &yogh;e be&thorn; neih a|swounde;</L>
<L>Bi him &thorn;at &thorn;ou makest &thorn;e aftur&middot; &thorn;at for vs &thorn;olede wounde,</L>
<L N="424">But &thorn;ou wolle on him bi-leeue&middot; &thorn;ou schalt here in a stounde</L>
<L>Of myn hond &thorn;ole de&thorn;&middot; and &thorn;i pruyde ben i-brouht to grounde;</L>
<L>For al &thorn;in heuene y nul bi-leue&middot; ne for Mark&middot; ne for pounde":</L>
<L>&para; "Nay Certes," qu[o]d &thorn;is o&thorn;er&middot;, "&thorn;ou ne schalt me not so lere,</L>
<L N="428">&THORN;at ich to eny mon schule a-bouwe&middot; bote he herre &thorn;en ich were":</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Emperour drou&yogh; out his swerd&middot; and smot of his hed riht &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>His &yogh;ongeste sone&middot; &thorn;at bi him sat&middot; &thorn;at was in his ten&thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>He let him cristene and make kyng&middot; of al his fader lond;</L>
<L N="432">His Men he &yogh;af al &thorn;at seluer&middot; &thorn;at he &thorn;ere fond,</L>
<L>&para; Mid &thorn;e Gold and riche &thorn;inges&middot; &thorn;at he fond &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e chirches &thorn;at &thorn;e schrewe destruyde&middot; he lette &thorn;er-wi&thorn; vp a-rere,</L>
<L>And made al &thorn;at lond in god bi-leeue&middot; &thorn;ere in Godes lawe;</L>
<L N="436">Alle &thorn;at nolde turne to God&middot; he brou&yogh;t hem sone of dawe:
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>&THORN;e holy Crois &thorn;at he fond &thorn;ere&middot; &thorn;at vr lord was onne i-do,</L>
<L>A-doun he nom wi&thorn; gret honour&middot; and ladde wi&thorn; him also</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Borwh of Ierusalem&middot;, and &thorn;o he com &thorn;er bi-syde</L>
<L N="440">Vppe &thorn;e Hul of Olyuete&middot; a stounde he gon a-byde;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e folk a-boute him com&middot; mid gret honour wi&thorn;-alle</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkeden God&middot; of &thorn;at cas&middot; &thorn;at hem was bi-falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e swete holi Crois&middot; a-&yogh;ein moste come,</L>
<L N="444">&THORN;at &thorn;e lu&thorn;ur kyng Cosdre&middot; hem hedde er bi-nome;</L>
<L>&para; A-doun of &thorn;e hul wende &thorn;e Emperour&middot; mid feir procession</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke wey &thorn;at vr lord wende&middot; to-ward his passion;</L>
<L>&THORN;o he com to &thorn;e borwh&middot; and wolde in atte &yogh;ate</L>
<L N="448">A feir Miracle vr lord sende&middot; &thorn;at he ne mihte in &thorn;er-ate;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e stones &thorn;at a-boute were&middot; a-doun a-non a-lihte</L>
<L>And stooden euene a-boute bi &thorn;e o&thorn;ur wal&middot; &thorn;at no mon in ne mihte;</L>
<L>Sori was &thorn;e Emperour&middot; and al his folk also</L>
<L N="452">And dredden &thorn;at heo not wor&thorn;i weoren&middot; a such holy &thorn;ing to do;</L>
<L>&THORN;er was wepynge and cri i-nouh on god&middot; &thorn;at he hem sende</L>
<L>Sum grace&middot;, &yogh;if his wille were&middot;, &thorn;at heo to &thorn;e Borwh wende;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o stod &thorn;er-bi an Aungel&middot; a Crois hee heold an honde:</L>
<L N="456">"Sir Emperour," he seide&middot;, "&thorn;ulke tyme&middot; &thorn;at vr lord was here a-londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he com in atte &yogh;ate&middot; to de&thorn;e to ben i-do,</L>
<L>Vppon a sely Asse he Rod&middot; in feble clo&thorn;us also,</L>
<L>He com wi&thorn; no gret nobleye&middot; so as &thorn;ou dest now,</L>
<L N="460">Wi&thorn; riche clo&thorn;us&middot; ne wi&thorn; o&thorn;er pruyde&middot;, &thorn;eih he were as heih as &thorn;ou":</L>
<L>&para; Mid &thorn;is word he wende a-&yogh;eyn&middot; &thorn;e Emperour a-non</L>
<L>A-lihte a-doun&middot; and his clo&thorn;us&middot; of caste euerichon,</L>
<L>Anon to his schurte&middot; and his Brech&middot; sore weopinde wi&thorn;|alle;</L>
<L N="464">&THORN;is stones risen vp a&yogh;eyn&middot; &thorn;at weren er doun i-falle,</L>
<L>And lay&middot; vche in his rihte stude&middot; as heo hedden er i-do,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;at opene as hit was er&middot; and &thorn;e wey clene also;
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperour nom &thorn;is swete Rode&middot; and al a fote him beer;</L>
<L N="468">&THORN;at folk suwede him wi&thorn; gret pres&middot; gret Ioye and blisse was &thorn;er,</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;er com so swete a smul&middot; as &thorn;ei hit from heuene were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al hit smulde wi&thorn; gret Ioye&middot; &thorn;at in &thorn;e cuntre weren &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Emperour bar &thorn;is swete crois&middot; in-to &thorn;e temple an heih,</L>
<L N="472">He gon singe &thorn;is newe song&middot; bi-foren alle &thorn;at weore &thorn;er neih:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;E Crois bri&yogh;tore to &thorn;is world&middot; &thorn;en Alle &thorn;e sterres beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art to honoure of alle men&middot; and muche to loue of alle treo;</L>
<L>Holiore &thorn;ou art &thorn;en al &thorn;at is&middot; for &thorn;ou one wor&thorn;iore were,</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e tresor of al &thorn;is world&middot; al one vppe &thorn;e bere;</L>
<L>&THORN;ow swete treo&middot; &thorn;at bere on &thorn;e&middot; &thorn;e swete Nayles also,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swete bur&thorn;ene&middot; of Godus sone&middot; &thorn;at on &thorn;e was i-do,</L>
<L>Saue nou al &thorn;is cumpanye&middot; &thorn;at i-gederet her is,</L>
<L N="480">And here to-day to-gedere i-brouht&middot; in &thorn;in heryinge i|wis":</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is song soong &thorn;e Emperour&middot; &thorn;at wel is vnderstonde,</L>
<L>For &yogh;it me hit singe&thorn; in holichirche&middot; whon me bere&thorn; &thorn;at crois an honde;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at folk honurede ek&middot; &thorn;at Crois&middot; so feire so heo mihten do,</L>
<L N="484">Wi&thorn; offringes&middot; and wi&thorn; song&middot; and wi&thorn; o&thorn;ure melodyes also;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is was &thorn;e holi Rode day&middot; &thorn;at in Septembre is</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore me honoure&thorn; in holichirche&middot; &thorn;ulke day &yogh;it i-wis:
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="59"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint Quiriac &thorn;e Bisschop&middot; prechede Godus lawe:</L>
<L N="488">Iulian &thorn;e lu&thorn;ur Emperour&middot; brouht him se&thorn;&thorn;e of dawe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e holi Roode&middot; &thorn;at he fond&middot;, and for he men &thorn;er-to drouh</L>
<L>To bi-leeue on Ihesu crist&middot; for al he heold hit wouh;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Emperour hedde seint Quiriac&middot; bi-fore him i-brouht</L>
<L N="492">He bad him leeuen in heor Maumetes&middot;, and &thorn;o he nolde nouht,</L>
<L>His riht hond he let furst of smyte&middot; And al i-do he seide &thorn;is:&mdash;</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou hast wel ofte&middot; &thorn;er-wi&thorn; i-write&middot; a&yogh;ein vr lawe i wis":</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ou gidi hound&middot;" seide &thorn;is gode Mon&middot;, "wel hastou i-do by me,</L>
<L N="496">Of my good &thorn;ou weore wel vnderstonde&middot; wel ou&yogh;t i blesse &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou hast bi-nome me &thorn;ulke lime&middot; &thorn;at ha&thorn; me ofte to sunne i-drawe,</L>
<L>For ich habbe &thorn;er-wi&thorn; ofte i-write&middot; a-&yogh;eyn Ihesu cristes lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e while &thorn;at ich was Gyew&middot; and on him bi-leeuede nouht:"</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;o &thorn;e Emperour sai&yogh; &thorn;at he nolde&middot; nout tornen his &thorn;ouht</L>
<L>He &yogh;af him drinken welled led&middot; and in his mou&thorn; helde &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Euere sat &thorn;is gode mon&middot; as &thorn;eih him no&thorn;ing nere;</L>
<L>Vp A Gledeire he leide him se&thorn;&thorn;e&middot; ouer a gret fuir and strong,</L>
<L N="504">To Rosten as me de&thorn; versch flesch&middot; grees was &thorn;er Among,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at fuir was&middot; al of Col&middot; and grece&middot; and &thorn;at salt was eke &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And of flesch &thorn;at was eke for brend&middot; &thorn;e woundes he salte also,</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo ne mihte torne &thorn;er-wi&thorn; his &thorn;ouht&middot; ne to de&thorn; him bringe,</L>
<L N="508">Heo bi-&thorn;ouhten hem&middot; &yogh;if heo mihte&middot; wi&thorn; eny o&thorn;er &thorn;inge;</L>
<L>&para; "Quiriac" he seide&middot; "&thorn;enk on &thorn;i-self&middot; and do aftur my lore,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou nult not&middot; vr godes honoure&middot; bote &thorn;ow wolle more,
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>Sey &thorn;at &thorn;ou nart&middot; cristene nout&middot; and ich wolle de-boner beo,</L>
<L N="512">And murie lyf &thorn;ou schalt lede &thorn;er-afterward&middot;, and &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt i-seo":</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e gode mon nolde don after him&middot;, a Caudrun he lette fulle</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Oyle&middot; and let hit se&thorn;en faste&middot; and let him &thorn;er-Inne pulle;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-Inne he se&thorn; &thorn;e gode Mon&middot; forte &thorn;at he weri was:</L>
<L N="516">&THORN;e gode Mon heriede vr lord euere and neuer &thorn;e worse him nas;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Emperour i-sau&yogh;&middot; &thorn;at he ne mihte him so ouer|come,</L>
<L>With a swerd he smot him &thorn;orwh &thorn;e herte&middot; &thorn;o he was of &thorn;e Ba&thorn;e inome;</L>
<L>His soule wente to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene&middot; aftur his tor|mentynge,</L>
<L N="520">Crist for &thorn;e loue of Seint Quiriac&middot; to &thorn;ulke Ioye vs bringe A. M. E. N.!</L>
</LG>


</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000094.tif" N="62">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>THE STORY OF THE HOLY ROOD<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harlein MS. 4196.<MILESTONE N="76b:1" UNIT="folio">.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De morte primi parentis Ade et de incepcione crucis Christi.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When adam oure form fader dere</L>
<L>Was of elde nyghen hundreth &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto [thritt]y<NOTE PLACE="marg">nearly effaced,</NOTE>, &thorn;an he kend</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at his life drogh nere &thorn;e end;</L>
<L>&THORN;an said he vntill eue, "&thorn;ou sall</L>
<L>All my suns bifor me call,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I may blis &thorn;am or I dy."</L>
<L N="8">And als he bad scho did in hy;</L>
<L>Scho cald [&thorn;am] vnto him &thorn;at tide,<MILESTONE N="76b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai come and stode all him biside,</L>
<L>Als he in his sekenes lay,</L>
<L N="12">And vnto him &thorn;us gan &thorn;ai say:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Fader, what harm es &thorn;e on hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou es in &thorn;i bed ligand,</L>
<L>And wharto hastou cald vs heder?"</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;an said he to &thorn;am al to-geder:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Suns," he said, "I far ful ill,</L>
<L>Of pine and sorow I find my fill."</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai answerd and said ogaine:&mdash;</L>
<L N="20">"Fader tell vs what es payne,</L>
<L>And how it es sorow to haue,</L>
<L>Say vs &thorn;e suth, so god &thorn;e saue;</L>
<L>For whils we in &thorn;is werld haue bene,</L>
<L N="24">Of sekenes haue we seldom sene."</L>
<L>&THORN;an said seth, "for suth I trow,</L>
<L>Fader, &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;ernes now</L>
<L>Of paradis fruit forto ett mare,</L>
<L N="28">Of &thorn;e whilk &thorn;ou has etin are;
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor ligges &thorn;ou sorowand swa,</L>
<L>Bot say to me and I sall ga</L>
<L>Sone vnto paradis &yogh;ate,</L>
<L N="32">And I sall grete &thorn;are in &thorn;e gate;</L>
<L>I sall mak site and sorows sere,</L>
<L>And so I hope god sall me here,</L>
<L>And send sum angell me to gete</L>
<L N="36">Sum of &thorn;at fruit &thorn;at &thorn;ou wald ett."</L>
<L>Adam vnto seth &thorn;an telles:&mdash;</L>
<L>"I &yogh;erne no fruit, ne no thing els,</L>
<L>Bot I haue dole with-owten dout,</L>
<L N="40">And euil in al my lims obout."</L>
<L>&THORN;an said seth and &thorn;ai all bidene,</L>
<L>"We wate neuer what euil es to mene;</L>
<L>Tell vs what thing &thorn;e greue &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="44">Wharto suld &thorn;ou laine fra vs?"</L>
<L>Als he lay &thorn;an &thorn;us said he:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Al my suns herkins to me!</L>
<L>When god had made me with his will</L>
<L N="48">&YOGH;owre moder &thorn;an he made me till;</L>
<L>In paradis sone he vs sett,</L>
<L>And gaf vs leue al fruit to ett;</L>
<L>He outtoke no thing bot a tre</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at he forbed bath hir and me;</L>
<L>In middes of paradis it stode,</L>
<L>And was knawing of ill and gude;</L>
<L>&THORN;e est he put in my powst&eacute;</L>
<L N="56">And &thorn;e north at my will to be,</L>
<L>And till &yogh;owre moder he toke &thorn;at tide<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bath &thorn;e west and &thorn;e sowth syde;</L>
<L>And twa angels he toke vs till,</L>
<L N="60">Vs forto were fra alkins ill;</L>
<L>Till on a tyme, sons, suth to say,</L>
<L>Oure angels went fra vs oway,</L>
<L>Bifor god &thorn;aire wirschip to ma;</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;an [com] &thorn;e fende &thorn;at es oure fa,
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>And in &yogh;owre moder fand he stede,</L>
<L>And did hir do efter his rede;</L>
<L>Sone scho ette, als he hir red,</L>
<L N="68">Of &thorn;e fruit god vs bath for-bed;</L>
<L>Scho bed it me and I ette sum,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us bigan oure care to cum;</L>
<L>&THORN;e gerrard &thorn;us gan hir bigile,</L>
<L N="72">And me also, allas &thorn;at while!</L>
<L>&THORN;an of oure werk was god il paid,</L>
<L>And als sone vnto me he said:&mdash;</L>
<L>'Adam, for &thorn;ou has left my lare</L>
<L N="76">And broken &thorn;e bode &thorn;at I bad are,</L>
<L>And mare wroght efter &thorn;i wife,</L>
<L>&THORN;an efter me &thorn;at lent &thorn;e life,</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i bodi sal I send</L>
<L N="80">Sexty wowndes and ten to lend,</L>
<L>Right fra &thorn;i heuid vnto &thorn;i hele,</L>
<L>Eghen and eres and ilka dele;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;i lims on ilka side</L>
<L N="84">Witht sorows sall be ocupide.' "</L>
<L>He said, "suns, god has sent &thorn;is thing</L>
<L>Vntill vs and all oure of-spring;</L>
<L>Bot oure lord god almighty</L>
<L N="88">Said we suld haue oile of mercy,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e werldes end, if we wald craue,</L>
<L>Of all &thorn;is site vs forto saue;"</L>
<L>All on &thorn;is wise when he had talde,</L>
<L N="92">He feled sorows ful many-falde;</L>
<L>He cried and said him self vnto,</L>
<L>"Allas! caytif what sall I do;</L>
<L>&THORN;at slike sorows er to me send,</L>
<L N="96">And has no medsin me to mend!"</L>
<L>When eue herd &thorn;at he said swa,</L>
<L>Scho wepid and had ful mekell wa,</L>
<L>And vnto god fast gan scho call,</L>
<L N="100">"Lord forgif me &thorn;ir angers all!
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>I wroght &thorn;e werk, &thorn;at wate I wele,</L>
<L>Wharfore we haue &thorn;is dole ilkdele."</L>
<L>Scho praied adam on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="104">"Lord lat me haue &thorn;i sorow sere,</L>
<L>For sertes I did all &thorn;e syn<MILESTONE N="77:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wharfore &thorn;ou es &thorn;ir angers in."</L>
<L>&THORN;an adam answerd hir vntill,</L>
<L N="108">"It may noght be wroght at oure will,</L>
<L>Oure lord of heuyn &thorn;at has it send</L>
<L>Thurgh his might he may it mend."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Adam &thorn;an vnto seth gan say:</L>
<L N="112">"Sun of a thing I sal &thorn;e pray,</L>
<L>Forto wend als I sall &thorn;e wys</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e &yogh;ates of paradis,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e &yogh;ates, when &thorn;ou cumes right,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;ou sal mak sorow in goddes sight;</L>
<L>Fall to erth and powder &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And pray god haue mercy on me,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an par auenture send sall he</L>
<L N="120">Sum of his angels to &thorn;at tre,</L>
<L>Of whi[l]k springes &thorn;e oile of life,</L>
<L>&THORN;at medcyn es to man and wife,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar forto send me sum dele,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;an hope I &thorn;at my care sal kele."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd seth and said in hy,</L>
<L>"To do &thorn;i will I am redy,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e bus teche to me &thorn;e way,</L>
<L N="128">And what I sall to &thorn;e angell say."</L>
<L>Adam said, "sun tell him till</L>
<L>How &thorn;at I haue angers ill,</L>
<L>And tell him also of &thorn;is thing</L>
<L N="132">How &thorn;at my life es nere ending;</L>
<L>And pray him me to certify</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e oile of mercy weterly,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk god hight me of his grace,</L>
<L N="136">When he me put out of &thorn;at place;
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>If he now &thorn;at sand to me will send,</L>
<L>Of all my sorow it sall me mend:"</L>
<L>"And sun," he said, "I sall &thorn;e say</L>
<L N="140">Wharby &thorn;ou sall ken &thorn;e way:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sall sone find a grene gate</L>
<L>Euyn vnto paradis &yogh;ate;</L>
<L>Wend estward and for no thing let,</L>
<L N="144">Vntill &thorn;ou in &thorn;at way be set;</L>
<L>&THORN;an many fotesteps saltou se,</L>
<L>Bath of &thorn;i moder and of me;</L>
<L>For by &thorn;at ilk way went we twa,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;i moder and I with-outen ma,</L>
<L>When we war put out of &thorn;at blis</L>
<L>To won in midelerth for oure mis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sin of vs twa allane,</L>
<L N="152">Was so grete and god with-gane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in what stedes oure fete gan fall,<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are groued neuer gres, ne neuer sall,</L>
<L>Bot euermore be ded and dri,</L>
<L N="156">And falow, and fade, for oure foly;</L>
<L>&THORN;us saltou find, with-outen mis,</L>
<L>Right to &thorn;e &yogh;ates of paradis."</L>
<L>Seth es went, with sorows sad,</L>
<L N="160">Furth right, als his fader bad,</L>
<L>And hastily he fand &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>Als adam vntill him gan say,</L>
<L>With welkit steppes, many ane,</L>
<L N="164">Als his fader bifore had gane;</L>
<L>And euen he held &thorn;at ilk gate</L>
<L>Vntill he come to paradis &yogh;ate:</L>
<L>On his face &thorn;an fell he downe</L>
<L N="168">And kest pouder opon his croune</L>
<L>Ful mekill murni[n]g gan he make,</L>
<L>And sorowed for his fader sake;</L>
<L>And vnto god fast gan he cri</L>
<L N="172">Of adam forto haue mercy,
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>And oile of mercy him to send,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he might in liking lend:</L>
<L>So als he made his praiers fast,</L>
<L N="176">God sent saint michael at &thorn;e last;</L>
<L>He bad &thorn;at seth he suld vp rise</L>
<L>And said vnto him on &thorn;is wise:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Seth," he said, "what sekes &thorn;ou here?</L>
<L N="180">I am michaell goddes messangere,</L>
<L>My lord of heuyn has ordand me</L>
<L>Ouer all his men keper to be;</L>
<L>And sertanly to &thorn;e I say,</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;at &thorn;e thar now&thorn;er grete ne pray</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;e oile of mercy here,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou gettes it on no manere,</L>
<L>Vntill a tyme if &thorn;ou tak tent</L>
<L N="188">When fiue thousand &yogh;ere er went,</L>
<L>Twa hundret and twenty &thorn;ar-till,</L>
<L>And also aght als es goddes will;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal god send doun his sun</L>
<L N="192">Crist in-to &thorn;e werld at won;</L>
<L>For mannes sins &thorn;an sal he dy,</L>
<L>And so fra bale he sall &thorn;am by;</L>
<L>Grauen he sall be in a stede</L>
<L N="196">And rise &thorn;e thrid day right fra &thorn;e ded,</L>
<L>And lif ogayne, in lim and lith;</L>
<L>And adam &thorn;an sall rise him with;</L>
<L>Adam and all his of-spring,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;at god vntill his blis will bring;</L>
<L>With crist &thorn;an sall &thorn;ai right vp ryght<MILESTONE N="77b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And wende to won in lastand light;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;i fader right vp rise</L>
<L N="204">And wend to welth in paradis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at same crist als I tell &thorn;e</L>
<L>In &thorn;e flum sal baptist be;</L>
<L>To saue man saules he sall be send</L>
<L N="208">And all fals trowth he sall defende;
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>&THORN;e oyle of mercy sal he gif</L>
<L>Till all &thorn;at in his law will lif;</L>
<L>And till all &thorn;at will sese of sin</L>
<L N="212">Sal he gif blis &thorn;at neuer sal blin;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;i fader cum fra paine</L>
<L>And dwell in paradis ogayne;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore if &thorn;ou &thorn;i fader se</L>
<L N="216">Say him als I haue said to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>'His daies er dreuen vnto &thorn;e end,</L>
<L>Langer in &thorn;is life may he noght lend.'</L>
<L>Bot first now, or &thorn;ou wend oway,</L>
<L N="220">Sall &thorn;ou do als I &thorn;e say;</L>
<L>Wende vnto paradis &yogh;ate</L>
<L>And put in bot &thorn;i heuid &thorn;arate,</L>
<L>And lat &thorn;i body stand &thorn;aroute,</L>
<L N="224">And luke what &thorn;ou sese &thorn;e obout;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou any selkuth se</L>
<L>Cum ogayne and tell to me."</L>
<L>Seth went and did on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="228">And saw ful many selkuthes sere;</L>
<L>He herd &thorn;are noyse and nobill smell,</L>
<L>Swetter &thorn;an any tong might tell;</L>
<L>Gay herbes and trese &thorn;are gan he se,</L>
<L N="232">And fowles sang ful grete plent&eacute;;</L>
<L>In middes of paradis saw he right</L>
<L>A well &thorn;at was schinand ful bright,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whilk foure flodes ran out,</L>
<L N="236">And went ouer al &thorn;e werld obout;</L>
<L>He saw of &thorn;a foure flodes clere</L>
<L>Come al &thorn;e water in &thorn;is werld here;</L>
<L>Obouen &thorn;e well persayued he</L>
<L N="240">Whare &thorn;are stode a ful faire tre,</L>
<L>With branches &thorn;aron maniane,</L>
<L>Bot bark ne lefe ne had it nane;</L>
<L>&THORN;an had seth meruail in his mode</L>
<L N="244">Whi &thorn;at tre so naked stode;
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>And wele he hopid, his hert with-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was for his fader sin,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e steppes war &thorn;at he had sene;</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at neuer bare none herbes grene,<MILESTONE N="78" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And all for &thorn;e sin of &thorn;am twa,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor he trowed &thorn;e tre was swa;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is thoght when he had left,</L>
<L N="252">In ogaine &thorn;an luked he eft,</L>
<L>And hastily &thorn;an gan he se</L>
<L>A meruaile of &thorn;e mekill tre;</L>
<L>Him thoght &thorn;at it stode vp ful euyn</L>
<L N="256">And rechid on heght right to &thorn;e heuyn,</L>
<L>And bark inogh &thorn;ar-on was sene</L>
<L>With leues &thorn;at was gay and grene;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e crop of &thorn;at tre on hight</L>
<L N="260">A litill childe he saw full right,</L>
<L>Lapped all in clathes clene,</L>
<L>Als it right &thorn;an born had bene,</L>
<L>So till his sight it semed &yogh;ing,</L>
<L N="264">He had grete meruaile of &thorn;is thing;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e erth &thorn;an luked he</L>
<L>And saw &thorn;e rotes of &thorn;at same tre,</L>
<L>Weterly him thoght &thorn;ai fell</L>
<L N="268">In-to &thorn;e vtterest end of hell,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are him thoght he had a sight</L>
<L>Of his bro&thorn;er saul ful right,</L>
<L>Abell &thorn;at was sakles slaine.</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;an to &thorn;e angell he went ogayne</L>
<L>And tald vnto him albidene,</L>
<L>Als he &thorn;are had herd and sene;</L>
<L>He pried &thorn;e angell tell him mare</L>
<L N="276">Of &thorn;e childe &thorn;at he saw &thorn;are;</L>
<L>&THORN;e angell answerd him in hy,</L>
<L>And said what it suld signify;</L>
<L>"&THORN;e childe &thorn;at &thorn;ou saw in &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;e sun of god for suth es he,
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>His schewing here noght els it ment</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at he sall till &thorn;e erth be sent;</L>
<L>He sall fordo &thorn;i fader syn,</L>
<L N="284">And vnto welth ogayne him win;</L>
<L>He es &thorn;e oile of mercy right,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk was to &thorn;i fader hight,</L>
<L>When he fra paradis gan wende,</L>
<L N="288">Thurght formast fanding of &thorn;e fende;</L>
<L>Fra bale to blis &thorn;is barn sal bring</L>
<L>&THORN;i fader and all his of-spring<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>of of spring</I>.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ordaind er in &thorn;e werldes ende,</L>
<L N="292">Fra wa till endles welth to wende."</L>
<L>&THORN;e angell &thorn;an toke kirnels thre</L>
<L>&THORN;at war tane of &thorn;at same tre,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whilk oure bale bigan,</L>
<L N="296">And vnto seth &thorn;us said he &thorn;an:&mdash;</L>
<L>"With-in thre daies when &thorn;ou cumes hame<MILESTONE N="78:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sall &thorn;i fader dy Adam,</L>
<L>And in a graue he sall be graid,</L>
<L N="300">And, when he es in erth so laid,</L>
<L>&THORN;ir kirnels &thorn;at I gif &thorn;e to</L>
<L>&THORN;an in his mowth &thorn;ou sall &thorn;am do,</L>
<L>For of &thorn;am sall thre wandes spring,</L>
<L N="304">And ilkone sall be of sere thing:</L>
<L>&THORN;e first of cyder suthly es,</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund sal be of cypres,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e thrid of pine sal be;</L>
<L N="308">And &thorn;ai bitaken &thorn;e trenit&eacute;,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cyder &thorn;e fader alweldand,</L>
<L>And in cypres &thorn;e sun we vnderstand,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e pyne &thorn;e hali gaste bi skill."</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;us tald &thorn;e angell seth vntill,</L>
<L>And when he was &thorn;us kyndely kend,</L>
<L>Hastily hamward gan he wend,</L>
<L>And hame also with him he had</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;e kirnels als &thorn;e angell bad.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000103.tif" N="71">
<HEAD>De obitu primi parentis ade.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When seth had wroght all on &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>And cumen hame fra paradise,</L>
<L>Vntill his fader fast gan he fare,</L>
<L N="320">Als he lay in sekenes sare,</L>
<L>And tald vnto him albidene</L>
<L>How he had done whare he had bene,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e angell gan him hete</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;at he suld haue his bale to bete,</L>
<L>Oile of mercy fra god send</L>
<L>To saue him in &thorn;e werldes end.</L>
<L>When adam herd him sogat say,</L>
<L N="328">&THORN;a wordes ful gretely gan him pay,</L>
<L>And in his life &thorn;an anes he logh,</L>
<L>For he hopid forto win fra wogh,</L>
<L>And forto be saued sertainely;</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;arfore to god &thorn;us gan he cry,</L>
<L>"Lord me list no langer lif,</L>
<L>Mi gaste in-to &thorn;i hend I gif</L>
<L>Forto wis it at &thorn;i will,</L>
<L N="336">In whilk stede so it sall go till."</L>
<L>&THORN;us he died with-in &thorn;e thrid day</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e angell vnto seth gan say;</L>
<L>&THORN;an had he lifed in &thorn;is werld here</L>
<L N="340">Nien hundreth and threty &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>For mans kinde was &thorn;an so strang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai moght wele lif so lang.</L>
<L>When he was ded &thorn;us als I tell,</L>
<L N="344">Both wife and barnes opon him fell<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And lay opon &thorn;e cors criand,</L>
<L>Heuid to heuid and hand to hand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai trowed to turn life him vntill,</L>
<L N="348">For &thorn;ai kowth &thorn;an none o&thorn;er skill;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai murned with dreri mode,</L>
<L>Michaell come and by &thorn;am stode,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er angels gudely graid,
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="72"></L>
<L N="352">And vnto seth al &thorn;us he said:</L>
<L>"Wepes namore, bot bese still,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us it es my lordes will,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I sal teche here &yogh;ow vnto</L>
<L N="356">How &yogh;e with &thorn;is cors sall do;</L>
<L>Takes him vp and wendes with me,</L>
<L>For in erth sall he bereed be."</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke &thorn;e cors vp &thorn;am omang,</L>
<L N="360">And &thorn;e angels bifore gan gang</L>
<L>Singand all ful solempnely,</L>
<L>And makand nobill melody;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e vale of ebron &thorn;ai him broght</L>
<L N="364">And groue him &thorn;are, als &thorn;am gude thoght.</L>
<L>&THORN;an al his barnes awonderd ware</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e sight &thorn;at &thorn;ai saw &thorn;are;</L>
<L>&THORN;e angel said &thorn;an to &thorn;am in hy,</L>
<L N="368">"Of &thorn;is thing haues no ferly,</L>
<L>For als we now do him vnto</L>
<L>So sal &yogh;e with &yogh;owre ded men do;</L>
<L>Gers beri &thorn;am in erth or stane,</L>
<L N="372">For all sall di &thorn;at life<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>lift.</I></NOTE> has tane."</L>
<L>Seth &thorn;an opon &thorn;a kirnels thoght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he fra paradis had broght;</L>
<L>In his fader mowth he &thorn;am did</L>
<L N="376">Als &thorn;e angell gan him bid;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;a kirnels thurgh goddes grace</L>
<L>Wex thre wandes in litill space,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;a wandes grete ferlis fell,</L>
<L N="380">Als men may here me efter tell;</L>
<L>Ful mekill sele was to &thorn;am sent,</L>
<L>Als men may here wha takes entent;</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De tribus uirgis in ore ade crescentibus</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In adams mouth &thorn;ir wandes stode,</L>
<L N="384">Till tyme of noie efter &thorn;e flode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was to wit with-outen were,</L>
<L>A thowsand sexty and twelue &yogh;ere;
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>And furth &yogh;it groued &thorn;ai in adam</L>
<L N="388">Fra noie till tyme of abraham,</L>
<L>Fra abraham &yogh;it stode &thorn;ai &thorn;en</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e cumyng of moysen;</L>
<L>And now&thorn;er flitted fer no nere,<MILESTONE N="78b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="392">And ilkone groued by &thorn;am self sere;</L>
<L>Ane elne of lenkith &thorn;a wandes ware</L>
<L>And all &thorn;is time wex &thorn;ai nomare,</L>
<L>Bot in astate ay war &thorn;ai sene,</L>
<L N="396">And euer grouand in like grene;</L>
<L>Lang efter &thorn;at tyme &thorn;us bifell</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e childer of israel</L>
<L>Went with moyses thurght &thorn;e se,</L>
<L N="400">Fra pharao and his men&yogh;&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mekill wa had to &thorn;am wroght,</L>
<L>And in grete bondage had &thorn;am broght;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai past &thorn;e se bath hale and sound,</L>
<L N="404">And pharao and his men war dround;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;aire fase war &thorn;us for-done</L>
<L>To &thorn;e vale of ebron come &thorn;ai sone,</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai in &thorn;at dale gan dwell</L>
<L N="408">Forther-mar &thorn;an &thorn;us bifell;</L>
<L>Opon ane euyn als moyses &yogh;ode</L>
<L>He saw whare &thorn;ir thre wandes stode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at are in adams mowth was sett,</L>
<L N="412">And with grete honore he &thorn;am grett;</L>
<L>"For suth," he said, "&thorn;ir wandes mene</L>
<L>&THORN;e trinit&eacute; &thorn;am thre bitwene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;is wise er samin sett,</L>
<L N="416">For in &thorn;e rote all war &thorn;ai mett."</L>
<L>&THORN;a wandes &thorn;an thoght he forto take</L>
<L>Wirschip to &thorn;am forto make;</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e erth when he drogh &thorn;am out</L>
<L N="420">So nobil smell was &thorn;am obout,</L>
<L>And so gude sauore gan &thorn;ai fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his men wend wonder wele
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had bene cumen right,</L>
<L N="424">To &thorn;e land of hest &thorn;at &thorn;am was hight;</L>
<L>Al his folk &thorn;ai war ful fayne</L>
<L>And loued god with might and mayne:</L>
<L>Moyses toke &thorn;a wandes schene;</L>
<L N="428">And lapped &thorn;am in clathes clene,</L>
<L>And als a relik obout &thorn;am bare,</L>
<L>With wirschip, als &thorn;ai worthy ware:</L>
<L>Ay whils &thorn;ai dwelled so in fere,</L>
<L N="432">And &thorn;at was foure and fourty &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at war with wormes smeten,</L>
<L>Or els with wilde bestes beten,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai might neght &thorn;a wandes nere</L>
<L N="436">&THORN;ai suld als fast be hale and fere,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at defaut suld &thorn;ai find nane,</L>
<L>Thurgh towcheing of &thorn;e wandes allane:</L>
<L>So it bifell &thorn;e folk had care<MILESTONE N="79" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="440">For &thorn;at &thorn;am wanted water &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;aire hertes &thorn;ai bigan</L>
<L>To be mis-trowand ilka man,</L>
<L>To god &thorn;ai groched al bidene;</L>
<L N="444">And moyses said to &thorn;am in tene,</L>
<L>"Mistrowand men herkins to me,</L>
<L>If &yogh;e in trowth will stedefast be,</L>
<L>We sall gett water grete wane</L>
<L N="448">Here out of &thorn;is hard stane."</L>
<L>For god had bidden him on &thorn;is wise</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld strike on &thorn;e flint twise,</L>
<L>And largely &thorn;an suld it gif</L>
<L N="452">Water &thorn;at &thorn;ai with might lif;</L>
<L>&THORN;an with his wand &thorn;e stane strake he</L>
<L>And water went out grete plent&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men and bestes had &thorn;aire fill</L>
<L N="456">Of water at &thorn;aire awin will;</L>
<L>And for moyses toke all &thorn;e mede</L>
<L>And loued noght god for his gude dede,
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>Ne gert &thorn;e folk na louing make</L>
<L N="460">To him &thorn;at sent it for &thorn;aire sake,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore oure lord god all-mighty,</L>
<L>Said vnto moyses opinly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld noght &thorn;a childer bring</L>
<L N="464">Vnto &thorn;e land of his heteing,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e land of promisiowne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he had made vnto &thorn;am boune.</L>
<L>&THORN;an moyses wist and wele he kend</L>
<L N="468">&THORN;at his life drogh nere &thorn;e ende;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hill of thabor &thorn;an went he</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he sett &thorn;ir wandes thre,</L>
<L>By-side a water vnder &thorn;at hill,</L>
<L N="472">For he hopid it was goddes will</L>
<L>&THORN;at gude werk suld with &thorn;am be done;</L>
<L>&THORN;an efter &thorn;is he died sune.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Quomodo dauid tulit uirgas in ierusalem.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Still &thorn;an stode &thorn;a wandes &thorn;are</L>
<L N="476">A thowsand &yogh;ere and wex nomare,</L>
<L>Bot in astate ay gan &thorn;ai stand</L>
<L>Till dauid was king of iews land;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was a lang tyme bitwene,</L>
<L N="480">And euer &thorn;ai groued ilyke grene;</L>
<L>&THORN;an dauid was thurgh &thorn;e haly gaste</L>
<L>Warned &thorn;at he suld wende in haste,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e land of araby</L>
<L N="484">Till &thorn;e hill of thabor hastily,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thre wandes &thorn;are forto fett,</L>
<L>&THORN;at moyses &thorn;e profett had sett;<MILESTONE N="79:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To ierusalem &thorn;at &thorn;ai war broght</L>
<L N="488">For thurgh &thorn;am suld be wonders wroght,</L>
<L>And diuers dedis done bidene,</L>
<L>And efterward so was it sene;</L>
<L>&THORN;us when dauid warned was</L>
<L N="492">Till araby sone gan he pas,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hill of thabor fast he &yogh;ode,
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>Whare &thorn;ir ilk thre wandes stode;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e stede he went full euyn,</L>
<L N="496">Als he was warned with god of heuyn;</L>
<L>And when he of &thorn;e wandes had sight</L>
<L>He honord &thorn;am with all his might,</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;am vp out of grounde;</L>
<L N="500">And swilk a smell &thorn;are was &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>And noise and nobill melodi</L>
<L>Of diuers maners of minstralsy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at dauid and his men&yogh;&eacute; wend</L>
<L N="504">&THORN;e haly gaste had &thorn;are descend,</L>
<L>So mekill mirth gan with &thorn;am mete</L>
<L>Of nobill noyse and sauore swete;</L>
<L>&THORN;an dauid laid &thorn;a wandes in fere</L>
<L N="508">In a kase al of siluer clere;</L>
<L>He sang ful fast so was he faine</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise he went ogayne;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai went so by &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L N="512">Seke men many gan &thorn;ai mete,</L>
<L>All war &thorn;ai helid in gude degr&eacute;,</L>
<L>Thurgh vertu of &thorn;a wandes thre.</L>
<L>Dauid was ful glad and blith,</L>
<L N="516">Vnto his cuntr&eacute; come he swith;</L>
<L>&THORN;e nyend day efter hame come he</L>
<L>To ierusalem &thorn;e riche cet&eacute;,</L>
<L>Bot night it was thurgh goddes will</L>
<L N="520">When &thorn;ai come &thorn;e cet&eacute; vntill,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e wandes had dauid thoght</L>
<L>With wirschip whare he sett &thorn;am moght,</L>
<L>And in a dike he did &thorn;am right</L>
<L N="524">Biside his castell all &thorn;at night,</L>
<L>And seker men he sett to wake,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld no harmes take;</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn he thoght to seke a space</L>
<L N="528">To plant &thorn;a wandes in honest place,</L>
<L>Forto be keped honestly,
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>And wirschipd als &thorn;ai war worthy.</L>
<L>To rest he went es noght at laine,</L>
<L N="532">And sone at morn he come ogaine;</L>
<L>He fand his wandes hale and sownde</L>
<L>Ful fast grouand on &thorn;e grounde,<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-of grete wonder him thoght,</L>
<L N="536">Bot remu &thorn;am &thorn;an wald he noght,</L>
<L>For in his hert he trowed right</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai war sett thurgh godis might;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-fore he lete &thorn;am stand &thorn;are still,</L>
<L N="540">And bad &thorn;at none suld negh &thorn;am till;</L>
<L>And forto dwell with-outen dout</L>
<L>He made a stif wall &thorn;am obout,</L>
<L>Stalwurthly of lime and stane,</L>
<L N="544">So &thorn;at negh to &thorn;am suld nane.</L>
<L>&THORN;e same lenkith &yogh;it war &thorn;ai &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als moyses in desert &thorn;am bare;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;us when dauid sett &thorn;am has,</L>
<L N="548">&THORN;an wex &thorn;ai so &thorn;at wonder was,</L>
<L>&THORN;e body wex in a hale tre</L>
<L>And &thorn;e crop was branches thre;</L>
<L>And for it wex so dauid made</L>
<L N="552">A serkell al of siluer brade,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at it suld sawded be</L>
<L>All obout &thorn;e haly thre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he might wit, with-outen were,</L>
<L N="556">How mekill it wex ilka &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>For it wex grete thurgh goddes grace</L>
<L>And also lang in litill space;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at stede &thorn;an stode it &thorn;are</L>
<L N="560">Threty &yogh;ere and sumdele mare,</L>
<L>And wex ful fast, I vnder-stand,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e tyme was nere cumand;</L>
<L>&THORN;an dauid wex dreri in mode,</L>
<L N="564">For in his hert he vnderstode</L>
<L>&THORN;at [he] a sinful man had bene
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>And vnt[o] god he gan him mene;</L>
<L>Sitand vnder &thorn;at haly tre,</L>
<L N="568">Grete sorow in his hert had he,</L>
<L>And in his sorowing said he &thorn;us,</L>
<L><I>Miserere mei deus</I> et <I>c</I>'.</L>
<L>And so he made his mis to mende</L>
<L N="572">&THORN;e sawter buke right to &thorn;e ende;</L>
<L>And in remission of his syn</L>
<L>To mak a kirk he gan bigin,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-obout he begged fast,</L>
<L N="576">Till foure and thwenty &yogh;eres war past;</L>
<L>And bisid him both day and night</L>
<L>With werkmen &thorn;at war wise and wight;</L>
<L>And for he was a synfull man</L>
<L N="580">Of god &thorn;us was he warned &thorn;an:&mdash;</L>
<L>"A hows to me saltou neuer make,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es for &thorn;i sinnes sake."<MILESTONE N="79b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Dauid answerd and said in hy,</L>
<L N="584">"Lord, wha sall make &thorn;i hows bot I,</L>
<L>Wha sall vnto &thorn;i werk tak tent,</L>
<L>Sen vnto me no sele es sent."</L>
<L>"Salomon &thorn;i sun," said he,</L>
<L N="588">"Sall mak a temple vnto me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euer-mare sal be in minde,</L>
<L>And in meneing omang man-kinde."</L>
<L>&THORN;an dauid wist righ[t] wele inogh,</L>
<L N="592">&THORN;at his life fast till ende drogh,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at cet&eacute; gert he call</L>
<L>&THORN;e eldest men and maisters all;</L>
<L>And hastily &thorn;ai come him till</L>
<L N="596">Forto wit what was his will;</L>
<L>&THORN;an vnto &thorn;am al &thorn;us said he,</L>
<L>"Takes salomon my sun for me,</L>
<L>For, sirs, als sune I sal be ded,</L>
<L N="600">And god has chosen him in my stede;</L>
<L>His corown so he gaf oway
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>And so he died &thorn;at ilk day;</L>
<L>&THORN;an in a grafe &thorn;ai gan him graue,</L>
<L N="604">Whare kinges suld &thorn;aire beriing haue,</L>
<L>With sang and grete solempnit&eacute;,</L>
<L>Als fell to swilk a lord at be.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Quomodo salomon perfecit templum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Salomon was corond king,</L>
<L N="608">And led &thorn;e land at his liking;</L>
<L>Moste sutile werkmen has he soght</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e temple fast &thorn;ai wroght,</L>
<L>And endid it of masonry</L>
<L N="612">In &thorn;e space of &yogh;eres twa and thretty;</L>
<L>Forto tell all his fader tyme</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;e wirking of him;</L>
<L>And when it suld till end be brogh[t],</L>
<L N="616">&THORN;e wrightes &thorn;at &thorn;e timber wroght</L>
<L>A mekill balk &thorn;am bud haue ane,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cuntr&eacute; &thorn;ai kouth find nane,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai soght in toun and in cet&eacute;,</L>
<L N="620">And nowre-whare might &thorn;ai find a tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald acorde vnto &thorn;aire met,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;at dauid king had sett;</L>
<L>It forto take &thorn;e king cumand</L>
<L N="624">And bad it suld no langer stand;</L>
<L>&THORN;an doun &thorn;ai hewit &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;aire werk might endid be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai caried it vnto &thorn;e kirk</L>
<L N="628">And ordand werkmen it to wirk;</L>
<L>&THORN;e maisters has &thorn;aire mesure tane,<MILESTONE N="80" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lenkith threty cubites and ane;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai polist it and made it plaine,</L>
<L N="632">Bot all &thorn;aire wirking was in vayne;</L>
<L>When it was made efter &thorn;aire merk,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wand it vp vnto &thorn;e werk</L>
<L>And langer &thorn;an &thorn;ai fand &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L N="636">By a cubet &thorn;an it suld be;
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;at fare &thorn;ai war vnfaine,</L>
<L>And sune &thorn;ai gat it doun ogayne</L>
<L>Eft &thorn;ai toke &thorn;aire mesures &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="640">And kuttes it als wele als &thorn;ai can;</L>
<L>"Do wind it vp" biliue &thorn;ai bid,</L>
<L>Bot al was in waste &thorn;at &thorn;ai did;</L>
<L>&THORN;an was it schorter &thorn;an &thorn;e assise</L>
<L N="644">Thrise wroght &thorn;ai with it on &thorn;is wise;</L>
<L>Acorde to &thorn;at werk wald it noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-of &thorn;am all grete wonder thoght;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai cald &thorn;e king for he suld se</L>
<L N="648">How &thorn;ai had wroght with &thorn;at tre,</L>
<L>For mekill tene was &thorn;am bitid,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ai war al so crafty kid;</L>
<L>When salomon saw it was swa,</L>
<L N="652">In-to &thorn;e temple he gert it ta,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at it suld honowrd be,</L>
<L>For sum might trowed he in &thorn;at tre;</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er balk &thorn;an haue &thorn;ai soght,</L>
<L N="656">And al &thorn;e werk till end &thorn;ai wroght.</L>
<L>&THORN;e haly tre, on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>Lay in &thorn;e temple many a &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Twa pilers of &thorn;e kirk bitwene,</L>
<L N="660">&THORN;e king gert kepe it &thorn;are ful clene,</L>
<L>And made &thorn;e custom in &thorn;at cuntr&eacute;,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at ilka man suld be</L>
<L>In &thorn;at stede anes in ilka &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="664">And ilkone on &thorn;aire best manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at haly tre forto honowre</L>
<L>&THORN;at se&thorn;in bare oure sauioure.</L>
<L>So it bifell opon a &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="668">Al &thorn;e cuntr&eacute;, fer and nere,</L>
<L>Vnto ierusalem &thorn;ai went</L>
<L>To honore &thorn;at tre with gude entent;</L>
<L>A woman was &thorn;are &thorn;am omang</L>
<L N="672">&THORN;at in hir hert ay hopid wrang;
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>Scho soght &thorn;eder &thorn;e sight to se</L>
<L>And trowed no vertu in &thorn;e tre;</L>
<L>Hir thoght it was scorne in hir wit</L>
<L N="676">&THORN;at o&thorn;er men so honord it;</L>
<L>Maximilla was hir name,<MILESTONE N="80:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Scho sat &thorn;aron hir self to schame,</L>
<L>And for scho trowed no might &thorn;arin;</L>
<L N="680">Hir clathes biliue bigan to brin</L>
<L>Als herdes &thorn;at had bene right dry,</L>
<L>&THORN;an cried scho loud, thurgh prophecy,</L>
<L>And said, "my lord mighty ihesu</L>
<L N="684">Haue mercy and on me &thorn;ou rew."</L>
<L>When &thorn;e iews herd hir on ihesu call,</L>
<L>Grete tene in hert &thorn;an had &thorn;ai all;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said "scho sklanders oure goddes euyn</L>
<L N="688">For a new god we here hir neuyn";</L>
<L>&THORN;ai bad &thorn;at bald men suld be boune</L>
<L>To haue hir tite out of &thorn;e toune,</L>
<L>And sune, with-outen o&thorn;er rede,</L>
<L N="692">&THORN;ai staned hir vnto &thorn;e ded;</L>
<L>Scho was &thorn;e first &thorn;at suferd schame</L>
<L>For &thorn;e neueni[n]g of ihesu name.</L>
<L>It was &thorn;aire custum, als men knew,</L>
<L N="696">&THORN;at who so neuind &thorn;at name ihesu,</L>
<L>He suld be staned to ded als sone</L>
<L>And so was with &thorn;at woman done.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De probatica piscina.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ful many when &thorn;ai saw &thorn;is sight</L>
<L N="700">Honord &thorn;e tre with all &thorn;aire might,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto made &thorn;ai more loueing</L>
<L>&THORN;an vntill any o&thorn;er thing;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e iews thoght grete despite,</L>
<L N="704">And to &thorn;at tre &thorn;ai went ful tyte;</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e toun &thorn;ai did it draw,</L>
<L>For men &thorn;ar-in no might suld knaw,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai saw grete worde of it went,
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="82"></L>
<L N="708">And men &thorn;arto toke mekill entent</L>
<L>And many men honord it mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;an goddes &thorn;at in &thorn;e iewri ware;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;ai ordand &thorn;am omang</L>
<L N="712">&THORN;at na more worde of it suld gang,</L>
<L>Bot for vertu &thorn;at was &thorn;ar-in</L>
<L>&THORN;ai durst it now&thorn;er breke ne brin;</L>
<L>In to a dike &thorn;ai gan it kast,</L>
<L N="716">So to be wasted at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore in &thorn;at dike &thorn;ai it did;</L>
<L>Bot god wald noght &thorn;e might war hid,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;at so grete word of it went,</L>
<L N="720">&THORN;arfore his sande &thorn;arto he sent;</L>
<L>Euer-ilka day a sertaine tyme,</L>
<L>Bitwix &thorn;e vnderon and &thorn;e prime,</L>
<L>His angels to &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L N="724">Ful oft-si&thorn;es men might &thorn;am se,<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai moued &thorn;e water in &thorn;at tide</L>
<L>And wesche &thorn;e tre on ilka side;</L>
<L>And all men &thorn;at war seke and sare</L>
<L N="728">If &thorn;ai in &thorn;at tyme might be &thorn;are,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e water was moued swa;</L>
<L>Wha so might first in-to it ga,</L>
<L>If he had neuer so mekill bale,</L>
<L N="732">Hastily he suld be hale</L>
<L>Thurgh vertu of &thorn;at haly tre;</L>
<L>&THORN;is was knawin in ilk cuntr&eacute;,</L>
<L>For mani &thorn;at blind and croked ware</L>
<L N="736">Hastily war &thorn;ai helid &thorn;are;</L>
<L>So when &thorn;e iews persayued right,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;e tre was schewid slike might,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said it suld noght lang be swa;</L>
<L N="740">Out of &thorn;e water &thorn;ai gan it ta,</L>
<L>And ordand it to be a brig,</L>
<L>Ouer a-no&thorn;er bek to lig,</L>
<L>For so &thorn;ai trowed &thorn;at mens fete,
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="83"></L>
<L N="744">And bestes &thorn;at went by &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>Suld cum and ga all ouer &thorn;at tre</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it suld wasted be;</L>
<L>For grete despite in hert &thorn;am thoght</L>
<L N="748">&THORN;at wonders thurgh it war wroght.</L>
<L>&THORN;us lay &thorn;is tre &thorn;are, als I tell,</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;e sage quene, dame sibell,</L>
<L>Come to ierusalem on a &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="752">Wisdom of salomon to here;</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at side hir gate was graid</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;is haly tre was laid,</L>
<L>And sone when scho &thorn;ar-of had sight</L>
<L N="756">Scho honord it with all hir might,</L>
<L>Kneland doune on ai&thorn;er kne,</L>
<L>Swilk vertu trowed scho in &thorn;e tre;</L>
<L>Hir clathes gert scho &thorn;ar-on lig,</L>
<L N="760">And bare fete went scho ouer &thorn;e brig;</L>
<L>Thurgh prophecy &thorn;an &thorn;us scho said&mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;is ilk tre &thorn;at here es laid</L>
<L>A verray signe wele may it seme</L>
<L N="764">Of a domesman &thorn;at all sal deme,</L>
<L>Als lord and maister moste mighty,</L>
<L>&THORN;us may &thorn;is signe wele signify."</L>
<L>Scho lended &thorn;are ay whils hir list,</L>
<L N="768">Grete wit of salomon scho wist;</L>
<L>And se&thorn;in ogayne gan scho ga</L>
<L>To hir cuntr&eacute; &thorn;at scho come fra,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at tre euer scho gan honowre</L>
<L N="772">&THORN;at se&thorn;in bare oure sauiowre;<MILESTONE N="80b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is haly tre lay in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Vntill &thorn;at crist suld suffe[r] dede,</L>
<L>When dome was gifen ordand was he</L>
<L N="776">Forto be hanged opon a tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at als a cros &thorn;an suld be wroght;</L>
<L>On swilk a tre &thorn;an had &thorn;ai thoght,</L>
<L>Sone a iew stode vp in hy,
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="84"></L>
<L N="780">And &thorn;us he said thurgh prophecy:&mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;e kinges tre, I rede, &yogh;e take,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &yogh;e laid ouer &thorn;e lake</L>
<L>To make a cros both large and lang</L>
<L N="784">&THORN;e kyng of iews &thorn;ar-on to hang."</L>
<L>To &thorn;is &thorn;ai all assented &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And rathly out of &thorn;e toune &thorn;ai ran;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai toke &thorn;e tre &thorn;an &thorn;are it lay,</L>
<L N="788">&THORN;e thrid part &thorn;ai hewed oway,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e rembnand haue &thorn;ai made</L>
<L>A large cros, bath lang and brade;</L>
<L>Viij cubites &thorn;ai made it lang</L>
<L N="792">With-outen &thorn;at in &thorn;e erth suld gang,</L>
<L>And a&thorn;er side of cubites thre</L>
<L>&THORN;at abouen &thorn;e heuid suld be;</L>
<L>When it [was] made &thorn;us at &thorn;aire will,</L>
<L N="796">&THORN;e cet&eacute; sone &thorn;ai broght it till,</L>
<L>To pilate went &thorn;ai ful gude spede,</L>
<L>He held him wele paid of &thorn;aire dede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De fabrice clauorum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>E cros es made, als it sall be,</L>
<L N="800">Bot &thorn;an &thorn;am nedes nayles thre;</L>
<L>&THORN;e iews war ful redy boune</L>
<L>And ran for na[i]les in-to &thorn;e toune;</L>
<L>Vnto a smith &thorn;ai come ful sone</L>
<L N="804">And bad, "belamy, biliue haue done,</L>
<L>Make thre nayles stif and gude</L>
<L>At naile &thorn;e prophet on &thorn;e rode";</L>
<L>When &thorn;e smith herd &thorn;aire entent,</L>
<L N="808">How &thorn;at ihesu suld be schent,</L>
<L>In hert he had ful mekyll wa</L>
<L>Obout &thorn;e nayles forto ga,</L>
<L>For of ihesu he vnder-stode</L>
<L N="812">&THORN;at [he] was prophet trew and gude;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore wele in his hert he thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at for him suld no nayles be wroght;
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>He answerd &thorn;am with wordes fre</L>
<L N="816">And said "&yogh;e gett none nailes for me,</L>
<L>God has sent on me his merke</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I may wirk no werk;"</L>
<L>In his bosum he hid his hand<MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="820">And said he hurt it on a brand,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ar-on," he said, "I haue slike pine</L>
<L>&THORN;at I hope my hand to tyne."</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd &thorn;e iews kene</L>
<L N="824">And said vnto him all in tene:</L>
<L>"All for noght &thorn;ou feynes &thorn;e,</L>
<L>All &thorn;i sare-nes will we se,</L>
<L>And bot we find &thorn;i tales trew</L>
<L N="828">Ful sare it sall &thorn;i seluen rew."</L>
<L>&THORN;us thai thret him in &thorn;aire saw,</L>
<L>And gert him &thorn;are his hand out draw,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was &thorn;are schewed in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="832">Grete gudenes, thurgh goddes grace;</L>
<L>His hand semed als it war sare</L>
<L>And hurting had it neuer &thorn;e mare;</L>
<L>&THORN;e iews saw &thorn;at it was so,</L>
<L N="836">And namore said &thorn;ai him vnto;</L>
<L>Furth come &thorn;an &thorn;e smithes whife,</L>
<L>A fell woman and full of strife,</L>
<L>By &thorn;e iews &thorn;are &thorn;ai stode,</L>
<L N="840">Scho spac hir husband litill gude;</L>
<L>"Sir," scho said, and loud gan cry,</L>
<L>"Sen when had &thorn;ou slike malady;</L>
<L>&YOGH;istereuen, when &thorn;e day was gane,</L>
<L N="844">Euill on &thorn;i handes had &thorn;ou nane,</L>
<L>And sen sekenes es sent to &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ir men sall noght vnserued be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sall haue nayles or &thorn;ai ga,</L>
<L N="848">Als sone my self sall &thorn;am ma."</L>
<L>Scho blew &thorn;e belise ferly fast,</L>
<L>And made &thorn;e yren hate at &thorn;e last.
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>&THORN;e iews helppid hir forto smite</L>
<L N="852">So &thorn;at thre nayles war made ful tite;</L>
<L>Hir husband saw and stode ful still,</L>
<L>He durst noght say &thorn;at scho did ill;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war full grete and rudely wroght,</L>
<L N="856">Bot &thorn;arfore &thorn;ai forsuke &thorn;am noght,</L>
<L>Bot sone, when &thorn;ai &thorn;ir nailes had,</L>
<L>Furth &thorn;ai went with hert ful glad,</L>
<L>And hastily &thorn;ai toke &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="860">Vntill &thorn;ai come to sir pilate.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000119.tif" N="[87]">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>FINDING OF THE CROSS.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harlein MS. 4196,<MILESTONE N="149b:2" UNIT="folio">.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>De Inuencione sancte crucis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MEn aw to honure euer omang</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros &thorn;at al our hele on hang;</L>
<L>And how &thorn;at haly tre was fun,</L>
<L N="4">Was &thorn;is feste ordand and bigun;</L>
<L>&THORN;at tre vs aw forto do honoure</L>
<L>&THORN;at bare oure lord and oure sauioure.</L>
<L>Whils Constantyne &thorn;e nobil king</L>
<L N="8">Lifd here in erth in grete liking,</L>
<L>Trew he was, in dede and saw,</L>
<L>And lely lifed he in his law;</L>
<L>In Rome he regnid als Emperoure,</L>
<L N="12">And gouerned it with grete honoure;</L>
<L>So in his tyme, trewly to tell,</L>
<L>All on &thorn;is maner it bifell:&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e grekis and &thorn;e folk of barbary</L>
<L N="16">Gederd ful grete cumpany,</L>
<L>Forto gif batail ogaynes rome,</L>
<L>And so by strenkit it to ouercum;</L>
<L>And when king Constantine herd tell</L>
<L N="20">Off al &thorn;is fare, how it byfell,</L>
<L>In his hert he had grete drede,</L>
<L>For ful grete power gun &thorn;ai lede;</L>
<L>He ordand him grete cumpany</L>
<L N="24">Of men of armes and archery</L>
<L>His land with fighting to defend,</L>
<L>And to hald it fro his enmis hend;</L>
<L>And als he lay opon a night,</L>
<L N="28">Bifore &thorn;at day &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld fight,</L>
<L>Him thoght he lukid to heuyn on high,
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e aire him thoght he sigh</L>
<L>&THORN;e same cros &thorn;at crist was on done,</L>
<L N="32">And a voice sayd &thorn;us to him sone:</L>
<L>"Ordayne &thorn;ine armes on &thorn;is kin wise,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ou ouercum &thorn;ine enmise;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is figure fully &thorn;ou trayst,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;an thar &thorn;e no thing be abaist;</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;is in &thorn;ine armes for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall &thorn;ou haue &thorn;e victori."</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>In hoc vince.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wakkend &thorn;an and was ful glad,<MILESTONE N="150" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="40">For he so gude herting &thorn;an had;</L>
<L>Vp he rase with hert ful light</L>
<L>And to his moder he went ful right,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was saynt Elyne &thorn;e noble quene,</L>
<L N="44">And tolde vnto hir ilkdele bidene;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is tithing scho was ful fayne</L>
<L>And gert ordan, with al hir mayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he suld haue swilk armes dight,</L>
<L N="48">Als he had sene by gastly sight;</L>
<L>His awin armes sone doun war laid</L>
<L>And &thorn;e cros in his scheld purtraid,</L>
<L>Byfore him in batayle to bere,</L>
<L N="52">And so he went furth to &thorn;e were;</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;e vertu of &thorn;e croyce,</L>
<L>Als he was warned by gastly voyce,</L>
<L>Al his enmis he ouer-come</L>
<L N="56">And broght &thorn;e victori to Rome.</L>
<L>Saint Elyne &thorn;an was wunder fayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir sun was cumen safe ogayne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk figure of &thorn;e rode</L>
<L N="60">Honurde &thorn;ai with mayn and mode;</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e cros no thing &thorn;ai knew,</L>
<L>Ne no thing wist &thorn;ai of Ihesu,</L>
<L>Ne no thing wist &thorn;ai what it ment</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at &thorn;ai honurd with gude entent.
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>&THORN;an king Constantine gert call</L>
<L>Of Iewry &thorn;e maisters all,</L>
<L>Forto enquere by &thorn;aire clergy</L>
<L N="68">What thing &thorn;at signe suld signify:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai said, "sir, lely we &yogh;ow hete,</L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;is tyme was a prophete</L>
<L>Hight ihesuc, and [in] &thorn;is same Cet&eacute;</L>
<L N="72">Was he hanged on swilk a tre;</L>
<L>Ful many men &thorn;arbi was mend,</L>
<L>And grete vertu &thorn;arof was kend,</L>
<L>Bot sone efter &thorn;e iews it hid,</L>
<L N="76">For no might suld of it be kid,</L>
<L>And how it was hid sal &yogh;e here.</L>
<L>Sir, it bifell in &thorn;is manere&mdash;</L>
<L>When ihesuc vnto ded was done,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;e iews &thorn;an tok &thorn;aire counsail sone,</L>
<L>Forto hide &thorn;at ilke haly tre,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it suld noght honurd be;</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e grete hill of caluary</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;ore groue &thorn;ai it ful priuely,</L>
<L>With two crosses &thorn;at theues on hang,</L>
<L>And also &thorn;e nayles &thorn;at war strang;</L>
<L>Al kest &thorn;ai priuely in a pyt,<MILESTONE N="150:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="88">So &thorn;at no man suld of &thorn;am wit;</L>
<L>&THORN;ore haue &thorn;ai liggen, on &thorn;is maner,</L>
<L>Sethin more &thorn;an two hundreth &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Sethin Tytus and vaspasian come</L>
<L N="92">And destroyd mony iews of Rome;</L>
<L>For right als &thorn;ai boght ihesu fre</L>
<L>For thritty penis of &thorn;aire mon&eacute;,</L>
<L>So war &thorn;ai sold to &thorn;aire enmy</L>
<L N="96">Euer thritty iews for a peny;</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wise war &thorn;ai al broght doun,</L>
<L>Vnder &thorn;e Emperoure subieccione,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at no man wun &thorn;ore sald</L>
<L N="100">Of &thorn;e Emperure bot &thorn;ai wald hald,
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>And sethin als wide als &thorn;ai er saun</L>
<L>Has no iew hous of his awyn;</L>
<L>Swilk maystris war made &thorn;am omell,</L>
<L N="104">And efter &thorn;at tyme &thorn;us bifell:&mdash;</L>
<L>In Rome ane Emperoure was &thorn;an</L>
<L>&THORN;at named was sir adrian,</L>
<L>Cristen law wald he none ken,</L>
<L N="108">Bot euer distryed al cristenmen;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Emperoure wele vnderstode</L>
<L>Whore his elders had hid &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>And herby persayued he it right,</L>
<L N="112">For cristen men both day and night</L>
<L>Come to honure &thorn;at haly stede,</L>
<L>And bousomly &thorn;ore made &thorn;aire bede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai honurd &thorn;e mount of caluary,</L>
<L N="116">In wirschip of &thorn;e cros namely.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Emperoure of Rome</L>
<L>Wist cristen men so &thorn;eder come,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros he wold noght &thorn;ethin take,</L>
<L N="120">Bot &thorn;us he ordand for &thorn;aire sake</L>
<L>In &thorn;at same place to edify</L>
<L>A temple for &thorn;aire maumetry,</L>
<L>For cristen men suld &thorn;an forbere</L>
<L N="124">In &thorn;at stede to mak prayere;</L>
<L>&THORN;an cristen men &thorn;at place refused,</L>
<L>None of &thorn;am efter &thorn;eder vsed,</L>
<L>And so it wurthed at &thorn;e last</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e cros al out of minde was past,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was for no man herd say</L>
<L>&THORN;arof ne in what stede it lay.</L>
<L>Lang efter &thorn;e temple of maumetry</L>
<L N="132">Was all distroyd fro Caluary,</L>
<L>&THORN;an groued &thorn;e stede with thornes and breris,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e cros no thing men heris;</L>
<L>For two hundreth &yogh;eres war omell,</L>
<L N="136">Bitwix &thorn;e tymes &thorn;at I of tell.<MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>&THORN;an Constantine was Emperoure</L>
<L>And rewlid rome with grete honoure;</L>
<L>Vnto him was tolde in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L N="140">How &thorn;at &thorn;e iews &thorn;e cros gun hide.</L>
<L>Vnto his moder he said in hi,</L>
<L>"Moder, sen we haue &thorn;e victori</L>
<L>And myne enmise &thorn;us er slone,</L>
<L N="144">Thurgh vertu of &thorn;e cros allone,</L>
<L>And clerkis has told to &thorn;ow and me</L>
<L>&THORN;at criste was ded on swilk a tre,</L>
<L>Ful fayn I wold &thorn;at tre war soght</L>
<L N="148">And sone vnto more honure broght."</L>
<L>&THORN;an said his moder, saynt Elyne,</L>
<L>"Sun, for suth I sal noght fyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at haly tre or I haue fun."</L>
<L N="152">And sone hir way scho has bigun,</L>
<L>Furth scho went with faire men&yogh;&eacute;,</L>
<L>To ierusalem, &thorn;at riche cet&eacute;.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e iews herd hereof tell</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;at &thorn;e quene come &thorn;am omell,</L>
<L>Grete wunder had &thorn;ai albidene,</L>
<L>What thing hir cuming suld bimene.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e iews sone did scho call</L>
<L N="160">To cum into &thorn;aire comun hall,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sertayn suth hir forto lere</L>
<L>Of thinges &thorn;at scho wold enquere;</L>
<L>Here-fore &thorn;e iews had mekil dout,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;ai gedird togeder in grete rout,</L>
<L>And priuely &thorn;ai ask &thorn;is thing,</L>
<L>What was &thorn;e caus of &thorn;e quenes cuming.</L>
<L>And sum, als &thorn;ai had herd of hir,</L>
<L N="168">Said scho come for &thorn;e cros to spir,</L>
<L>Waron crist vnto dede was broght,</L>
<L>And ilkone said &thorn;ai knew it noght;</L>
<L>So was &thorn;ore ane &thorn;at hiyght Iudas,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at grete mayster omang &thorn;am was;
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>Saint simyon sun for suth was he,</L>
<L>And Simyon was sun of &yogh;ach&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Iudas said, "sumdele I mene</L>
<L N="176">Of thinges &thorn;at here bifore has bene;</L>
<L>Simyon, my fader, als &yogh;e sall here,</L>
<L>Told vnto me on &thorn;is manere:&mdash;</L>
<L>When he wist wele sune forto dy</L>
<L N="180">'Sun,' he said, 'herkin me in hy,</L>
<L>A counsail sall I tel to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk I will you hald priu&eacute;;</L>
<L>If it bifall, sun, in &thorn;i liue<MILESTONE N="150b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="184">&THORN;at any spir, o&thorn;ir man or wiue,</L>
<L>Or efter &thorn;e cros will &thorn;e ass,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ihesu crist on hanged was,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ai &thorn;arfore do &thorn;e to dede,</L>
<L N="188">Tell &thorn;am vnto swilk a stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at now es waste and al vnkid,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ore I wote wele was it hid;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou may &thorn;i ded escheu,</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;an wald I &thorn;at no man it kneu.'</L>
<L>&THORN;us tald he to me in what stede</L>
<L>&THORN;ai groue &thorn;e rode bi comun rede,</L>
<L>Bot if we any o&thorn;er wise mai do,</L>
<L N="196">I rede we tel noman &thorn;arto."</L>
<L>&THORN;an had &thorn;ai meruail in &thorn;aire mode</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai herd neuer are of &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>&THORN;an come &thorn;ai furth, ilkone bidene,</L>
<L N="200">In comun hall bifor &thorn;e quene.</L>
<L>Sone on &thorn;is wise scho said &thorn;am to&mdash;</L>
<L>"Dose swith and chese one of &thorn;ir two,</L>
<L>Whethir &yogh;ow es leuir to suffer dede,</L>
<L N="204">Or els to tel me in &thorn;is stede</L>
<L>Whore cristes cros in erth es hid,</L>
<L>And bot &yogh;e do, als I &yogh;ow bid,</L>
<L>Ilkone &yogh;e sall be brint &thorn;is day."</L>
<L N="208">And sone a fire scho did puruay,
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai saw &thorn;e fyr on brede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire hertis &thorn;an had &thorn;ai drede:</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e quene al gun &thorn;ai cry,</L>
<L N="212">"Lady, of vs here haue mercy,</L>
<L>For we wote no thing how it was;</L>
<L>If any wote &thorn;an wote Iudas,</L>
<L>For he was ane old prophet sun,</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;e laws wele better mai he cun;</L>
<L>His elders war of &thorn;e alde state,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;aire werkes sumdel he wate."</L>
<L>&THORN;an lete scho al &thorn;o o&thorn;er go,</L>
<L N="220">And Iudas toke hir vnto;</L>
<L>And for he wald tell no resoun,</L>
<L>He was done in depe dungeoun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore he lay in mirknes grete,</L>
<L N="224">Seuyn dayes, with-outen drink or mete.</L>
<L>For hunger he cried on &thorn;e seuynd day,</L>
<L>"Saue me and I sall yow say</L>
<L>Whore &yogh;e sall fynd &thorn;e rude tre,</L>
<L N="228">Als my fader tolde vnto me;</L>
<L>Vnto me es &thorn;is mater dym,</L>
<L>Bot sum knawing I haue by him."</L>
<L>Fro prisun &thorn;an was Iudas tone,<MILESTONE N="151:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="232">And furth went with &thorn;am ilkone</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e mount of Caluary;</L>
<L>&THORN;am folowd ful grete cumpany.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai come whore &thorn;ai wald be,</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;an Iudas knelid doun on his kne,</L>
<L>He said, "lord, &thorn;at all has in wald&euml;,</L>
<L>If tales be trew &thorn;at men has talde,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou be he &thorn;is werld bigan,</L>
<L N="240">And verrayli es both god and man,</L>
<L>And of a maiden in erth was born,</L>
<L>Als sere prophetis haue said biforn,</L>
<L>Send us sum takening of &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L N="244">To find &thorn;e rude tre in &thorn;is place,
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>Wharon &thorn;i self wald suffer dede,</L>
<L>If it be hid here in &thorn;is stede."</L>
<L>Als Iudas &thorn;us gun his prayers make,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;e hill obouen bigan to quake,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arof rase a ful grete reke,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at was ful wele smelland smeke;</L>
<L>Ful mekil mirth was &thorn;am omell,</L>
<L N="252">Fo[r] neuer man feld swetter smell;</L>
<L>&THORN;an Iudas fast bigan to cry,</L>
<L>And he said ful stedfastly,</L>
<L><I>In veritate</I>, christe, <I>tu es redemptor mundi</I>,</L>
<L N="256">"In suthfastnes, lord criste, I trow,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sauioure of &thorn;is werld es &thorn;ow,</L>
<L>&THORN;at born was of &thorn;e mayden chaste,</L>
<L>And sall be euer of mightes maste;</L>
<L N="260">Vnto &thorn;i law I wil me take,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Ieus law euer I forsake."</L>
<L>&THORN;an cristen man &thorn;ai gan him mak</L>
<L>And turned his name to Quiriak,</L>
<L N="264">Sethin was he Bisschop in hali kirk,</L>
<L>And hali werkis oft gun he wirk.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai biheld whore &thorn;e smel come out,</L>
<L>And fast grubed &thorn;ai &thorn;ore obout;</L>
<L N="268">So depe &thorn;ai grubbed and so fast,</L>
<L>Thre crosses fand &thorn;ai at &thorn;e last;</L>
<L>Ane of crist both large and lang,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er two &thorn;at theues on hang,</L>
<L N="272">Bot &thorn;ore was noman &thorn;at knew</L>
<L>Whilk was &thorn;e cros of ihesu.</L>
<L>&THORN;an Quiriak prayd, with hert and hend,</L>
<L>&THORN;at god suld &thorn;am &thorn;e nailes send</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;at nayled crist &thorn;e rude vnto;</L>
<L>And sune when he had prayed so</L>
<L>Thre nayles aperd vnto &thorn;are sight,<MILESTONE N="151:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e erth schineand ful bright;</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;ai toke thre nayles and crosses thre
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>And bare &thorn;am to &thorn;e riche cet&eacute;;</L>
<L>Ful mikel folk come &thorn;am ogayne</L>
<L>And of &thorn;are fare &thorn;ai war ful fayne;</L>
<L N="284">And on a bere &thorn;ore gun men bring</L>
<L>A ded bodi vnto &thorn;e beryiing.</L>
<L>Quiriak bad &thorn;am &thorn;at it bare</L>
<L>Set doune &thorn;e bere omang &thorn;am &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="288">So forto proue &thorn;are, or &thorn;ai pas,</L>
<L>Whilk of &thorn;a crosses cristes was;</L>
<L>Quiriak fast vnto god prayd</L>
<L>And ane cros to &thorn;e cors he layd,</L>
<L N="292">And sethin ane o&thorn;er he laid &thorn;artill,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;it euer lay &thorn;e bodi styll;</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrid cros &thorn;an he toke for&thorn;i</L>
<L>And layd it vnto &thorn;e ded body,</L>
<L N="296">And als sune als it neghed nere</L>
<L>&THORN;e cors rase up, both hale and fere;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at saw &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>Loued god, with al &thorn;aire might;</L>
<L N="300">And so &thorn;ai past into &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>With a fful fayre processioune;</L>
<L>Al loued &thorn;ai god, with ioyful mode,</L>
<L>And saynt elyn scho bare &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;an sone omang &thorn;am herd &thorn;ai &yogh;ell</L>
<L>A ful grete dyn of deuils of hell;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai cried, "allas and wayloway,</L>
<L>For dole what sal we do &thorn;is day;</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;e tre es funden whilk we suppose</L>
<L>Sall ger vs all oure pouwer lose,</L>
<L>For we haue power in no place,</L>
<L>Whore men on &thorn;am &thorn;at takin mase;</L>
<L N="312">Now mun oure power fro us pas,</L>
<L>Wo wurth &thorn;e while it funden was!</L>
<L>For fro &thorn;at figure bihoues vs fle</L>
<L>So with man-kind ouercumen er we;</L>
<L N="316">It puttes oway all oure powere,
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at we mai noght negh it nere,</L>
<L>Bot-if we may with any gyn</L>
<L>Mak &thorn;am to do dedly syn;</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;an with &thorn;am wil I wun and wake,</L>
<L>For all &thorn;e crosses &thorn;at &thorn;ai can make,</L>
<L>Bot I may neuer no man spill</L>
<L>With syn, bot-if &thorn;am seluin will;</L>
<L N="324">Asay I sall, with sere sutelt&eacute;,</L>
<L>To ger men syn and serue me."</L>
<L>Quiriak said &thorn;an to &thorn;e fende<MILESTONE N="151b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou wikked deuil &thorn;i way &thorn;ou wende,</L>
<L N="328">Vnto &thorn;e deppest hole of hell,</L>
<L>Euermore in dole to dwell;</L>
<L>For funden es now &thorn;e haly tre</L>
<L>&THORN;at fellis &thorn;i pride and &thorn;i poust&eacute;."</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;e fendes &thorn;an with hidose cry</L>
<L>Vanist fro &thorn;am ful sudanly;</L>
<L>&THORN;an went &thorn;ai furth with meri mode</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;aire temple &thorn;ai bare &thorn;e rude.</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;an &thorn;e nobil quene Eline</L>
<L>Gert mak a case of syluer fyne,</L>
<L>With gold and precius stones plent&eacute;,</L>
<L>And closid &thorn;arin &thorn;at haly tre;</L>
<L N="340">And on &thorn;e mount of caluary</L>
<L>Gert scho mak a kirk in hy,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ore scho set &thorn;e haly tre</L>
<L>Of all men honord forto be;</L>
<L N="344">And sone when it was &thorn;eder broght,</L>
<L>Fro sere sides men &thorn;eder soght,</L>
<L>And ful grete grace was &thorn;ore schewd,</L>
<L>And grete releue to lerd and leude;</L>
<L N="348">Thurgh cristen land so es it kend,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fro &thorn;e fendes it mai us fend,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai may do us none ill,</L>
<L>Bot-if oure self assent &thorn;artill;</L>
<L N="352">For in werld has he no powere,
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>Night ne day to negh us nere,</L>
<L>If we his werkis will forsake,</L>
<L>And cristes cros opon vs make.</L>
<L N="356">God grante us grace so to honoure</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros &thorn;at bare oure sauioure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may to &thorn;at blis be broght,</L>
<L>Whilk crist with his blode to us boght.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
