<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000154.tif" N="[122]">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>EXPOSITION OF THE HOLY ROOD<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 4196,<MILESTONE N="177:2" UNIT="folio">.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>In festo exaltacionis sancte crucis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A king sum tyme in cuntr&eacute; was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at had to name king chodroas,</L>
<L>A sun he had &thorn;at was his ayre,</L>
<L N="4">And o&thorn;er menz&eacute; many and faire.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e cuntr&eacute; of pers was he king,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e land at his dedeing.</L>
<L>He gert ilk cet&eacute; and ilk toune</L>
<L N="8">Vnto his biding be so boune,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in a trone up he him sett,</L>
<L>And cumand &thorn;am with-owten lett</L>
<L>&THORN;at king of kinges &thorn;ai suld him call,<MILESTONE N="177b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12">And allso god grettest of all,</L>
<L>And lord of lordes both loud and still,</L>
<L>And none on melde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read <I>molde</I>.</NOTE> mete him untill.</L>
<L>Zit was noght &thorn;is in &thorn;at sesowne</L>
<L N="16">Inogh till his confusione;</L>
<L>Bot to ierusalem he went,</L>
<L>And said all suld be schamely schent</L>
<L>&THORN;at trowed on crist or on his lay.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ar-to he dose all &thorn;at he may,</L>
<L>In ierusalem &thorn;aire kirkes he stroyde,</L>
<L>And cristen men ful gretly noyed.</L>
<L>He toke his wai &thorn;an to &thorn;e graue</L>
<L N="24">Whare crist was layd &thorn;at vs sall saue,</L>
<L>It to destroy with all his mayn;</L>
<L>Bot for ferdnes he turned ogayne,</L>
<L>And durst do no thing at &thorn;e kyrk,
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="123"></L>
<L N="28">Bot wikkedly &thorn;us gan he wirk.</L>
<L>Saint Eline &thorn;e nobill quene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lang bifore his tyme had bene,</L>
<L>Fand &thorn;e cros<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>cors</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;at men cald &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at ihesuc died on for oure gude,</L>
<L>And to ierusalem scho it broght,</L>
<L>And graithed it &thorn;are als hir gude thoght,</L>
<L>In siluer and go[l]d al bidene,</L>
<L N="36">For &thorn;at it suld be kepid clene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at same kirk gert scho make</L>
<L>Coriosly for &thorn;at cros sake,</L>
<L>For men suld hald &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L N="40">In honore als it aw to be.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is ilk king chosdroass<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>choso|roass</I>.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>When he wist whare &thorn;is ilk cros was,</L>
<L>He gert his men with grete maystry</L>
<L N="44">Haue it forth with him in hy</L>
<L>Out of ierusalem cet&eacute;,</L>
<L>And broght it whare him liked to be.</L>
<L>When he was &thorn;us cumen hame ogayn,</L>
<L N="48">Of his iorn&eacute; he was ful fayne,</L>
<L>And hastili &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&thorn;ant</I>.</NOTE> gert he dight</L>
<L>A faire toure all off siluer bright;</L>
<L>He made it nobilly for &thorn;e nanes,</L>
<L N="52">Within all ful of precius stanes.</L>
<L>A trone of gold &thorn;arin he sett,</L>
<L>With precius stanes all ouer plett,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arein gert he gayly dyght,</L>
<L N="56">Like son and mone and sternes bright;</L>
<L>Also zit gert he mak &thorn;arin</L>
<L>Propirtese by preu&eacute; gyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was like untill a heuyn;<MILESTONE N="177b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="60">And rayn &thorn;arfro cumand ful euyn</L>
<L>And preu&eacute; whistils war omang</L>
<L>Made euyn like to angels sang.</L>
<L>&THORN;are in &thorn;at toure als him gude thoght,
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="124"></L>
<L N="64">A sege untill him self he wroght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he gert with mekill pride</L>
<L>Set &thorn;e haly cros him biside.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar als a god he sat in stall,</L>
<L N="68">And so he bad men suld him call.</L>
<L>His kingdom and all his riallt&eacute;,</L>
<L>Vntill his sun haly gaf he;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is wise &thorn;at curst caytiue</L>
<L N="72">In maumetry wald lede his liue.</L>
<L>And so he did full many a day</L>
<L>Ledeand &thorn;e folk in fendes lay.</L>
<L>&THORN;us with &thorn;e deuil we lat him dwell,</L>
<L N="76">And of his son I sall now tell.</L>
<L>A nobill king of cristendum,</L>
<L>&THORN;at namen was heraclium,</L>
<L>Was gouernowre of grete [empire]</L>
<L N="80">Souerainly als lord and syre;</L>
<L>Childer he had and worthly wife,</L>
<L>In cristes law he led his life.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is son of chosdroas</L>
<L N="84">In his hert euill angerd was</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is cristen king had name</L>
<L>More &thorn;an he or his sire at hame.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore he ordand him in hy,</L>
<L N="88">And gaderd a grete cumpani</L>
<L>Of sarzins by his assent;</L>
<L>And with ful grete ost es he went,</L>
<L>With &thorn;is cristen king to fight,</L>
<L N="92">And to destroy him if he might.</L>
<L>Bot sone eraclius herd tell,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is falshed how it bi-fell.</L>
<L>He ordand him full hastily</L>
<L N="96">Of cristen men grete cumpany.</L>
<L>Bot als it was oure lordes will,</L>
<L>When aither come o&thorn;er vntill,</L>
<L>In place whare &thorn;ai swld batayl take,
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="125"></L>
<L N="100">On &thorn;is wisse gan &thorn;ai couenant make.</L>
<L>A water was &thorn;am twa by-twene,</L>
<L>And a brig all ouer it clene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sarzyn was mekill of brede and lenth,</L>
<L N="104">And traisted mikill in his awin strenkth.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;is forward gan he ma</L>
<L>To do &thorn;e batail bitwix &thorn;am twa.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e cristend man suld mete him<MILESTONE N="178:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="108">In middes &thorn;e brig was ouer &thorn;e brim,</L>
<L>And whe&thorn;er so might maistri win</L>
<L>On his side suld &thorn;e bataill blin;</L>
<L>And he suld haue in his poust&eacute;</L>
<L N="112">All &thorn;at &thorn;ai bath had, land and fe.</L>
<L>To &thorn;is couenant assented &thorn;ai bath,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arto band &thorn;ai &thorn;am with ath,</L>
<L>&THORN;at if &thorn;aire men on ow&thorn;ir side</L>
<L N="116">Come forto help &thorn;am in &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld be cut for &thorn;aire iornay,</L>
<L>&THORN;aire armes and &thorn;aire legges oway,</L>
<L>And so be kasten in &thorn;e flode,</L>
<L N="120">And saue &thorn;am suld none erthly gude.</L>
<L>When bath &thorn;e sides war sworn &thorn;ar-till,</L>
<L>&THORN;is couenand lely to fulfill,</L>
<L>&THORN;e twa lordes<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>lorde lordes</I>.</NOTE> on &thorn;e brig<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>bring</I>.</NOTE> met,</L>
<L N="124">And ai&thorn;er hard on o&thorn;er set.</L>
<L>Ful fast &thorn;are faght &thorn;ai tow in fere,</L>
<L>And none o&thorn;er durst negh &thorn;am nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cristen men, with hertes fre,</L>
<L N="128">Prayed to ihesu crist, &thorn;at he</L>
<L>Suld send &thorn;aire prince &thorn;e victory,</L>
<L>Als he for &thorn;am on rode wald day,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;ai praied &thorn;an with a voice:&mdash;</L>
<L N="132">"Thurgh vertu of &thorn;i haly croyce,</L>
<L>Whar-thurgh &thorn;ou wan &thorn;e victori</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fende, oure fals enmy,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou grante &thorn;is day oure prince to wyn
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="126"></L>
<L N="136">&THORN;e maistri ouere zon fals sarzyn."</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere all prayed &thorn;ai fast;</L>
<L>And ihesuc herd &thorn;am at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>And ordand to his trew serwand</L>
<L N="140">Of &thorn;e sarzin to hawe ouer<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>euer.</I></NOTE> hand,</L>
<L>And to destroy him in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>Blisced be he &thorn;at gaf slike grace.</L>
<L>Sone when &thorn;e sarzins saw &thorn;is sight,</L>
<L N="144">How &thorn;aire maister to ded was dight,</L>
<L>Swilk drede in hert had &thorn;ai ilkane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai oblist &thorn;am noght allane,</L>
<L>To hald &thorn;e couenand made byforne,</L>
<L N="148">Bot new athes all haue &thorn;ai sworn,</L>
<L>With eraclius forto stand,</L>
<L>In ill and gude, with hert and hand,</L>
<L>And wilfully all hale hete &thorn;ai,</L>
<L N="152">Forto leue on cristes lay,</L>
<L>And forto bycum cristen men,</L>
<L>And crist for &thorn;aire god euer to ken.</L>
<L>Sone when eraclius saw &thorn;at sight,<MILESTONE N="178:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="156">He resayued &thorn;am with hert ful light,</L>
<L>And cownsaild &thorn;am with wordes fre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai suld all baptist be,</L>
<L>And trow in crist with gude entent,</L>
<L N="160">And to his saw all &thorn;ai assent.</L>
<L>So war &thorn;ai baptist all &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>And lifed euer in cristes lay.</L>
<L>Veraclius<NOTE PLACE="marg">So in MS.</NOTE> when &thorn;is was done,</L>
<L N="164">In-to pers puruaid him ful sone,</L>
<L>And with him all &thorn;at cumpany</L>
<L>&THORN;at bifore lifed in maumetry.</L>
<L>And als he went thurgh-out &thorn;at land,</L>
<L N="168">All &thorn;e folk &thorn;at he &thorn;are fand</L>
<L>Ou&thorn;er war &thorn;ai baptist sone</L>
<L>Or els &thorn;ai war vnto ded done.</L>
<L>&THORN;us conquert he all &thorn;at cuntr&eacute;,
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="127"></L>
<L N="172">Till he come tyll &thorn;at same cet&eacute;,</L>
<L>Whare Cosdroas so sitand es</L>
<L>Als a god in grete reches.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e toure he went full sone</L>
<L N="176">And fand him sitand in his trone,</L>
<L>Dubbed obut with pricius stanes,</L>
<L>And dight ful nobilly for &thorn;e nanes.</L>
<L>Biside him stode &thorn;at haly tre</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at &thorn;ai had soght so forto se;</L>
<L>And souerainly for &thorn;at tre sake,</L>
<L>Wirschip to him gan &thorn;ai make.</L>
<L>&THORN;an cosdroas was full affraid,</L>
<L N="184">And &thorn;us Eraclius to him said:&mdash;</L>
<L>"If &thorn;o will haue &thorn;i life in land,</L>
<L>Als I say sall &thorn;ou vnder-stand,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou has done &thorn;is tre honore,</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;at bare ihesu oure sauyore;</L>
<L>All if &thorn;ou did it noght for him</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e grante I life and lym.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e reuerence of &thorn;is haly tre,</L>
<L N="192">If &thorn;o will trow in ihesu fre,</L>
<L>And forsake all &thorn;i mawmetry,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou and &thorn;i folk yn affy,</L>
<L>And turn &thorn;e unto ihesu crist,</L>
<L N="196">And in his name will be baptist,</L>
<L>&THORN;i life in land &thorn;an haue &thorn;ou sall</L>
<L>And all &thorn;i kingdom still withall.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou will noght do &thorn;is rede</L>
<L N="200">With my swerd &thorn;ou sal be dede."</L>
<L>&THORN;is sarzin wald noght turn his mode,</L>
<L>To leue his fals goddes for no gude.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore Eraclius ful sone<MILESTONE N="178b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="204">Strake of his heuyd with-outen hone,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at he sul[d] haue beriing,</L>
<L>By-caus &thorn;at he had bene a king.</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ai toke &thorn;at haly tre,
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="128"></L>
<L N="208">With ful grete solempnit&eacute;,</L>
<L>And bare it<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>if</I>.</NOTE> furth so &thorn;am omang,</L>
<L>With himpnes and with nobil sang.</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk &thorn;an war ful glad,</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at &thorn;ai &thorn;is haly tre &thorn;us had.</L>
<L>Hamward &thorn;ai toke &thorn;e way in hy,</L>
<L>With mekill mirth and melody;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai come in &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L N="216">Doun ouer &thorn;e mownt of olyuete,</L>
<L>Als it fell in &thorn;are iornay,</L>
<L>To ierusalem &thorn;e redy way,</L>
<L>Graithly furth &thorn;ai held &thorn;e gate,</L>
<L N="220">Vnto &thorn;ai come till &thorn;at ilk zate,</L>
<L>Whare ihesuc crist went in ful playn,</L>
<L>When he come &thorn;eder at suffer payn;</L>
<L>And mekill folk of &thorn;at same toune,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at war cumen with processiowne,</L>
<L>For wirschip of &thorn;e haly tre,</L>
<L>And sum &thorn;at reall sight to se,</L>
<L>Eraclius him self gan ride</L>
<L N="228">Bifor &thorn;e prese with mekill pride,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;er lordes &thorn;at with him ware,</L>
<L>&THORN;e haly cros oma[n]g &thorn;am bare.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us, with grete solempnit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="232">Entred &thorn;ai to &thorn;at cet&eacute;.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;ai neghed &thorn;e zates nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is meruaill fell on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e zates, &thorn;at bifore war wide,</L>
<L N="236">Closed samyn sone in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at kenyng of zate was &thorn;are nane,</L>
<L>Bot all closed alls a wall of stane,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ai might no takning se,</L>
<L N="240">On whilk syde &thorn;ai suld haue entr&eacute;.</L>
<L>Sone when &thorn;ai saw &thorn;is wonder dede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;aire hertes &thorn;ai had grete drede.</L>
<L>Eraclius<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>Era|chius</I>.</NOTE> and o&thorn;er ma,
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="129"></L>
<L N="244">When &thorn;ai saw &thorn;at it was swa,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai praied ihesuc oure sawiowre</L>
<L>In &thorn;at case &thorn;am to socoure,</L>
<L>Thurgh uertu of &thorn;at haly tre,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at &thorn;ai might win to &thorn;at cet&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;us praied &thorn;ai all with drery steuyn,</L>
<L>Heueand up &thorn;aire heuides till heuyn;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ai loked so up on hight,<MILESTONE N="178b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="252">&THORN;ai saw ane angell schineand bright,</L>
<L>Euyn opon &thorn;e wall standand,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e cros in his hand;</L>
<L>He stode obouen whare &thorn;e zate suld be,</L>
<L N="256">And &thorn;ir wordes on &thorn;is wise sayd he.</L>
<L>He said, "when crist of heuyn king,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lord es of all erthly thing,</L>
<L>&THORN;is same wai to &thorn;is cet&eacute; went,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;are forto suffer<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>susfer</I>.</NOTE> grefe turment,</L>
<L>In at &thorn;is zate he toke &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>Bot he come all on o&thorn;er array.</L>
<L>Grete hors for him none ordand was,</L>
<L N="264">Bot sitand on a simple ass;</L>
<L>He was noght cled in kinges clething,</L>
<L>Bot pouerly went he in all thing;</L>
<L>He went noght with grete minstralsy,</L>
<L N="268">Bot in his prayers ful preuely:</L>
<L>Ensaumple suthly forto gif</L>
<L>To &thorn;am &thorn;at in his law wald lif,</L>
<L>In him to trow with trew entent,</L>
<L N="272">And mekely to wende als he went."</L>
<L>When &thorn;is was said, he went up euyn,</L>
<L>With grete light, till oure lord in heuyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Emperoure &thorn;an Eraclius</L>
<L N="276">Ful hertly thanked dere ihesuc;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e folk &thorn;at with him ware</L>
<L>War ful faine of &thorn;is ferly fare.</L>
<L>Sone of his stede doun es he light,
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="130"></L>
<L N="280">And kest of all his clething bright,</L>
<L>His corown and his kinges array</L>
<L>And his dubbing he did oway,</L>
<L>And barefot went he on his fete,</L>
<L N="284">Bereand &thorn;e cros<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>cors</I>.</NOTE> by &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is maner did &thorn;ai all.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e king come nere &thorn;e wall,</L>
<L>It opind and wex zates wide,</L>
<L N="288">Als it had bene bifor &thorn;at tyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai entred &thorn;an with solempne sang,</L>
<L>Ful mekill mirth was &thorn;am oma[n]g;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e cros bare &thorn;ai &thorn;am bitwene,</L>
<L N="292">Till &thorn;e stede whare it bifore had bene,</L>
<L>And up &thorn;ai set it really,</L>
<L>And honord it als was worthi.</L>
<L>&THORN;at day &thorn;are, thurgh &thorn;e cors allane,</L>
<L N="296">War miracles wroght ful maniane,</L>
<L>Of sere blind men &thorn;at had &thorn;aire sight,</L>
<L>And crokid men war made ful right;</L>
<L>Of parlesy war helid grete wane,<MILESTONE N="179:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="300">And dum and defe ful maniane;</L>
<L>And leprous men had hele in haste,</L>
<L>And out of many war deuils chaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;us war &thorn;ai held ful grete plent&eacute;,</L>
<L N="304">Thurgh vertu of [&thorn;at] haly tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bare ihesu oure sawiowre,</L>
<L>Vnto him be euer honowre.</L>
</LG>


</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000163.tif" N="[131]">
<HEAD>VIII.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>DISPUTE BETWEEN MARY AND THE CROSS<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Vernon MS.<MILESTONE N="315b:3" UNIT="folio">.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Disputacio inter Mariam et Crucem, secundum Apocrafum.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>Oure ladi freo&middot;,</L>
<L>on Rode treo&middot;,</L>
<L>made hire mon:</L>
<L N="4">Heo seide on &thorn;e&middot;</L>
<L>&thorn;e fruit of me&middot;</L>
<L>is wo bigon:</L>
<L>Mi fruit I&middot; seo&middot;</L>
<L N="8">in blodi bleo&middot;</L>
<L>Among his fon,</L>
<L>Serwe I&middot; seo&middot;,</L>
<L>&thorn;e veines fleo&middot;</L>
<L N="12">from blodi bon:</L>
<L>Cros&middot;! &thorn;ou dost no trou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>On a pillori&middot; my fruit to pinne,</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; no spot&middot; of Adam sinne;</L>
<L N="16">Flesch&middot; and veines&middot; nou fleo a-twinne,</L>
<L>Wherfore I&middot; rede of routhe&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>Cros&middot; &thorn;i bondes schul ben blamed,</L>
<L>Mi fayre fruit&middot; &thorn;ou hast bi-gyled;</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;e fruites Mooder&middot; was neuere a-famed,</L>
<L>Mi wombe is feir&middot;, founden vn-fuyled:</L>
<L>Chyld&middot; whi artou not a-schamed
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>On a pillori&middot; to ben I&middot;-piled?</L>
<L N="24">Grete Iewes&middot; &thorn;us weore gramed,</L>
<L>And dyede&middot; for heore werkes wyled;</L>
<L>In mournyng&middot; I&middot; may melte;</L>
<L>Mi fruit&middot; &thorn;at is so holi halwed,</L>
<L N="28">In a feeld&middot; is fouled&middot; and falwed;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grete Iewes&middot; he is galwed,</L>
<L>And dye&thorn;&middot; for Monnes gelte:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>FOr grete Iewes&middot; galwes were grei&thorn;ed,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at euer to Robbyng&middot; Ronne ryf;</L>
<L>Whi schal my sone&middot; on &thorn;e beo leid,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer nuy&yogh;ed&middot; mon nor wyf?</L>
<L>A drinke of de&thorn;&middot; so&thorn;liche seid,</L>
<L N="36">Cros &thorn;ou &yogh;euest&middot; &thorn;e lord of lyf:</L>
<L>His veynes to bursten&middot; wi&thorn; &thorn;i breid,</L>
<L>Mi fruit stont nou&middot; in a strong stryf;</L>
<L>Blod from hed&middot; is hayled,</L>
<L N="40">Fouled&middot; is my fayre fruit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer dude&middot; tripet ne truit</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;eues &thorn;at loueden&middot; ryot and ruit;</L>
<L>Whi schal my sone&middot; be nayled?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<L N="44">&THORN;orw&yogh; Iugement&middot; &thorn;ou art en-Ioynet</L>
<L>To bere fooles&middot;, ful of sinne:</L>
<L>Mi sone from &thorn;e&middot; schulde beon ensoynet,</L>
<L>And neuere his blod&middot; vppon &thorn;e rinne;</L>
<L N="48">But nou is tru&thorn;e&middot; wi&thorn; tresun teynet,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;eoues to honge&middot;, fer in fenne;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; feole nayles&middot; his limes ben feynet,</L>
<L>A careful Moder&middot; men mai me kenne,</L>
<L N="52">In Bales&middot; I&middot; am bounde;
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>&THORN;at fruit was&middot; of a Mayden born,</L>
<L>On a &thorn;eoues tre&middot; is al to torn;<MILESTONE N="316" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A Broche&middot; &thorn;orw-out his brest bo[r]n</L>
<L N="56">His holi herte&middot; ha&thorn; wounde:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>V.</HEAD>
<L>Tre &thorn;ou art loked&middot; bi &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>&THORN;eoues&middot; traitours&middot; on &thorn;e to d[e]ye,</L>
<L>But now is trou&thorn;e&middot; wi&thorn; tresun drawe,</L>
<L N="60">And vertu&middot; falle&thorn; in vices weye;</L>
<L>But loue&middot; and treu&thorn;e&middot;, in so&thorn;fast sawe,</L>
<L>On a treo&middot; traytours&middot; hem teye,</L>
<L>Vertu is&middot; wi&thorn; vices slawe:</L>
<L N="64">Of alle vertues&middot; my sone is keye,</L>
<L>Vertu&middot; swettore &thorn;en spices;</L>
<L>In fot&middot; and&middot; hond&middot; bere&thorn; blodi prikke,</L>
<L>His hed is ful of &thorn;ornes&middot; &thorn;ikke,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;e goode honge&thorn;&middot; a-mong &thorn;e wikke,</L>
<L>Vertu dye&thorn; wi&thorn; vices&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VI.</HEAD>
<L>Tre vnkynde; &thorn;ou schalt be kud,</L>
<L>Mi sone step-Moder&middot; I&middot; &thorn;e calle:</L>
<L N="72">Mi fruit was born&middot; wi&thorn; beestes on bed,</L>
<L>And be my flesch&middot; my flour gan falle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; my brestes&middot; my brid I&middot; fed;</L>
<L>Cros&middot; &thorn;ou &yogh;euest him&middot; Eysel&middot; and Galle!</L>
<L N="76">Mi white Rose&middot; Red is spred,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fostred was in&middot; a fodderes stalle;</L>
<L>Feet&middot; and fayre hondes;</L>
<L>&THORN;at nou ben croised&middot; I&middot; custe hem ofte,</L>
<L N="80">I&middot; lulled hem&middot; I&middot; leid hem softe:</L>
<L>Cros &thorn;ou holdest hem&middot; hi&yogh;e on lofte</L>
<L>Bounden&middot; in bledyng bondes&middot;!
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="134"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<L>Mi loue&middot; i&middot;lol ed vp in &thorn;e eyr,</L>
<L N="84">Wi&thorn; cradel bond&middot; I&middot; gan him bynde,</L>
<L>Cros he stike&thorn; nou&middot; on &thorn;i steir,</L>
<L>Naked a-&yogh;eyn&middot; &thorn;e wylde wynde:</L>
<L>Foules fourmen heor nestes&middot; in &thorn;e eyr,</L>
<L N="88">Wolues in den&middot; reste &thorn;ei fynde,</L>
<L>Bot Godes sone&middot;, in heuene heir,</L>
<L>His hed nou leone&thorn;&middot; on &thorn;ornes tynde,</L>
<L>Of Mournyng&middot; I&middot; may mynne;</L>
<L N="92">Godes hed&middot; ha&thorn; reste non,</L>
<L>But leone&thorn;&middot; on his scholder bon;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ornes&middot; &thorn;orwh his flesch gon,</L>
<L>His wo&middot; I&middot; wyte hit sinne:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VIII.</HEAD>
<L N="96">Cros to slen&middot; hit is &thorn;i sleiht,</L>
<L>Mi fayre fruit&middot; &thorn;ou berest fro blis;</L>
<L>Cros &thorn;ou holdest him so heih on hei&yogh;&thorn;,</L>
<L>Mi fruites feet&middot; I&middot; mai not kis;</L>
<L N="100">Mi mou&thorn; I&middot; pulte&middot;, my sweore I&middot; strei&yogh;t</L>
<L>To cusse his feet&middot;, so&thorn; &thorn;ing hit is:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes&middot; from &thorn;e cros me kei&yogh;t,</L>
<L>On me&middot; &thorn;ei made heore mouwes amis,</L>
<L N="104">Heore games&middot; and heore gaudes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes wrou&yogh;ten&middot; me ful wo:</L>
<L>Cros&middot; I&middot; fynde&middot; &thorn;ou art my fo,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou berest my brid&middot;, beten blo,</L>
<L N="108">A-mong &thorn;eose fooles fraudes&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IX.</HEAD>
<L>Cristes cros&middot; &yogh;af onswere:&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cross responds.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ladi to &thorn;e&middot; I&middot; owe honour,
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>&THORN;i brihte palmes&middot; nou I&middot; bere;</L>
<L N="112">Mi schyning schewe&thorn;&middot; &thorn;orw &thorn;i flour,</L>
<L>&THORN;i feire fruit&middot; on me ginne&thorn; tere;</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruit me florische&thorn;&middot; in blod colour</L>
<L>To winne &thorn;e world&middot; &thorn;at lay in lure;</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at Blosme Blomed&middot; vp in &thorn;i bour,</L>
<L>Ac not for &thorn;e&middot; al-one;</L>
<L>But for to winne&middot; all &thorn;is world,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swelte&middot; vndur &thorn;e deueles swerd:</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;orw feet and hond&middot; God let him gerd,</L>
<L>To A-mende monnes mone&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>X.</HEAD>
<L>Adam dude&middot; ful huge harmes,</L>
<L>Whon he bot A bite&middot; vndur a bouh,</L>
<L N="124">Wherfore &thorn;i sone&middot; ha&thorn; sprad his Armes,</L>
<L>On a treo tyed&middot; wi&thorn; teone I-nouh;</L>
<L>His flesch&middot; is smite wi&thorn; de&thorn;es &thorn;armes,</L>
<L>And swelte&thorn; heer-in&middot; a swemly swouh;</L>
<L N="128">His Breste is bored&middot; wi&thorn; de&thorn;es swarmes,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; his de&thorn;&middot; fro de&thorn; he drouh</L>
<L>Alle&middot; his leoue freondes;</L>
<L>As Ozie spac&middot; in prophecie</L>
<L N="132">And seide&mdash;"&thorn;i sone seinte Marie,</L>
<L>His de&thorn;&middot; slou&yogh; de&thorn;&middot; on Caluarie,<MILESTONE N="316:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;af lyf&middot; wi&thorn;-outen endes&middot;":</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XI.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e stipre&middot; &thorn;at is vnder &thorn;e vyne set</L>
<L N="136">May not bringe&middot; for&thorn; &thorn;e grape;</L>
<L>&THORN;eih &thorn;e fruit&middot; on me beo knet,</L>
<L>His scharpe schour&middot; haue I&middot; not schape:</L>
<L>Til grapes&middot; to &thorn;e presse beo set</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;er renne&thorn;&middot; no red wyn&middot; in rape;
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>Neuere presse&middot; pressed bet,</L>
<L>I&middot; presse wyn&middot; for kniht and knape:</L>
<L>Vp-on a Blodi brinke</L>
<L N="144">I&middot; presse a grape&middot;, with strok and stryf,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Rede wyn&middot; renne&thorn; ryf:</L>
<L>In Samaritane&middot; God &yogh;af a wyf</L>
<L>&THORN;at leof licour to drynke:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XII.</HEAD>
<L N="148">LAdi&middot; loue do&thorn; &thorn;e to alegge</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruit is prikked&middot; wi&thorn; speres ord:</L>
<L>On Cros&middot;, wi&thorn;-outen knyues egge,</L>
<L>I&middot; kerue fruit&middot; of godes hord;</L>
<L N="152">Al is al red&middot;, Rib&middot; and Rugge,</L>
<L>His bodi blede&thorn;&middot; a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e bord;</L>
<L>I&middot; was piler&middot; and bar a brugge,</L>
<L>God is weie&middot;, witnesse of word;</L>
<L N="156">God sei&thorn; he is&middot; so&thorn;fast weye;</L>
<L>Mony folk slod&middot; to helle slider,</L>
<L>To heuene&middot; mihte no mon &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>Til god dyed&middot; and tau&yogh;te whider</L>
<L N="160">Men drawen&middot; whon &thorn;ei dye&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIII.</HEAD>
<L>Moyses ha&thorn; fourmed&middot;, in his figour,</L>
<L>A&middot; whit lomb&middot;, and non o&thorn;er beste</L>
<L>Schulde be sacred vr saueour,</L>
<L N="164">And be mete of mihtes meste;</L>
<L>I&middot; was &thorn;at cheef chargeour,</L>
<L>I&middot; bar flesch&middot; for folkes feste;</L>
<L>Ihesu crist&middot; vre saueour</L>
<L N="168">He fede&thorn;&middot; bo&thorn;e lest and meste,</L>
<L>Rosted&middot; a-&yogh;eyn &thorn;e sonne;</L>
<L>On me lay&middot; &thorn;e lomb of loue,
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="137"></L>
<L>I&middot; was plater&middot; his bodi a-boue,</L>
<L N="172">Til feet&middot; and hondes&middot; al-to cloue,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; blood&middot; I&middot; was bi-ronne:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIV.</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;it Moyses&middot; in Rule ha&thorn; rad,</L>
<L>We schulde ete vr lomb&middot; in sour vergeous;</L>
<L N="176">Sour vergeous mai make&middot; vr soules glad,</L>
<L>To serwe sore&middot; for sunnes ours;</L>
<L>Sour vergeous schal make&middot; &thorn;e deuel a-drad,</L>
<L>For he flecche&thorn;&middot; fro godes spous;</L>
<L N="180">Beo a staf&middot; stonde&thorn; sad,</L>
<L>Whon &yogh;e fongen flesch&middot; in godes hous,</L>
<L>&THORN;at staf&middot; is Cristes Crouche;</L>
<L>Stonde&thorn; stifli&middot; bi &thorn;at stake,</L>
<L N="184">Whon &thorn;at &yogh;e fongen&middot; flesch in Cake,</L>
<L>&THORN;en schal no feond&middot; maystri make,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure soules for to touche:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XV.</HEAD>
<L>For pardoun schewe&thorn;&middot; be a shrine,</L>
<L N="188">Wi&thorn; nayl&middot; and brede&middot; on bord is smite,</L>
<L>Rede lettres&middot; write be lyne,</L>
<L>Bluwe&middot; Blake&middot; a-mong men pite:</L>
<L>Vr lord I&middot; likne&middot; to &thorn;is signe,</L>
<L N="192">His bodi&middot; vppon a bord&middot; was bite,</L>
<L>In Briht blod&middot; his bodi gan schyne;</L>
<L>Hou wo him was&middot; may no mon wite,</L>
<L>Red vp-on &thorn;e Roode;</L>
<L N="196">Vr pardoun brede&middot;, from top too to,</L>
<L>Writen hit was&middot; wi&thorn; wonder wo,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; Rede woundes&middot; and strokes blo,</L>
<L>Vre Book&middot; was bounden in bloode&middot;:
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="138"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVI.</HEAD>
<L N="200">Adam&middot; stod vp in stede,</L>
<L>In Bitter galle&middot; his gost he dreint;</L>
<L>A-&yogh;eyn &thorn;at galle&middot; God &yogh;af vs mede,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; swete Merci&middot; Bitter is queynt;</L>
<L N="204">His Bodi was Book&middot; &thorn;e Cros was brede,</L>
<L>Whon crist for vs&middot; &thorn;er-on was cleynt:</L>
<L>No mon gat pardoun&middot; wi&thorn; no bede,</L>
<L>Weor he neuere&middot; so sely a seynt,</L>
<L N="208">Til book on bord&middot; was sprad;,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sharpe nayles&middot; dunted and driue,</L>
<L>Til feet&middot; and hondes&middot; al-to riue;</L>
<L>His herte blod&middot; vre book ha&thorn; &yogh;iue,</L>
<L N="212">To make&middot; vr gostes glad:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVII.</HEAD>
<L>Cristes Cros&middot; &yogh;it spac &thorn;is speche<MILESTONE N="316:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Furst was I&middot; presse&middot; wyn to wringe,</L>
<L>I&middot; bere a Brugge&middot;, wei to teche,</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;er semely Aungeles&middot; sitte and synge:</L>
<L>Lord of loue&middot; and lyues leche</L>
<L>For &thorn;e was set&middot; sely sacrynge,</L>
<L>To winne &thorn;e world&middot; &thorn;at was in wreche;</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e Cros was brede&middot;, pardoun to bringe,</L>
<L>Pardoun&middot; In book is billed;</L>
<L>What is pardoun&middot; vppon to minne?</L>
<L>Hit is for&yogh;iuenes&middot; of dedly sinne;</L>
<L N="224">Whon blod was writen&middot; on cristes kinne,</L>
<L>Pardoun was&middot; fulfilled:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVIII.</HEAD>
<L>Oure ladi seide&middot; Cros of &thorn;i werk</L>
<L>Wonder &thorn;e not&middot;, &thorn;ei&yogh; I&middot; be wro&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="139"></L>
<L N="228">&THORN;us seide Poule&middot;, Cristes clerk;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feolle Iewes&middot;, wi&thorn; false o&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Iewes&middot; ston hard, in sinnes merk,</L>
<L>Beoten a lomb&middot; wi&thorn;-outen lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="232">Softur &thorn;en watur&middot; vndur serk,</L>
<L>Meode&middot; or&middot; Milk&middot; medled bo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes&middot; weoren harde stones;</L>
<L>Softur &thorn;en watur&middot; or eny licour,</L>
<L N="236">Or dew&yogh; &thorn;at li&thorn;&middot; on &thorn;e lilie flour</L>
<L>Was cristes bodi&middot; in blod colour,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes wolden&middot; ha broken his bones&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIX.</HEAD>
<L>And mony A prophete&middot; gan make mon,</L>
<L N="240">And seide&middot; "lord send us &thorn;i lomb</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e wildernesses ston,</L>
<L>To fende vs&middot; from &thorn;e lyon cromp:"</L>
<L>Of mylde mount of Syon</L>
<L N="244">Be-com mon&middot;, In A Maydens womb,</L>
<L>Made a bodi&middot;, wi&thorn; blessed bon,</L>
<L>In a Maidens blod&middot; &thorn;i bodi flomb:</L>
<L>At Barreres&middot; weore debate;</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;orw&yogh; stones&middot; In &thorn;e wildernes</L>
<L>Men mi&yogh;te better&middot; ha crepet I&middot;-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;en bored&middot; in-to heuene blis,</L>
<L>Til blod&middot; brac vp &thorn;e &yogh;ate&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XX.</HEAD>
<L N="252">Sin monnes sone&middot; was so nedi,</L>
<L>To beo lad&middot; wi&thorn; lomb mylde,</L>
<L>Whi weore gylours&middot; so gredi</L>
<L>For to defoule&middot; my faire childe?</L>
<L N="256">Cros whi weore &thorn;ou&middot; so redi</L>
<L>To rende my fruit&middot;, feor in fylde?
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>Ladi to make&middot; &thorn;e deuel dredi,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cross replies:]</NOTE></L>
<L>God schop me a scheld&middot;, schame to schilde,</L>
<L N="260">Til lomb of loue&middot; dyede;</L>
<L>And on me &yogh;eld &thorn;e gost&middot; wi&thorn; vois;</L>
<L>I&middot; was chose&middot; a Relik chois,</L>
<L>&THORN;e signe of Ihesu cristes crois,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;er dar no deuel&middot; a-byde:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXI.</HEAD>
<L>Moni folk I&middot; fende&middot; from heore fos:</L>
<L>Cristes Cros&middot; &thorn;is sawes seide:&mdash;</L>
<L>Heuene &yogh;ates&middot; weore closed clos<NOTE PLACE="marg">[crux respondit:]</NOTE></L>
<L N="268">Til &thorn;e lomb&middot; of loue dyede,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is write&middot; in tixt&middot; and glos:</L>
<L>Aftur Cristes de&thorn;&middot; prophetes preide:</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e lomb of loue&middot; dyed and ros</L>
<L N="272">In helle pyne&middot; monkynde was teyde:</L>
<L>At houre of his none;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lomb of loue&middot; seyde his &thorn;ou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>Nou is folfuld&middot; &thorn;at wel is wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="276">A Mon is out of bondes brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And heuene dores&middot; vndone:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXII.</HEAD>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e Fader&middot; &thorn;at al schal folfille,</L>
<L>His sone to heuene is an help,</L>
<L N="280">I&middot; was piler&middot; and stod ful stille:</L>
<L>After o&thorn;ur &yogh;iftes&middot; now gostes &yogh;elp,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend&middot; &thorn;at al &thorn;is world wolde kille,</L>
<L>His swerd he pulte vp&middot; in his kelp;</L>
<L N="284">To helle he horlede&middot; from &thorn;at hille,</L>
<L>Beerynge&middot; as a Beore whelp:</L>
<L>A beore is bounden&middot; and beted;</L>
<L>Cristes Cros&middot; ha&thorn; craked his croun,
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="141"></L>
<L N="288">&THORN;e lomb ha&thorn; leid&middot; &thorn;e Lyoun a-doun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lomb is lord&middot; in eueri toun,</L>
<L>So Cristes blod&middot; ha&thorn; pleted:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIII.</HEAD>
<L>In holy writ&middot; &thorn;is tale is herde,</L>
<L N="292">&THORN;at goode &yogh;iftes&middot; god vs &yogh;af;</L>
<L>God sei&thorn; him-self&middot; he is schepherde,</L>
<L>And vche an heerde&middot; bi-houe&thorn; a staf;<MILESTONE N="316b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Cros&middot; I&middot; calle&middot; &thorn;e heerdes &yogh;erde,</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;er-wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel&middot; a dunt he &yogh;af,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;erde&middot; &thorn;e wolf he werde,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; duntes&middot; drof him al to draf:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cros&middot; &thorn;is tale tolde;</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at he was staf&middot; in &thorn;e heerdes hond,</L>
<L>Whon schep breken&middot; out of heore bond,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wolf he wered&middot; out of lond</L>
<L>&THORN;at deuoured&middot; cristes folde:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIV.</HEAD>
<L N="304">&YOGH;it seide&middot; &thorn;e Meke Marie&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[respondit Maria.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Roode&middot; &thorn;ou reendest my Rose al red:</L>
<L>&THORN;reo Iewes coomen&middot; from Caluari</L>
<L>&THORN;at day&middot; &thorn;at Ihesu &thorn;oled ded,</L>
<L N="308">Alle &thorn;ei seiden&middot; &thorn;ei weore sori,</L>
<L>For-dolled&middot; in a drouknyng dred;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei tolden hem alle&middot; wherfore&middot; and whi</L>
<L>Heore hertes were colde&middot;, as lumpyng led;</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;e furste&middot; heore tale tolde;</L>
<L>Whon crist was knit&middot; with corde on a stok</L>
<L>His bodi bledde&middot; a-&yogh;ein &thorn;at blok,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw feet and hondes&middot; nayles gan knok,</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;en gan myn herte&middot; to colde&middot;:
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="142"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXV.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E Secounde seide nay&middot; not &thorn;at&middot;</L>
<L>&THORN;at dude serwe&middot; in-to myn herte schete;</L>
<L>But whon &thorn;e Roode ros&middot; and doun was squat,</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;e nayles&middot; renten him hondes and feete,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw-out his helm&middot; &thorn;e harde hat</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ornes&middot; in-to his flesch gan crepe,</L>
<L>His Ioyntes&middot; vn-Ioynet&middot; I&middot; tok good gat;</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;o weop I&middot; water&middot; and teres leete,</L>
<L>To care I&middot; was enclyned;</L>
<L>In cloddres of blod&middot; his her was clunge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e flesch was from&middot; &thorn;e bones swonge,</L>
<L N="328">Drui&yogh;e drinkeles&middot; was his tonge,</L>
<L>His lippes to clouen&middot; and chyned&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXVI.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E &thorn;ridde seide&middot; &thorn;is &thorn;ouhte me lest</L>
<L>Of &thorn;eose peynes&middot; and o&thorn;er mo,</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;is peyne &thorn;ouhte me&middot; peyne mest;</L>
<L>Al his flesch&middot; he let of flo,</L>
<L>His Mylde Moder&middot; stod him nest,</L>
<L>Loked vpward&middot; And hire was wo,</L>
<L N="336">A swerd swapped hire&middot; &thorn;orw &thorn;e brest:</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e cros&middot; &thorn;e knyf com &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;is siht sauh I&middot; my-selue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e swerd of loue&middot; &thorn;orw hire gan launce,</L>
<L N="340">Heo swapte on swownyng&middot; &thorn;orw &thorn;at chaunce;</L>
<L>To scornen hire&middot; &thorn;ei gan daunce,</L>
<L>Iewes&middot; bi ten&middot; and twelue&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXVII.</HEAD>
<L>Sin Iewes made&middot; so muchel mon,</L>
<L N="344">To seon my brid&middot;, bounden in brere,
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>In sad serwyng&middot; moste I&middot; gon&middot;</L>
<L>To seon blodi&middot; my chyldes chere:</L>
<L>Fadres&middot; and Modres&middot; &thorn;at walken in won</L>
<L N="348">Schul loue heore children&middot; beo skiles clere;</L>
<L>&THORN;eose two loues&middot; weore in me al-on,</L>
<L>For fader and moder&middot; I&middot; was here,</L>
<L>&THORN;eose two loues&middot; in me weore dalt;</L>
<L N="352">I&middot; was fader&middot; of his flesch,</L>
<L>His Moder hedde&middot; an herte nesch,</L>
<L>Mi serwe flowed&middot; as water fresch,</L>
<L>Weopyng&middot; and wo&middot; I&middot; walt:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXVIII.</HEAD>
<L N="356">IN me weore tacched&middot; sorwes two,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e fader&middot; mihte non a-byde,</L>
<L>For he was euere&middot; in reste and Ro,</L>
<L>Ioyned&middot; in his Ioyes wyde,</L>
<L N="360">I&middot; serwed sore&middot; for to sei so:</L>
<L>I&middot; say whon &thorn;at my derlyng dide,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; duntes&middot; he was to de&thorn;e i-do,</L>
<L>Vp-on a tre&middot; his bodi was soyled;</L>
<L N="364">Whon trou&thorn;e is told&middot; and darted;</L>
<L>Of alle Ioyes&middot; God is welle,</L>
<L>&THORN;er mihte no serwe&middot; in him dwelle,</L>
<L>I&middot; serwed sore&middot; as Clerkes telle,</L>
<L N="368">Mi pyne&middot; was not departed&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIX.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E hattore loue&middot; &thorn;e caldore care,</L>
<L>Whon frendes fynde&middot; heore fruit defoyled;</L>
<L>&THORN;e dispitous Iewes&middot; nolde not spare,</L>
<L N="372">Til trie fruit&middot; weore tore and toyled;</L>
<L>Neuer Mayden&middot; Mournede mare,<MILESTONE N="316b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I&middot; sauh my child&middot; ben surded and soyled,
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>Myn herte to-clef&middot; wi&thorn; swerd of care;</L>
<L N="376">I&middot; sau&yogh; my brid&middot; with blod bem-oyled<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>ben oyled</I>.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>As Symeon&middot; seide beo-forn;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swerd of serwe&middot;, scharp I&middot;-grounde,</L>
<L>Schulde &yogh;iue&middot; myn herte a wounde;</L>
<L N="380">In more wo&middot; &thorn;en I&middot; was bounde</L>
<L>Neuere buirde&middot; ha&thorn; born&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXX.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E dede&middot; wor&thorn;ily&middot; gan wake,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dai turned&middot; to nihtes donne,</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;e Merke Mone&middot; gan Mournyng make,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyht out leop&middot; of &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e temple walles&middot; gan chiuere&middot; and schake,</L>
<L>Veiles in &thorn;e temple&middot; a-two &thorn;ei sponne:</L>
<L N="388">Cros&middot; whi noldestou not crake,</L>
<L>Whon rihtful blod&middot; on &thorn;e was ronne,</L>
<L>And kuyndes&middot; losten heore kende;:</L>
<L>Whon my fruit&middot; on &thorn;e was fast,</L>
<L N="392">Cros&middot; whi weore &thorn;ou not a-gast?</L>
<L>&THORN;ow stod stif&middot; as eny mast,</L>
<L>Whon lyf&middot; left vp his ende&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXI.</HEAD>
<L>Whon &thorn;at Prince&middot; of Paradys</L>
<L N="396">Bledde&middot; bo&thorn;e brest&middot; and bak:</L>
<L>An he&thorn;ene clerk&middot; was seint Denys,</L>
<L>He seide&middot; &thorn;is world&middot; wente al to wrak,</L>
<L>He sau&yogh; &thorn;e planetes passen&middot; out of here pris,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;e brihte sonne&middot; gan waxen blak;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Clerk&middot; &thorn;at was so wonderly wys</L>
<L>Wonder wordes&middot; &thorn;er he spak,</L>
<L>Denys&middot; &thorn;is grete Clerk seide;</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;e day of doom&middot; drawe&thorn; to an ende,
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>Al vr kuyndes&middot; ha&thorn; lost vr kende;</L>
<L>Til God &thorn;at dyed&middot; for vch a kuynde</L>
<L>For Monnes kuynde deyde&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXII.</HEAD>
<L N="408">Foules fellen&middot; out of heore fliht,</L>
<L>Beestes gan Belwe&middot; in eueri binne:</L>
<L>Cros&middot; whon Crist&middot; on &thorn;e was cliht,</L>
<L>Whi noldestou not&middot; of mournyng minne?</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;e Cros seide&middot; ladi briht,</L>
<L>I&middot; bar ones &thorn;i fruit&middot; for monnes sinne,</L>
<L>More to amende&middot; monnes riht</L>
<L>&THORN;en for eny weol&thorn;e&middot; &thorn;at I&middot; gan winne;</L>
<L N="416">Wi&thorn; blod&middot; God bou&yogh;te his bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Whon Adam&middot; Godes biddyng brak;</L>
<L>He bot a bite&middot; &thorn;at made vs blak,</L>
<L>Til fruit weore tied&middot; on treo wi&thorn; tak&middot;,</L>
<L N="420">O&middot; fruit&middot; for ano&thorn;er&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXIII.</HEAD>
<L>Sin Cristes Cros&middot; &thorn;at kepe&thorn; &yogh;ifte</L>
<L>Graunted&middot; of &thorn;e fadres graunt,</L>
<L>I&middot; was loked&middot; I&middot; schulde vp-lifte</L>
<L N="424">Godes sone&middot; and maydenes faunt,</L>
<L>No Mon hedde&middot; scheld of schrifte;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel stod lyk&middot; A lyon raumpaunt,</L>
<L>Mony folk&middot; In-to helle he clihte,</L>
<L N="428">Til &thorn;e crosses dunt&middot; &yogh;af him a daunt;</L>
<L>Mi dedes are bounden&middot; and booked;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e werkes&middot; &thorn;at I&middot; haue wrouht</L>
<L>Weore founden&middot; in &thorn;e Faderes&middot; fore-&thorn;ouht,</L>
<L N="432">&THORN;erfore ladi&middot; lakke&thorn; me nouht,</L>
<L>I&middot; dude&middot; as me was looked:
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXIV.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;orw Blod&middot; and Watur&middot; cristendam was wrouht,</L>
<L>Holy writ&middot; witnesse&thorn; hit wel,</L>
<L N="436">And in wille&middot; of so&thorn;fast &thorn;ouht,</L>
<L>A Mon mai&middot; be cristened skil;</L>
<L>&THORN;at blod&middot; &thorn;at us alle bouht</L>
<L>Digne cristenyng&middot; gan vs del;</L>
<L N="440">At cristenyng&middot; crist for-&yogh;at vs nouht,</L>
<L>His blessede blod&middot; whon we gan fel:</L>
<L>Maiden&middot; Moder&middot; and Wyue;</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruit ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen vs baptem,</L>
<L N="444">Cristened we weore&middot; In Red rem,</L>
<L>Whon his bodi bledde&middot; on &thorn;e Beem,</L>
<L>Of Cipresse. and Olyue&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXV.</HEAD>
<L>AS Ihesu seide&middot; to Nichodemus</L>
<L N="448">"But a Barn&middot; be twy&yogh;es born,</L>
<L>Whon domus-day&middot; schal blowen his bemus,</L>
<L>He may elles liggen&middot; loddere for-lorn,</L>
<L>Furst of a wombe&middot;, &thorn;er reu&thorn;e remus,</L>
<L N="452">Si&thorn;&thorn;e in a font&middot;, &thorn;er synne awey is schorn":</L>
<L>I&middot; was cros&middot; to monnes quemus,</L>
<L>I&middot; bar &thorn;e fruit&middot; &thorn;ow bar bi-forn,<MILESTONE N="316b:3" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;i beryng&middot; Al-one;</L>
<L N="456">But &yogh;if I&middot; hedde&middot; I&middot;-boren him eft,</L>
<L>From riche reste&middot; mon hedde beo-reft</L>
<L>In a loren logge&middot; I&middot;-left&middot;,</L>
<L>Ay&middot; to grunte&middot; and grone&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXVI.</HEAD>
<L N="460">&THORN;ou art I&middot;-Crouned&middot; heuene quene,</L>
<L>&THORN;orw &thorn;e bur&thorn;e&middot; &thorn;at &thorn;ou beere,
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>&THORN;i garlond is al&middot; of graces grene,</L>
<L>Helle Emperesse&middot; in heuene Empere:</L>
<L N="464">I&middot; am a Relyk&middot; &thorn;at shine&thorn; shene,</L>
<L>Men wolde wite&middot; wher &thorn;at I&middot; were,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e parlement&middot; wol I&middot; bene,</L>
<L>On domes-day&middot; prestly a-pere;</L>
<L N="468">Whon Ihesu schal seye&middot; riht &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>"Trewely&middot; vppon &thorn;e Roode tre</L>
<L>Mon&middot; I dyede for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Mon what hastou&middot; don for me&middot;</L>
<L N="472">To beon&middot; my frendly feere&middot;?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXVII.</HEAD>
<L>At &thorn;e parlement&middot; shul puiten vp pleynyng,</L>
<L>Hou Maydenes fruit&middot; on me gan sterue,</L>
<L>Spere&middot; and spounge&middot; and sharp nayling,</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;orw &thorn;e harde hat&middot; &thorn;e heued shal kerue,</L>
<L>Shul preie&middot; to &thorn;at rihtful kyng:</L>
<L>Vche mon schal haue&middot; as &thorn;ei a serue,</L>
<L>Rihtful schul ryse&middot; to riche restyng,</L>
<L N="480">Truyt&middot; and tripet&middot; to helle shal sterue:</L>
<L>Mayden Meoke and Mylde;</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; taken in &thorn;e&middot; his fleschly trene</L>
<L>I&middot; bar &thorn;i fruit&middot; leo&thorn;i and lene;</L>
<L N="484">Hit is riht &thorn;e Roode&middot; helpe to a-rene</L>
<L>Wrecches&middot; &thorn;at wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;i chylde&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXVIII.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E queen a-cordet&middot; wi&thorn; &thorn;e cros</L>
<L>And a-&yogh;eyn him spak&middot; no more speche;</L>
<L N="488">&THORN;e queen &yogh;af&middot; &thorn;e Cros a cos,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ladi of loue&middot; loue gan seche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei&yogh; hire fruit&middot; on him were&middot; di&yogh;t to dros,</L>
<L>Whon rendyng ropus&middot; gan him reche:
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="148"></L>
<L N="492">Cristes cros&middot; ha&thorn; kept vs from los,</L>
<L>Maries preyers&middot; And God vr leche,</L>
<L>&THORN;e qween&middot; and &thorn;e Cros&middot; a corde:</L>
<L>&THORN;e qween bar furst&middot; &thorn;e cros afturward,</L>
<L N="496">To fecche folk&middot; from helleward,</L>
<L>On holy stayers&middot; to steyen vpward</L>
<L>And regne&middot; wi&thorn; God vr lorde&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXIX.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;E Clerk&middot; &thorn;at fourmed&middot; &thorn;is figour</L>
<L N="500">Of Maries wo&middot; to wite som,</L>
<L>He saih him-self&middot; &thorn;at harde stour,</L>
<L>Whon godes Armus&middot; weore rent aroum;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cros is a cold&middot; Creatour,</L>
<L N="504">And euere &yogh;it ha&thorn; ben&middot; def&middot; and dom,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei&yogh; &thorn;is tale beo florisshed&middot; with faire flour,</L>
<L>I&middot; preue hit&middot; on Apocrafum;</L>
<L>For witnesse&middot; was neuer foundet;</L>
<L N="508">&THORN;at neuere cristes cros spak,</L>
<L>Oure ladi leide&middot; on him no lak,</L>
<L>Bot to pulte&middot; &thorn;e deuel a-bak,</L>
<L>We speke&middot; hou crist was woundet&middot;:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XL.</HEAD>
<L N="512">IN Flesshly wede</L>
<L>God gan him hede,</L>
<L>Of Mylde May</L>
<L>Was bore to blede,</L>
<L N="516">As Cristes Crede</L>
<L>So&thorn;ly wol say;</L>
<L>On a stokky stede</L>
<L>He Rod&middot; we Rede,</L>
<L N="520">In Red Array;</L>
<L>From deueles drede
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Duyk vs lede,</L>
<L>At domes-day:</L>
<L N="524">Whon peple&middot; schal parte&middot; and pace;</L>
<L>To heuene halle&middot; or to helle woode,</L>
<L>Cristes cros&middot; and cristes blode</L>
<L>And Marie preiers&middot;, &thorn;at ben ful goode,</L>
<L N="528">Grant vs &thorn;e lyf&middot; of grace&middot; Amen.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit disputacio inter Mariam et Crucem. Secundum Apocrafum.</TRAILER>


</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000182.tif" N="[150]">
<HEAD>IX.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>[WITH AN <I>O</I> AND AN <I>I</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Douce MS. 126,<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio">.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>Godys sone &thorn;at was so fre,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;is world he cam,</L>
<L>And let hym naylyn vp-on a tre,</L>
<L N="4">Al for &thorn;e loue of man;</L>
<L>His fayre blod &thorn;at was so fre,</L>
<L>Out of his body it ran,</L>
<L>A dwelful sy&yogh;te it was to se;</L>
<L N="8">His body heng blak and wan,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an O and an I.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>His coroune was mad of &thorn;orn</L>
<L>And prikkede in-to his panne,</L>
<L N="12">Bo&thorn;e by hynde and a forn;</L>
<L>To a piler y-bowndyn</L>
<L>Ihesu was swi&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>And suffrede many a wownde</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at scharp and betere wore.</L>
<L>He hadde vs euere in mynde,</L>
<L>In al his harde &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>And we ben so vnkynde,</L>
<L N="20">We nelyn hym nat yknowe,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an O and an I.
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="151"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>But-&yogh;if we loue hym trewe,</L>
<L>Houre peynys ben in helle,</L>
<L N="24">&YOGH;arkyd euere newe;</L>
<L>Who so wele loue trewe</L>
<L>Byhold ihesu on &thorn;e croys,</L>
<L>How he heng pale of hewe,</L>
<L N="28">And cryde wi&thorn; mylde voys.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;risti&thorn; he gan to kalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewis herdyn &thorn;ys,</L>
<L>Eysel meynt wi&thorn; galle</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;ey bedyn hym y-wys,</L>
<L>With an O and an I.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<L>His &thorn;rist was to sey&yogh;e</L>
<L>For loue of manys soule,</L>
<L N="36">Hym longede for to dey&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Who so be proud in herte</L>
<L>&THORN;ynk on god al-my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And on his wowndys smerte,</L>
<L N="40">How rewly he was a-dy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Godys sone in trone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hey&yogh;est is of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Tok batayle a-lone</L>
<L N="44">For oure loue to fy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>With an O and an I.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>V.</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e batayle was so stronge,</L>
<L>At many a betyr wownde.</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;e ryche blod out spronge:</L>
<L>Trewe turtyl corounyd on hylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hey&yogh;est art of kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;y loue chaungy&thorn; my wille,
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="152"></L>
<L N="52">Whan &thorn;ou comyst in my mynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fend I forsake anon,</L>
<L>For on lady so hende;<MILESTONE N="91" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To seruyn &thorn;e lady &thorn;an wil I gon,</L>
<L N="56">For &yogh;he is of my kende,</L>
<L>With an O And an I.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VI.</HEAD>
<L>Ich am on of &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;y sone bou&yogh;te dere,</L>
<L N="60">He schal me nat for-go.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>A M E N .</TRAILER>


</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000185.tif" N="[153]">
<HEAD>X.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>[WITH AN <I>O</I> FOR AN <I>I</I><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Douce MS. 128,<MILESTONE N="258" UNIT="folio">.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;ou for holy churche ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Bare &thorn;e blody face,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e y praye, bo&thorn;e day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4">Of ioye sende me a space.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an O. for and an I. a space for to a-byde,</L>
<L>Thu bere myn arnde to &thorn;at lord. &thorn;at bare &thorn;e blody syde.</L>
<L>&para; Ihesu kyng in trone,</L>
<L N="8">Lord in magest&eacute;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e y make my mone</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; herte good and fre.</L>
<L>Frendes haue y none</L>
<L N="12">That wolde me knowe ne se,</L>
<L>My wonynge ys allone,</L>
<L>Lord wel wo ys me!</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; an O. and an I. My wonynge is wel wykke,</L>
