<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Manus depillans et alapans.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The hond, lord, &thorn;at tare of &thorn;yn here,</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;e honde &thorn;at flapped under &thorn;in here&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at pine be my socour there</L>
<L>That y haue y-sinwed with myn<NOTE PLACE="foot">with myn <I>is in a later hand</I>.</NOTE> here,</L>
<L>And of alle o&thorn;ur synne al so</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at wi&thorn; myn eren haue y herkened to.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">From MS. 11,748.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000210.tif" N="178">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Velamen ante oculos.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e cloth be-fore &thorn;in ine to,</L>
<L>To bobbe<NOTE PLACE="foot">bobby.</NOTE> &thorn;e &thorn;ey knyt it so,</L>
<L>Hit kepe me from<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro eche.</NOTE> ueniauns</L>
<L N="56">Of childhod and of ignorauns,</L>
<L>And of other<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle.</NOTE> sinnus also</L>
<L>&THORN;at i haue with my ine do,</L>
<L>And with<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn; my.</NOTE> nose smellud eke,</L>
<L N="60">Bo&thorn;e ho[le] and eke<NOTE PLACE="foot">also.</NOTE> seke.<MILESTONE N="75" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Tunica inconsutilis et uestis purpuria.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e whit cote &thorn;at hade sem none</L>
<L>And &thorn;e purpure &thorn;ey layd both upon one<NOTE PLACE="foot">laid loot up one.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey be my sokur and my helping,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at my bodi hat&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ther y haue.</NOTE> usud soft clo&yogh;ing.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000212.tif" N="180">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Virge et flagelle.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>With &yogh;erdes grete &thorn;ow were to-dachud,</L>
<L>With scourges smert al to-lachud,</L>
<L>&THORN;at peine me soker<NOTE PLACE="foot">be my socour.</NOTE> of sinnus<NOTE PLACE="foot">synne &thorn;is.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="68">Of slouth and of idelnes.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Corona spinea.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e coroune of &thorn;orn on &thorn;in hed &thorn;rast,<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;in her to-tar, &thorn;i skyn to-brast;</L>
<L>Schild<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at schild.</NOTE> me from pein of helle pit,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at i haue deseruud &thorn;orow uan-wite<NOTE PLACE="foot">wane-wit.</NOTE>.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Columpna cum corda.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To &thorn;e piler, lord, al so</L>
<L>With a rop &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">men.</NOTE> boundun &thorn;e to;</L>
<L>&THORN;e senewes from &thorn;e bones brast,</L>
<L N="76">So hard hit was draw and strened fast;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bond me alese of bondes,</L>
<L>Of unkind dede and unkindnes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Harde &thorn;ay drowe <I>and</I> stryned faste;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;enewys fro &thorn;e bonys to-barst.</L>
<L>&THORN;at bond alese me and vnbynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y haue trespassed <I>and</I> be vnkynde. The words "and vnbynde" and the next line are in paler ink.</L>
</LG></NOTE>.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000214.tif" N="182">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Uestigia saluatoris, quando exiuit per portam ierusalem, portando crucem, coronam spineam <MILESTONE N="76" UNIT="folio"> coronatus, mille passus sic incedens, roseum cruorem distillando.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ow bere &thorn;e cros and toke &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="80">Out at ierusalemus &yogh;ate;</L>
<L>&THORN;in foot-steppus suet and gode</L>
<L>Wer sene &thorn;orow schedi[n]g of &thorn;i blod.</L>
<L>&THORN;er mettust &thorn;ow with wymmen of bedlem,</L>
<L N="84">And al so with wymmen of ierusalem,</L>
<L>And alle<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>omitted.</I></NOTE> &thorn;ey wepten for &thorn;i turment;</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;ow seydust apertment,</L>
<L>"Ne wepe &yogh;e not for my wo,</L>
<L N="88">But for &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ow.</NOTE> self and &yogh;oure childurne also;</L>
<L>For hem &yogh;e moun ful sore wepe,</L>
<L>And salt teres for hem lete,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey schul haue turment hard</L>
<L N="92">An hundert wintur her afterwart."</L>
<L>&THORN;o steppus of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al &thorn;ay stappis of oure.</NOTE> sine &yogh;if us pardoun,</L>
<L>Wen we gon with<NOTE PLACE="foot">we gooth wi&thorn; good.</NOTE> deuociun</L>
<L>On<NOTE PLACE="foot">A.</NOTE> pilgremage on hors or fote;</L>
<L N="96">Of alle oure sinnus<NOTE PLACE="foot">sorwe</NOTE> &thorn;ey ben our bote.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000216.tif" N="184">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Claui.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e nayles &thorn;orow fet and handus to&mdash;<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ey helpe me out of sinne and wo</L>
<L>&THORN;at i haue in my liue do,</L>
<L N="100">With handus handult, with fet i-go.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Malleus.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e hamur bothe sterne and gret</L>
<L>&THORN;at drof &thorn;e nayles &thorn;orow hond and<NOTE PLACE="foot">nayles in cristis.</NOTE> fete</L>
<L>&THORN;ey<NOTE PLACE="foot">hit.</NOTE> be my socur<NOTE PLACE="foot">socour &thorn;at.</NOTE> in my lyf,</L>
<L N="104">&YOGH;if i<NOTE PLACE="foot">y eny.</NOTE> man smot with staf or knyf.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Uas cum felle.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e uescel with eysel and with galle<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Kep me from &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>omitted.</I></NOTE> sinnus alle,
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e soul is fowl uenim,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at i be not pusond &thorn;er-ine<NOTE PLACE="foot">that men be nou&yogh;t y-combred &thorn;er-yn.</NOTE>.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Spongea.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ow thurstudust sor with-alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey &yogh;eufe &thorn;e eysel medult with galle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at i haue dronken in glotonie,</L>
<L N="112">Hit saue me wen i schal diee,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, lord, now i pray to &thorn;e</L>
<L>For &thorn;at greuauns &thorn;ow suferdst for me<NOTE PLACE="foot">ll. 113, 114 <I>omitted.</I></NOTE>.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Lancea.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, &thorn;e scharp spere i-ground<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at in &thorn;in herd mad a wonde,</L>
<L>Hit kuench &thorn;e sine<NOTE PLACE="foot">synnes.</NOTE> &thorn;at i haue wrogt,</L>
<L>With al myn hert euel i-&thorn;owt,</L>
<L>And of my stout prid &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="120">And myn unbuxumnes al-so.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Scala.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e laddur upset be enchesoun</L>
<L>Wen &thorn;ow wer ded be take adoun<NOTE PLACE="foot">to take &thorn;e doun; <I>originally</I>, by take a-doun.</NOTE>,
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>Wen i ham ded in<NOTE PLACE="foot">on.</NOTE> ani sinne</L>
<L N="124">Take me &thorn;at i ne die &thorn;er-ine.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Forceps.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e tonges &thorn;at drow &thorn;e nayles out,</L>
<L>Of fet, of handes, al about,</L>
<L>And louset his<NOTE PLACE="foot">loosed &thorn;i.</NOTE> bodi from &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L N="128">Of alle my sinnus &thorn;ey lese<NOTE PLACE="foot">loose.</NOTE> me.<MILESTONE N="78" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Iudeus spuens in facie christi.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e iewe &thorn;at spit<NOTE PLACE="foot">spathe.</NOTE> in goddus face&mdash;</L>
<L>For he hit suffurd, he &yogh;yf us<NOTE PLACE="foot">me.</NOTE> grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haue reuilud or ani man me,</L>
<L N="132">For &thorn;at despit for-&yogh;yf it be.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000222.tif" N="190">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Christus portans crucem in humero.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e cros be-hind his bak-bon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;olud deth uppon&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me grace in my liue</L>
<L N="136">Clene of sine me to schriue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto uerey<NOTE PLACE="foot">al-so.</NOTE> repentauns,</L>
<L>And here to fulfille my penauns.</L>
</LG>
</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Sepulcrum christi.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e sepulcur &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">that he.</NOTE> &thorn;erinne was layde<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="140">His blessud bodi al be-bled<NOTE PLACE="foot">for-bleed.</NOTE>&mdash;
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>He me send, or &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>omitted.</I></NOTE> i deye,</L>
<L>Sorow of hert and ter of ye,</L>
<L>Cler and<NOTE PLACE="foot">Clene.</NOTE> clensud &thorn;at i be,</L>
<L N="144">Or i to my graue tee;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at i mow<NOTE PLACE="foot">mote.</NOTE> on domus day</L>
<L>To &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">thi.</NOTE> dom cum with-out dedli<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>omitted.</I></NOTE> fray</L>
<L>And wend to<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;e.</NOTE> blis in<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn;.</NOTE> cumpanie,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ei.</NOTE> os<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at.</NOTE> men schul<NOTE PLACE="foot">schal.</NOTE> neuer dye,</L>
<L>But dwelle in ioy wit oure lord ri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn; ou&yogh;te dri&yogh;t, <I>read</I> oure Dri&yogh;t.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is euer day and neuer ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at last schal with-outen ende;</L>
<L N="152">Now iesu crist [us]<NOTE PLACE="foot">ous.</NOTE> &thorn;idur send<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>MS. 11,748 adds two lines:&mdash;</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iesu, &thorn;at deidest one &thorn;e rode tree,</L>
<L>Graunte ous &thorn;is for charite. Amen.</L>
</LG><P>Then follows at once:&mdash;</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>These armes of crist bothe god <I>and</I> man</L>
<L>Seint peter discriued ham.</L>
<L>What man &thorn;es armes ouer-&yogh;aith</L>
<L>And for hure synnes sory and schriue beeth</L>
<L>To seye hit a twelfe monthe eche day wi&thorn; good chere</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; sixe thowsaund <I>and</I> seuen hundred and fiue and fifty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>And half a &yogh;ere <I>and</I> dayes thre</L>
<L>This is y-grauntyd for to be</L>
<L><I>And</I> for the vernicle haue he may</L>
<L>Fourty dayes eueryche day</L>
<L>And for the pytye with good chere</L>
<L>Grauntyd is sextene thowsaund &yogh;ere</L>
<L><I>And</I> sixe [an] thirty dayes &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>For to segge euery day A pater noster <I>and</I> v. Aue maria wi&thorn; o Crede.</L>
</LG></NOTE>. amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV4>
<DIV4 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000226.tif" N="194">
<P><FIGURE>
<HEAD>Graciarum acciones iesu christo stanti in sepulcro.</HEAD>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> &thorn;ank &thorn;e, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ow me wrout,<MILESTONE N="79" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with strong peynus &thorn;ow me bout;</L>
<L>I &thorn;ank &thorn;e, lord, with ruful entent</L>
<L N="156">Of &thorn;i peynus and &thorn;i turment,</L>
<L>With carful hert and dreri mod,</L>
<L>For schedynd of &thorn;i swet blod.</L>
<L>What may i say &thorn;ow hast done for me?</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;i bodi was bonden to a tre,</L>
<L>With scourges knit &thorn;e knottis<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. knoctis.</NOTE> grete</L>
<L>&THORN;i blessud bodi was al for-bete,</L>
<L>On eueri side turnud and torne,</L>
<L N="164">Also naked as &thorn;ow were borne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hol sted was found none</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e croun to &thorn;e ton.</L>
<L>&THORN;i blessud bodi &thorn;er hit stod,<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="168">Al hit was be-helet in blod;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ow were so for-swong,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e iues &thorn;ey did &thorn;e hong,</L>
<L>With scharp naylus &thorn;orow hand and fet</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;ey let &thorn;e hong til &thorn;ow wer ded;</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;i deth, to us sote,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey pittun a spere to &thorn;in hert rote;
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wiked iwes with sturdi mode</L>
<L N="176">Let &thorn;er-out strem &thorn;in hert blod.</L>
<L>Alas! lord, &thorn;i penus &thorn;ow tholudust &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Oure sinnus hit mad so wellawo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ese instrumentus &thorn;at here pertend<NOTE PLACE="marg">Read purtraid.</NOTE> be&thorn;</L>
<L N="180">In memori of &thorn;i bittur deyt,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey hulpun hem to do &thorn;i passioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey help us to oure sauacioun;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey greuet &thorn;e ful sore,</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;in anguich wex so lenger &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>Lord, what may i for &thorn;at &yogh;ylde &thorn;e?</L>
<L>&THORN;ow desirdust no&yogh;t but loue of me.</L>
<L>Lord, &thorn;ow &yogh;if me grace and my&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="80" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="188">With al min hert to loue &thorn;e ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>In lyf and deth, in wele and wo,</L>
<L>Let neuur min hert turne &thorn;e fro,</L>
<L>And or hit so be for thing unwrest</L>
<L N="192">For loue let, lord, min hert brest;</L>
<L>In a blessud tym &thorn;en was I bore,</L>
<L>When al my loue to &thorn;e is core.</L>
<L>But merci, lord, i &thorn;e prey,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;ow let me neuer in sine dye,</L>
<L>Werethorow i schuld dampned be;</L>
<L>Derworth lord, for &thorn;i pit&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;is graunt me, lord, i prey to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="200">For mari loue &thorn;i moder fre. amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ese armus of crist bo&thorn; god and man,</L>
<L>Sent petur &thorn;e pop discriuet hem.</L>
<L>Wat man &thorn;is armes ouer-se,</L>
<L N="204">For his sinnus sori and schereuen be,</L>
<L>&THORN;re &yogh;er of pardon is &thorn;e summe</L>
<L>Of sent petrus grant, furst pope of rome;</L>
<L>And xxx popes aftur him &thorn;at were,<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="208">An C dayus ich yauf with gode chere;
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>xxxviii bichoppus eke also,</L>
<L>Ich grant bi him self xl dayus &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>Pope innocent mad a gret counsail</L>
<L N="212">And al &thorn;is confermed with-outen fayl,</L>
<L>And more pardon &yogh;af also,</L>
<L>iiii &yogh;ere ii C dayus &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>And ich bischop sayd to-for-hand</L>
<L N="216">For sy&yogh;t of &thorn;e uernacul hath graunt</L>
<L>xl dayus to pardon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-with-al her benisun.</L>
<L>And also who &thorn;at eueri day</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;is armus of crist be-hold may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at day he ne sal dee no wiked ded</L>
<L>Ne be cumbert with &thorn;e kued;</L>
<L>And also to wymen hit is meke and mild,</L>
<L N="224">When &thorn;ey trauelne of her chi[l]d.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soum of wekeus to se hit ich day</L>
<L>A. C. and xix and half get &thorn;ow may,</L>
<L>To sen it ich day in &thorn;e mone&thorn; also<MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="228">V. C. &yogh;er and xviii and xii wokes &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>To sen it a twelf-moneth ich day enter</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; vi. M<SUP>o</SUP>. vii. C. v. and fifti &yogh;ere</L>
<L>And half &yogh;ere and dayes &thorn;re</L>
<L N="232">Of pardon, &thorn;us popus ha&thorn; graunted &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>


</DIV4>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000203.tif" N="[171]">
<HEAD>XIII.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>THE SYMBOLS OF THE PASSION<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Additional MS. 22,029.]</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The vernacul&mdash;I honowre hym [and the]</L>
<L>&THORN;at the made throwe hys pryuy[t&eacute;];</L>
<L>The clothe he set ovyr hys face,</L>
<L N="4">The prynte he lefte ther, of hys grace,</L>
<L>Hys mowthe, hys nose, hys eyn too,</L>
<L>Hys berd, hys here he ded also.</L>
<L>Schyld me, lorde, for &thorn;at in myn lyffe</L>
<L N="8">That I haue synnyd with myn wyttys fyve,</L>
<L>Namelyche with mowthe of stlawndrynge,</L>
<L>Of fals othys and bakbytynge,
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>And makyng boste with tonge alsoo</L>
<L N="12">Of many synnys that I haue doo:</L>
<L>Lorde of heuyn, for-zeue it me</L>
<L>Throwe vertew of the fygure &thorn;at I here se.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thys knyffe betoknythe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> circumsysy[on],</L>
<L N="16">That dystroyd owre synnys alle and sum</L>
<L>Of owre formfathyr adam,</L>
<L>Wher-thorowe we toke &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> kynde of man.</L>
<L>From temptacyon of lecherye,</L>
<L N="20">Lorde, kepe me tylle that I deye.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The pelycan hys blode dothe blede</L>
<L>&THORN;er-with hys byrdys for to fede,</L>
<L>It betoknythe vppe-on the rode</L>
<L N="24">Owre lorde fed vs with hys precius blode,</L>
<L>Whan [h]e vs bowt owt of helle</L>
<L>In ioye and blys with hym to dwelle,</L>
<L>And be owre fathyr and owre fode,</L>
<L N="28">And we hys chyldyr meke and good.
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="175"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The pens also that Iudas tolde,</L>
<L>Wher-for iesu cryste was solde&mdash;</L>
<L>Lorde, schylde me from treson and couetyse,</L>
<L N="32">Ther-in that I deye in no wyse.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The lantern &thorn;at they bare in the lygthe,</L>
<L>Whan cryste was takyn with-in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> nygthe&mdash;</L>
<L>Lord, kepe me from nygthys synne,</L>
<L N="36">That I neuyr be take ther-In.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swerdys and stauys that &thorn;<SUP>ei</SUP> bere</L>
<L>Ther iesu cryste to fere with there&mdash;</L>
<L>From fendys, lorde, kepe thow me,</L>
<L N="40">Of them, lorde, a-ferd that I not be.
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="177"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Uythe a zarde he had a stroke,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-with the iewys hys hede they broke;</L>
<L>With good chere and myld mode,</L>
<L N="44">Alle he suffyrd and stylle he stode.</L>
<L>Whan I mys-do ar ony man do me,</L>
<L>It be for-zeve for that pet&eacute;.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The handys, lorde, &thorn;at tare of thyn here,</L>
<L N="48">And &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> hande &thorn;at clappyd the vndyr &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ere&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at peyn, lorde, be myn socowre there</L>
<L>That I haue synnyd with pryde of here,</L>
<L>And alle othyr synnys also</L>
<L N="52">That with erys I haue herkynd to.
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="179"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The clothe be-forn thyn eyn too,</L>
<L>To bobbyn the they knyt it soo&mdash;</L>
<L>Lord, kepe me from vengawns</L>
<L N="56">Of chyldhode and of ignorawns,</L>
<L>And eke synnys also</L>
<L>That I haue sene with myn eyn too,</L>
<L>And with myn nose smyllyd eke,</L>
<L N="60">Bothe olde and seke.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thyn own cote that had seme non,</L>
<L>The purpylle &thorn;at they leyd lotte vppe-on&mdash;</L>
<L>Lorde, be myn socowre and myn helppyng</L>
<L N="64">That myn bodye hathe vsyd mys clothyng.
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="181"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Uythe zardys grete &thorn;ou ware alle to-daschyd,</L>
<L>With scorgys smerte alle to-laschyd;</L>
<L>Lord, socowre me of synnys thys,</L>
<L N="68">Of stlowthe and eke of ydylnes.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The crown of thorn on &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> hed preste,</L>
<L>Thyn here to-tere, thy skyn to-breste.</L>
<L>Lord, socowre me of synnys thys,</L>
<L N="72">Of stlowthe and eke of Idylnes.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> pyller, lorde, also,</L>
<L>With a rope men bownd &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> too,</L>
<L>Hard drawe and streynyd faste;</L>
<L N="76">The senews from &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> bondys braste.</L>
<L>Lorde, lose me of bondys in dystresse,</L>
<L>Thowe I ded onkend a-geyns kyndnesse.
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thowe bare the cros ouyr the lake,</L>
<L N="80">Owt of iherusalem at the gate;</L>
<L>Thy fote-steppys swete and good</L>
<L>Wer sene throwe schedyng of &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> precyus blode.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mettyst with women of bethleem,</L>
<L N="84">And also women of iherusalem;</L>
<L>Alle they wepyd for &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> torment;</L>
<L>To them &thorn;ou seyddyst a-perte-ment,</L>
<L>"Wepe ze not for myn woo,</L>
<L N="88">But for zowre childyr also;</L>
<L>For them ze maye sore wepe,</L>
<L>And salte terys for them lete;</L>
<L>For they schal haue torment hard</L>
<L N="92">An hundyrd wyntyr here-aftyrwa[r]d."</L>
<L>Tho steppys for vs of grace zeue pardon,</L>
<L>Whan we goo, wythe deuocyon,</L>
<L>On pylgrymage on hors ar on fote.</L>
<L N="96">Of myn synnys, lorde, be myn bote.
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="185"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The naylys throwe fete and handys also,</L>
<L>Lorde, kepe me owt of synne and woo,</L>
<L>That I haue in myn lyffe doo,</L>
<L N="100">With handys handyld or on fote goo.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The hamyr bothe stern and grete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at droffe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> naylys throw hand and fote,</L>
<L>Lord, be myn socowr in alle myn lyffe,</L>
<L N="104">Iffe ony man stryke me with staffe or knyffe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lines 101-104 follow line 124 in the MS.</NOTE>.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The vessel of aysylle and of galle,</L>
<L>Lord, kepe me from &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> synnys alle,
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>That to sowle ben venym,</L>
<L N="108">That I be not poysynd ther-in.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan &thorn;ou thrystyd sore with-alle,</L>
<L>They gaffe the eysyll with byttyr galle;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at I haue dronke in glotenye</L>
<L N="112">For-geue me, lorde, ar than I deye.</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, the spere so scharpe I-grownde,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at in thyn herte made a wownde,</L>
<L>It quenchyth the synne &thorn;at I haue wrowt,</L>
<L>With alle myn harte fulle ewle thowt,</L>
<L>And myn stowt pryd also,</L>
<L N="120">And myn onbuxumnes ther-too.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The ledder, vppe-set be encheson</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou war ded to be take a-down,
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at I am In synne,</L>
<L N="124">Lord, lete me not dey ther-in.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The pensynnys, &thorn;at drewe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> naylys owt</L>
<L>Of fete and handys, alle a-bowt,</L>
<L>And losyd &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> bodye from &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tre,</L>
<L N="128">Of myn synnys, lord, lose &thorn;ou me.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The iewys &thorn;at spytte, lorde, in thy face</L>
<L>Ze suffyrd alle, and gaffe them grace;</L>
<L>That I haue gylte or ony man me,</L>
<L N="132">It be for-zeue for &thorn;at pet&eacute;.
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="191"></L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The cros be-hynd &thorn;<SUP>i</SUP> bakke-bon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou suffyrd dethe vppe-on&mdash;</L>
<L>Lord, geue me grace, in my lyue,</L>
<L N="136">Clene of synne me to schryue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to very repentawns</L>
<L>With spas to performe myn penawns.</L>
</LG>
<P><FIGURE>
</FIGURE></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The sepulkyr wher-in &thorn;ou war hyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;i blyssyd bodye alle for-bled&mdash;
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>Lord, grawnt me, ar &thorn;at I deye,</L>
<L>Sorowe of herte with terys of eye,</L>
<L>Clene clensyd for thy mercye,</L>
<L N="144">Er &thorn;at I in myn graue lye,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at I may at domys daye</L>
<L>To &thorn;at dome cum with-owt fraye,</L>
<L>And wend to blysse in cumpany,</L>
<L N="148">Ther as men schalle neuyr dye,</L>
<L>But dwelle In blysse with &thorn;at lord brygthe,</L>
<L>Wher euyr is day but neuyr nygthe,</L>
<L>And lest schal with-owt ende:</L>
<L N="152">Iesus cryste vs thedyr send!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="appendix"><PB REF="00000229.tif" N="[197]">
<HEAD>APPENDIX.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>DISPUTE BETWEEN MARY AND THE CROSS.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>I<NOTE PLACE="foot">The numbers are those of the corresponding stanzas in the text, pp. 131-149, the order being somewhat different.</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<L><B>O</B> litel whyle lestene&thorn; to me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Royal MS. 18 A 10,<MILESTONE N="126b" UNIT="folio">]</NOTE></L>
<L>Ententyfly, so haue &yogh;e blys,</L>
<L>Gode ensaumple here schul &yogh;e,</L>
<L N="4">Of noble Mater wrou&yogh;t it is,</L>
<L>How Mary spak to &thorn;e rode tre,</L>
<L>Whan her sone was in angvys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cros answeryd &thorn;at lady fre,</L>
<L N="8">Ful myldely sei&yogh;e clerkys wys,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at &thorn;is tale haue made cou&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei haue expouned it by si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A good ensaumple and a bry&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="12">But Apocrifum &thorn;ei holde it ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For tre spak neuere wi&thorn; mou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Oure lady fre,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e rode tre,</L>
<L N="16">Sche made her mone,</L>
<L>And seyde, "on &thorn;ee</L>
<L>Is fruyt of me</L>
<L>Full wo-bygone:</L>
<L N="20">With blody ble</L>
<L>My fruyt I gan see,
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>Among hys fone:</L>
<L>Of Sorewe I see,</L>
<L N="24">Hys veynes fle</L>
<L>Fro blody bone:</L>
<L>&para; Tre, &thorn;ou dost no treu&thorn;e,</L>
<L>On pilory my fruyt to pynne,</L>
<L N="28">He ha&thorn; no spot of Adam synne,</L>
<L>Flessche and veynes fle atwynne,</L>
<L>Wherfore I rede of reu&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Cros, &thorn;i bondes schul be blamed,</L>
<L N="32">My gode fruyt &thorn;ou hast bigyled;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fruytes modir was neuer famed,</L>
<L>My wombe is faire founde vnfyle[d]:</L>
<L>Child, why art &thorn;ou no&yogh;t aschamed</L>
<L N="36">On pilory to be I-pyled,</L>
<L>As grete &thorn;euys &thorn;at were gramed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deyeden &thorn;orou&yogh; her werkis wylde?</L>
<L>&para; Blode from hede is hayled,</L>
<L N="40">All to-fowled is my faire fruyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer dyd treget ne truyte</L>
<L>With &thorn;euys &thorn;at loue ryot vnri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Why schal my sone be nayled?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<L N="44">&para; &THORN;e grete &thorn;evys galowes were greyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere to robbe ronnen ryfe;</L>
<L>Why schal my sone &thorn;er-on be leyde?</L>
<L>He noy&yogh;ed neuer man ne wyfe.</L>
<L N="48">A drynk of dee&thorn; so&thorn;ely seyde,</L>
<L>Cros, &thorn;ou &yogh;euyst<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>&yogh;euyf.</I></NOTE> &thorn;e lord of lyfe:</L>
<L>Hys veynes breke with &thorn;i breyde,</L>
<L>My fruyte stont in stroke and stryfe:
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="199"></L>
<L N="52">&para; The faire fruyte of my flessche,<MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My leue childe with-oute lak,</L>
<L>For Adam goddis biddyng brak;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blood ran on my briddes bak,</L>
<L N="56">Droppynge as dewe on ryssche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; The Iugement haue &thorn;ei Ioyned</L>
<L>To bere fooles full of synne:</L>
<L>&YOGH;it scholde my sone fro &thorn;ee be soyned,</L>
<L N="60">And neuer hys blood on &thorn;e rynne;</L>
<L>But now is tru&thorn;e with tresoun twyned,</L>
<L>With a &thorn;eef to henge fer in fenne;</L>
<L>With fele nayles hys feet be pyned,</L>
<L N="64">A careful modir men may me kenne,</L>
<L>&para; In balys I am bounde:</L>
<L>&THORN;e brid &thorn;at was of a mayde borne,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is tree is all for-torne;</L>
<L N="68">A broche &thorn;orow hys breest was borne,</L>
<L>Hys hert now ha&thorn; a wounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>V.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Tre, &thorn;ou art loked by lawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at a &thorn;eefe and a traytour on &thorn;e schal deye,</L>
<L N="72">Now is tru&thorn;e with tresoun drawe,</L>
<L>Vertu is falle by vicys weye;</L>
<L>Love and tru&thorn;e and so&thorn;efast sawe,</L>
<L>On a tre traytours do teye,</L>
<L N="76">Now is vertue with vyces slawe:</L>
<L>Of all vertues cryst is keye,</L>
<L>&para; Vertue is swetter &thorn;an spyces,</L>
<L>In foote and honde he bere&thorn; blody prykke,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;e heed is full of &thorn;ornes &thorn;ikke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e goode hange&thorn; among &thorn;e wikke,</L>
<L>Vertue &thorn;us deie&thorn; wi&thorn; vyces.
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="200"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Cros, vnkynde &thorn;ou schalt be kyd,</L>
<L N="84">My sonys stepmodir I &thorn;e calle:</L>
<L>My bridde was borne with beeste on bedde,</L>
<L>And by my Fleissche my fruyt gan fall[e],</L>
<L>And with my breestys my brid I fedde;</L>
<L N="88">Cros, &thorn;ou &yogh;yuest hym eysell and galle!</L>
<L>My white rose rede is spred,</L>
<L>&THORN;at floryssched was in fodders stalle;</L>
<L>&para; Feet and faire handes</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at now be croysed I kissed hem ofte,</L>
<L>I lulled hem and leyde hem softe:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou Cros haldes hym hi&yogh;e alofte</L>
<L>Bounde in blody bandes!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<L N="96">&para; My love I lulled vppe in hys leir,<MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With cradel-bande I gan hym bynde,</L>
<L>Cros, he stike&thorn; vppon &thorn;i steir,</L>
<L>Naked in &thorn;e wylde wynde:</L>
<L N="100">Fowles formen her nest in &thorn;e eyr,</L>
<L>Foxes in den rest &thorn;ei fynde,</L>
<L>But goddys sone and heuenys eir,</L>
<L>Hys hede holde&thorn; on &thorn;ornes tynde,</L>
<L N="104">&para; Of moornyng I may mynne:</L>
<L>My sonys hed ha&thorn; reste none,</L>
<L>But lene&thorn; on &thorn;e schuldre bone;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ornes &thorn;orow &thorn;e panne is gone</L>
<L N="108">Thys woo I wyte synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Cros, to sle hym is &thorn;i slei&thorn;e,</L>
<L>My blody brid &thorn;ou berest fro blysse;</L>
<L>Cros, &thorn;ou holdest hym hi&yogh;e on hei&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="112">Hys faire feet I may not kysse:
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>My mou&thorn;e I putte, my swere I strecche</L>
<L>Hys feet to kys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes fro &thorn;e cros me kecche,</L>
<L N="116">And on me make her mowe amys,</L>
<L>&para; Her game and her gawdes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes wrou&yogh;t on me wo:</L>
<L>Cros, I fynde &thorn;ou art my fo,</L>
<L N="120">My brid &thorn;ou berist beten blo;</L>
<L>Among &thorn;es folys frawdys."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IX.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Cristys Cros &thorn;an &yogh;af answere:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Lady, to &thorn;e I owe honour,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;i bry&yogh;t palme now I bere;</L>
<L>My schynyng schewe&thorn; of &thorn;i flour,</L>
<L>Thy trye fruyt I to-tere;</L>
<L>&THORN;i fruyt me florysschi&thorn; in blood colour</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e worlde to wynne as &thorn;ou mayst here;</L>
<L>&THORN;is blossom blomed in &thorn;i bour,</L>
<L>&para; Not all for &thorn;e alone,</L>
<L>But forto wynne all &thorn;is werd;</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at waltere&thorn; vndir &thorn;e deueles swerd:</L>
<L>&THORN;orowe foote and honde god lete hym gerd,</L>
<L>To amende mannys mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>X.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Adam dyd full grete harmes,</L>
<L N="136">He bote a fruyt vnder a bowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore &thorn;i fruit spred hys armes,</L>
<L>On tre &thorn;at is ti&yogh;ed with tyndes towe;</L>
<L>Hys body is smyte ny &thorn;e &thorn;armes,</L>
<L N="140">He swelt with a swemely swow;</L>
<L>Hys breest is bored with dee&thorn;is armes,</L>
<L>And with hys dee&thorn; fro dee&thorn; vs drowe
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>&para; And all hys goode freendys,<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="144">As Isayas spak in prophecye:</L>
<L>He seyde '&thorn;i sone, seynt Marye,</L>
<L>Hys de&thorn;e slowe de&thorn;e in Caluarye,</L>
<L>And leue&thorn; with-oute endys'.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XII.</HEAD>
<L N="148">&para; Lady, love do&thorn;e &thorn;e alegge</L>
<L>Fruite prikkyd with sperys orde:</L>
<L>I Cros, with-oute knyues egge,</L>
<L>I kerue fruit best of horde;</L>
<L N="152">All is rede, Ribbe and rigge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bak blede&thorn; a&yogh;ens &thorn;e borde;</L>
<L>I am a pyler and bere a brigge,</L>
<L>God is &thorn;e weye, witnesse one worde;</L>
<L N="156">&para; God sei&thorn; he is so&thorn;efast weye:</L>
<L>Many folk slode to hell slider,</L>
<L>To heuene noman cowde &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>Til god dei&yogh;ed and tau&yogh;t whider</L>
<L N="160">Men drawe whan &thorn;ei deye:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; And Moyses fourmed hys figour,</L>
<L>A whyte lambe, and noon o&thorn;er beest</L>
<L>He sacred so oure sauyour,</L>
<L N="164">To be mete of my&yogh;tes meest,</L>
<L>And chosen cheef in honour,</L>
<L>I bare fleissche to folkys feest;</L>
<L>Iesu cryst oure creatour,</L>
<L N="168">Hys Flessche fede&thorn; leste and mest,</L>
<L>&para; Rosted a&yogh;ens &thorn;e sonne;</L>
<L>On me lay &thorn;e lambe of love,</L>
<L>I was plater, hys body above,</L>
<L N="172">Whan flessche and veynes all to-clove,</L>
<L>With blood I was bironne.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="203"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;it Moyses &thorn;is resoun rad,</L>
<L>'Ete &yogh;oure lambe with soure vergeous';</L>
<L N="176">Sowre saws make &thorn;e sowle glad,</L>
<L>Sorowe for synnes oures;</L>
<L>&THORN;at vergeous make&thorn; &thorn;e fende a-drad,</L>
<L>And fer fle&thorn; fro goddis spous;</L>
<L N="180">And bere a staaf and stonde sadde,</L>
<L>Whan flessche &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fedi&thorn; in goddis hows,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is staf is crystis crouche;</L>
<L>Stonde &thorn;ou styf by &thorn;is stake,</L>
<L N="184">Whan &yogh;e fonge &yogh;owre fleissche in take,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;e deuyll no maystryes make,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure sowles to touche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan pardoun is schewed with a scryne,<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="188">With boke on bord with nayles smyte,</L>
<L>With rede lettres wryten blyne,</L>
<L>Blewe and blak among me pyte:</L>
<L>My lorde I likne to &thorn;at signe,</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;e body was bored and on borde bete,</L>
<L>In bri&yogh;t blode oure boke gan schyne;</L>
<L>How woo he was no wi&yogh;t may wyte,</L>
<L>&para; Ne rede in hys rode;</L>
<L N="196">&YOGH;oure pardoun boke fro top to too,</L>
<L>Wryten it was full wonder woo,</L>
<L>Rede woundes and strokes bloo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;oure boke was bounde in blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIII.</HEAD>
<L N="200">&para; In holy write &thorn;is tale I herde,</L>
<L>How riche &yogh;iftis god vs &yogh;af;</L>
<L>God sei&thorn; hym-self a good scheperde,</L>
<L>And euery herde byhoue&thorn; a staf;
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="204"></L>
<L N="204">&THORN;e cros I kalle &thorn;e heerdys &yogh;erde,</L>
<L>&THORN;erwith &thorn;e deuyl a dent he &yogh;af,</L>
<L>With &thorn;at &yogh;erd &thorn;e wolfe he werid,</L>
<L>With dyntes drofe hym all to draf."</L>
<L N="208">&para; &THORN;e Cros &thorn;is tale tolde,</L>
<L>How he was &thorn;e staf in herdis hande,</L>
<L>Whan scheep borsten oute of bande<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>hande</I>.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wolfe he wered oute of lande</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at deuouride crystis folde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Oure ladye seyde, "Cros, of &thorn;i werk<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Mari]a.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wonder na&yogh;t &thorn;ei I be wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;us seyde Poule, crystes clerk,</L>
<L N="216">To &thorn;e fikell Iewes, with-oute o&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Iewes stone hard, with synnes merke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei bete a lambe with-oute lo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Softer &thorn;an water vnder serk,</L>
<L N="220">Milk or mede melled bo&thorn;e:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iewes were &thorn;e hard stonys.</L>
<L>Softer &thorn;an water or mylk lycour,</L>
<L>Or dew &thorn;at lithe on lily-flour</L>
<L N="224">Was cristes body in blode colour,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes brisseden hys bonys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XX.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Si&thorn;e mannys sone was so nedy,</L>
<L>To be lad as a lamb so mylde,</L>
<L N="228">Why were gylours so gredy</L>
<L>To fowle so my faire chylde?</L>
<L>And Cros, why were &thorn;ou so redy</L>
<L>My fruite to foule fer in felde?"</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;e cros seyde, "to make &thorn;e deuyll dredy,</L>
<L>God schope me schelde schame to schelde,
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>&para; Si&thorn;e lombe of love dyede,<MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And on me &yogh;elde hys goost with voys;</L>
<L N="236">Men chose me a relyk choys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e signe of Iesu Crystis Croys,</L>
<L>&THORN;er dar no deuyl abyede:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Many folk, I defende fro her foos":</L>
<L N="240">Cristes cros &thorn;is sawe he seyde:&mdash;</L>
<L>"Heuene gate was keiyed clos</L>
<L>Til lambe of love now he deyede,</L>
<L>It is write in tixt and glos:</L>
<L N="244">For Cristis dee&thorn; prophetes preyde:</L>
<L>Till lambe of love deyed and roos</L>
<L>In hell pyne many folk was teyde:</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e houre of hi&yogh;est noone,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;e lambe of love seide his &thorn;ou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>'All is fullfilled &thorn;at well was wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Man is oute of bondys brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And heuene dorys vndone':</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXIII.</HEAD>
<L N="252">&para; And I was Cros and kepte &thorn;at &yogh;ifte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;eue was of fadres graunt,</L>
<L>I was loked I schulde vp-lifte</L>
<L>Goddis sone and Maydenes faunt<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>faint</I>.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="256">Noman had schelde of scrifte;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuyll stode as lyoun raumpaunt,</L>
<L>Many folk he keighte to hell clifte,</L>
<L>Till &thorn;e dyntes of &thorn;e cros gan hym adaunte;</L>
<L N="260">&para; My dede is founde and boked,</L>
<L>All &thorn;e werke &thorn;at I haue wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L>It was in &thorn;e fadres for&thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Louely lady, lak me nou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="264">I dyd as I was loked.
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="206"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXIV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; In water and blood cristenyng was wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Holy writ witnessi&thorn; it well,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e well of wor&thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="268">Man is cristened to soule hele;</L>
<L>&THORN;e blood &thorn;at all &thorn;e world ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A digne cristenyng he gan me dele;</L>
<L>Cryst in cristenynge for&yogh;at me nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="272">Hy[s] fressche blood whan I gan fele:</L>
<L>&para; Mayde modir and wyue!</L>
<L>Crystis blood &yogh;af me bapteme,</L>
<L>Bystreke I was with rede streme,</L>
<L N="276">Whan Iesu bled vpon a beme,<MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of cipresse and Olyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Iesu seyde to Nichodemus</L>
<L>But a barn be twies born,</L>
<L N="280">Whan domesday schal blowe his bemys,</L>
<L>He schulde lye as man lorn,</L>
<L>First bore of wombe where rew&thorn;e remys,</L>
<L>Si&thorn; with font synne is schorn:</L>
<L N="284">And I was cros to mannys quemys,</L>
<L>I baar &thorn;e fruyt &thorn;ou bere aforn,</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;i beryng alone;</L>
<L>But I had born hym efte,</L>
<L N="288">Fro riche rest man had be refte</L>
<L>And in a lore logge lefte,</L>
<L>Ay to grucche and grone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXVI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou were crowned heuene queen,</L>
<L N="292">For &thorn;e bir&thorn;en &thorn;at &thorn;ou bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;i garlond is of gracious greene,</L>
<L>Of hell Emperesse and heuene Empere:
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>I am &thorn;e relyk &thorn;at schyne&thorn; schene,</L>
<L N="296">Men wolde wyte where I were,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e pleyn parlement I schal been,</L>
<L>At domesday prestly to pere;</L>
<L>&para; Whan god schal seye ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="300">'Trewly on &thorn;ee rode tre,</L>
<L>Man, I dyed for loue of &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Man, what hast &thorn;ou do for me</L>
<L>To be my frendly fere?'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXVII.</HEAD>
<L N="304">&para; At parlement I wil put pleynyng,</L>
<L>How maydenes sone on me gan sterue,</L>
<L>Spere and spounge and hard naylyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hard hede &thorn;e helme gan kerue:</L>
<L N="308">And I schal crye ri&yogh;tful kyng,</L>
<L>Ilk man haue as &thorn;e serue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ri&yogh;t schul ryse to ryche reynynge,</L>
<L>Truyt and treget to helle schal terve:</L>
<L N="312">&para; Mayde meke and mylde!</L>
<L>God took in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> hy[s] flessch trewe,</L>
<L>I bare &thorn;i fruyt lele and newe;</L>
<L>It is ri&yogh;t &thorn;e rode to Eue helpe schewe</L>
<L N="316">Man, woman, and chylde".</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXVIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e queen &thorn;us acorded with &thorn;e Cros,<MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens hym spak nomore speche;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lady &yogh;af &thorn;e cros a cosse,</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;e lady of love longe loue gan seche,</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . . .</L>
<L N="324">. . . . . .
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e queen and &thorn;e cros acord:</L>
<L>&THORN;e queen bare first, &thorn;e cros aftirward,</L>
<L>To fecche folk fro hellward,</L>
<L N="328">On holy steyres to sty&yogh;e vpward</L>
<L>And reigne with oure lord.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXXIX.</HEAD>
<L>&para; A clerk fourmed &thorn;is figour</L>
<L>Of Maries sorwe to sei&yogh;e summe,</L>
<L N="332">As he had see in scharp schour,</L>
<L>How cristes armes were rent and rune;</L>
<L>&THORN;e cros is a colde creatour</L>
<L>And euer &yogh;it was deef and dum,</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;is tale florissched with a faire flour,</L>
<L>&THORN;is poynt I proue apocrifum;</L>
<L>&para; Witnesse was neuer founden</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere crystis cros spak,</L>
<L N="340">Ne oure lady leyde hym no lak,</L>
<L>But forto dryue &thorn;e deuyll a-bak,</L>
<L>Men speke of Cristes wounden.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A clerk fourmed &thorn;is fantasye,</L>
<L N="344">On cristes steruyng stok to stere;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bare &thorn;e body all blody,</L>
<L>Whan de&thorn;es dent gan hym dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is Apocrifum is no foly:</L>
<L N="348">In swich a lay dar &thorn;e na&yogh;t dere</L>
<L>&THORN;at do&thorn;e man to seke mercy,</L>
<L>Wikked werkes awey to were,</L>
<L>&para; In tixte ful well is write:</L>
<L N="352">A lombe<NOTE PLACE="marg">? <I>clerk.</I></NOTE> ha&thorn; larged all &thorn;is glose,</L>
<L>Plent&eacute; speche &thorn;er-In to prose,</L>
<L>&THORN;e counseill of &thorn;e cros to vnclose</L>
<L>Of Maryes woo to wite.
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="209"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XL.</HEAD>
<L N="356">&para; In flesshly wede</L>
<L>God gan hym hede,</L>
<L>Of mylde may</L>
<L>Was born to blede,</L>
<L N="360">As cristes crede</L>
<L>So&thorn;ely to say;</L>
<L>On stokky stede</L>
<L>He roode, men rede,</L>
<L N="364">In rede aray.</L>
<L>Fro deuelis drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at duk vs lede</L>
<L>At domesday,</L>
<L N="368">&para; Whan pepil schal parte and passe<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To holy heuene and hell &thorn;e wode.</L>
<L>Now Cristes crosse and crystes blode</L>
<L>And Maries praier mylde and goode</L>
<L N="372">Graunte vs &thorn;e lyfe of grace. Amen.</L>
</LG>


</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000242.tif" N="210">
<HEAD>FESTIVALS OF THE CHURCH. [Royal MS. 18 A x.]</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH><Q>&para; Deo nostro iocunda sit laudacio.</Q></EPIGRAPH>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"> &para; Ioyeful preisyng to god oure lord</L>
<L>&THORN;e sawter book bere&thorn; record.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>I.</HEAD>
<L>The lord &thorn;at is a howsholder,</L>
<L N="4">With faire festis folk he fat;</L>
<L>&YOGH;iue&thorn; hem wedys hym self do&thorn;e were,</L>
<L>On bolstre bed her balys bat;</L>
<L>Tonge gyue&thorn; talke and stere</L>
<L N="8">To preysen hym men taken gat;</L>
<L>Oure lord to preise is no ler,</L>
<L>&THORN;e same help man he byhat,</L>
<L>With hym on bedde, man, &thorn;ou sat</L>
<L N="12">&para; On &thorn;e bolstre of heuene blisse.</L>
<L>With hys fleisshe he fedi&thorn; &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>, &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;i sowle schal be clad as hys</L>
<L>In lyfe &thorn;at neuermore lat.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<L N="16">&para; Malachie witnesse ha&thorn; gunne</L>
<L>In hys rewle, as it is rad;</L>
<L>He sei&thorn; &thorn;at god is soo&thorn;fast sunne,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at same &thorn;i sowle is clad;</L>
<L N="20">&para; &THORN;i lordes wede &thorn;an hast &thorn;ou wonne</L>
<L>And with hys fleisshe &thorn;i goost is fed;</L>
<L>He let atame hys pyement tunne
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>To make his gode gestis glad,</L>
<L N="24">&para; With a spere of grounden gad;</L>
<L>&THORN;an was founde a fell fawset,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e trie tunne it was sette,</L>
<L>In cristes hert was pi&yogh;t and pette,</L>
<L N="28">Hys brest was al be-blad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>III.</HEAD>
<L>&para; I haue ioye forto gest</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e lambe of love with-oute o&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Hys flessche is oure faire feest,</L>
<L N="32">And curteisly he &yogh;eue&thorn; vs clo&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Viij feestis oure lord gan dresse,<MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And all be newe euery &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Heuene quene and hell Emperesse,</L>
<L N="36">A blisful blosum &thorn;i bosum bere!</L>
<L>&para; His fleissh fedi&thorn; more and lesse,</L>
<L>And fendi&thorn; vs from feendis fere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kirnell sprang at Cristemasse</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at now is crist in a cake clere,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e preest drynke&thorn; blessyd bere,</L>
<L>Goddis blood in sacrament.</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ty god omnipotent,</L>
<L N="44">Hys blessyd body ha&thorn; sent</L>
<L>To fede hys freendys here.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>V.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Cristemasse first is founde,</L>
<L>Whan god was borne with beest in bynne.</L>
<L N="48">At newe &yogh;ere cryst &thorn;oled wounde</L>
<L>And schadde hys blood for mannus<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. mainus.</NOTE> synne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Epiphanye is gret on grounde.</L>
<L>On estre day wel&thorn;es we wynne.
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="212"></L>
<L N="52">On holy &thorn;ursday god sti&yogh;e &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>On witsoneday god gan mynne</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;enke on mannys kynne,</L>
<L>He sent man &thorn;e holy goost.</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;e Trinit&eacute; feest ha&thorn; my&yogh;tes moost.</L>
<L>In Corpus christi wel &thorn;ou woost,</L>
<L>Is ioyned oure Ioye with gynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; At Cristemasse mayde Mary,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;orowe helpe of &thorn;e holy goostis heste,</L>
<L>&THORN;i brid was born and lay &thorn;e by,</L>
<L>Aboute bo&thorn;e bynne and beeste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aungels maden melody</L>
<L N="64">For ioye of cristis feeste;</L>
<L>A clere note &thorn;ei sang in &thorn;e sky,</L>
<L>Whan kyngis sone bare fleisshly creste.</L>
<L>&para; Scheperdes meest and leest,</L>
<L N="68">"Ioye to god full of love,"</L>
<L>Herden &thorn;ei Aungels synge above,</L>
<L>"Pes to man, &thorn;e deuyll is drove</L>
<L>Fro goddis trone in &thorn;e eest."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VII.</HEAD>
<L N="72">&para; &THORN;an my&yogh;t &thorn;e mylde may synge</L>
<L>Ysaye &thorn;e woord of &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seydest a &yogh;erd schulde sprynge</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;e rote of Ientill Iesse,</L>
<L N="76">&para; And schulde floure with florisschyng,<MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With primeroses greet plent&eacute;;</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e croppe schulde come a kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is a lord of power and pyt&eacute;,</L>
<L N="80">&para; My swete sone I see.</L>
<L>I am &thorn;e &yogh;erde, &thorn;ou art &thorn;e flour,</L>
<L>My brid is borne by beest in boure,
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>My primerose my paramour,</L>
<L N="84">With love I lulle &thorn;ee.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>VIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; &YOGH;it my&yogh;t &thorn;e mylde may among</L>
<L>Her cradel trille to and fro,</L>
<L>And syng, Osye, &thorn;i song!&mdash;</L>
<L N="88">"De&thorn;e, my de&thorn;e schal &thorn;ee slo."</L>
<L>&THORN;e de&thorn;e of hell is full strong,</L>
<L>Where spirites bren in blases blo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e flesshe schal dye &thorn;at my sone gan fong</L>
<L N="92">And sle &thorn;at de&thorn;e for euermo;</L>
<L>&para; To helle my child schal go.</L>
<L>As Osye bigan to speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt musell helle cheke</L>
<L N="96">And hell barre &thorn;i hand schal breke,</L>
<L>And fette frendes fro wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>IX.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Balaam tolde hys trewe entente,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Balaam.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of soo&thorn;fastnesse he schewed a signe&mdash;</L>
<L N="100">Of Iacob schulde a token be glente,</L>
<L>A sterre &thorn;at schulde schewe and schyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>X.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Moyses ffull well he spak<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Moyses.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e lambe &thorn;at sprang of mayden clene,</L>
<L N="104">A white lambe, with senn blak</L>
<L>Spotty my&yogh;t he neuere bene;</L>
<L>&para; He lyued with-oute lak,</L>
<L>Till a spere hys loue gan spene,</L>
<L N="108">Whan lambes blood on breeste and bak,</L>
<L>No boon was broke with Iewes kene;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lambe schyned full schene,
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="214"></L>
<L>&THORN;at Mary lulled in louely place,</L>
<L N="112">As sche was ful full of grace,</L>
<L>To loke in &thorn;e lambes face,</L>
<L>&THORN;at si&yogh;t god leue vs sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan wroot wi&thorn; penne,<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou lyuest in charyt&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lombe of loue lyue&thorn; with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And in god &thorn;i goost schal be,</L>
<L>In wel&thorn;e heuene to wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XII.</HEAD>
<L N="120">&para; Make cristys cradell of &thorn;i herte,</L>
<L>In bonde of love bynde hym fast,</L>
<L>On a poure begger put a scherte,</L>
<L>And wollen wedys &thorn;at warm will last,</L>
<L N="124">To poure in prisoun &thorn;ou schalt sterte,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue &thorn;e wrecches of &thorn;e good &thorn;ou hast.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is seyle sette on &thorn;i mast</L>
<L>And seyle in-to &thorn;e blisse of heuene;</L>
<L N="128">At domesday god schal full euene</L>
<L>Monewe &thorn;e dedis of mersy seuene</L>
<L>To kaytyfes &thorn;at be cast.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Rokke &thorn;i cradell hi&yogh;e and lowe,</L>
<L N="132">Mir&thorn;e and Mischeef haue in mynde,</L>
<L>In heuene is ioyned ioye Inow,</L>
<L>In hell fyre and fil&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt fynde;</L>
<L>Whasshe &thorn;i sowle white as snowe,</L>
<L N="136">And in &thorn;at bed &thorn;is barn schal &thorn;e bynde;</L>
<L>In a cote, with-oute slow,</L>
<L>Oure lady lolled &thorn;i leve frende.</L>
<L>&para; Man haue &thorn;is in mynde,
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="215"></L>
<L N="140">Rokke &thorn;i cradell aboue &thorn;e skye,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on &thorn;e Madenys melodye,</L>
<L>&THORN;enk on helle stynkyng stye,</L>
<L>Where goostis bren in bynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIV.</HEAD>
<L N="144">&para; In vitas patrum, a fader booke,</L>
<L>Swiche a tale &thorn;er is tolde;</L>
<L>A sinfull womman crist forsooke,</L>
<L>Putte in dispeir with deuelys bolde,</L>
<L N="148">Sche was hent on hard hoke,<MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For hete of fei&thorn; kepte sche colde,</L>
<L>Till a wyse preest with hyr woke</L>
<L>And seyde, "for &thorn;e Iesu was solde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XV.</HEAD>
<L N="152">&para; Take ensaumple of a childe in towne,</L>
<L>With myshap his croune is craked,</L>
<L>With brode lippys he bere&thorn; boune,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is wepyng and deel awaked.</L>
<L N="156">&para; &THORN;e Norys with &thorn;e childe do&thorn;e roune,</L>
<L>A rede Appil sche ha&thorn; hym taked,</L>
<L>And he forsake&thorn; hys sobbyng soune,</L>
<L>And mochel myr&thorn;e &thorn;ere is maked.</L>
<L N="160">&para; Now sette &thorn;i will styf stakede</L>
<L>In fruyte swetter &thorn;an any mayde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ow &thorn;i synne haue hym affrayede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue hym &thorn;i hert and he is apayede</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at pere hys pees ha&thorn; makede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Was neuer childe so sone stille</L>
<L>With pere ne with appil swete,</L>
<L>As Maydens sone &thorn;at dyed on hill</L>
<L N="168">And for &thorn;i loue blood gan swete;
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if hym &thorn;i herte, with good will,</L>
<L>He will ne&thorn;er grucche ne grete;</L>
<L>Hys goost he &yogh;elde with schrikes schrylle,</L>
<L N="172">So lo&thorn;e he was &thorn;i love to lete.</L>
<L>&para; Oure lady her hede sche schette in a schete,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it lay still doted and dased,</L>
<L>As a womman mapped and mased,</L>
<L N="176">Fro ri&yogh;tfull resoun robbed and rased,</L>
<L>Till fele teres gan flete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e boke sei&thorn; god aske&thorn; lyte</L>
<L>With &thorn;ee to make a loveday;</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;i hert weye&thorn; not half a myte</L>
<L>Ageyn &thorn;e lyf &thorn;at lasti&thorn; ay.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if hym &thorn;at, he will not flyte,</L>
<L>But flemon all &thorn;i foos away;</L>
<L N="184">He wil &thorn;e make chartre and skryte</L>
<L>In heuen hall to holde &thorn;i way.</L>
<L>&para; Vppon a blody bay</L>
<L>A chartre of pees god made to a &thorn;ef,<MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="188">To aske mercy he was leef;</L>
<L>God bad hym go with-oute greef,</L>
<L>Into paradys forto play.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XVIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Thys feest at freeste</L>
<L N="192">Godlyche gladed geste,</L>
<L>Mayden cryst keste,</L>
<L>And rokked hym ri&yogh;t in her reste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XIX.</HEAD>
<L>&para; At newe&yogh;ere &thorn;e flour ful fressche,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Circumcisio<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>Circimcisio</I>.</NOTE> domini.</NOTE></L>
<L N="196">In holy writte I vndirstode
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>Was corve in hys tendre flessche,</L>
<L>For mannys loue he bledde hys blode.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e blood droppyd as dew on ryssche</L>
<L N="200">Fro &thorn;e mylde membre of &thorn;at swete fode;</L>
<L>Synne was harde, hys blood was nessche,</L>
<L>To defende folk fro feendys wode.</L>
<L>&para; The Iewes aboute &yogh;ode</L>
<L N="204">The olde lawe to fulfille;</L>
<L>&THORN;e childe suffride and lay stille</L>
<L>To bigge vs all, and &thorn;at was skille,</L>
<L>Whyle &thorn;e olde lawe stode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XX.</HEAD>
<L N="208">&para; &THORN;at day his first blood he bledde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;af man gri&thorn;e grace to haue,</L>
<L>With a scharp flynt hys blood was schedde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at kyng was corve as a knaue,</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;e briddes lymes were brode spradde.</L>
<L>&para; On schort membre &thorn;e child was schaue,</L>
<L>In lowenes was &thorn;at brid lad to haue</L>
<L>To kepe men fro helle cave,</L>
<L N="216">Mannys sowle to save.</L>
<L>&para; Lownesse lay byne&thorn;e &thorn;e sterres,</L>
<L>To bye hys chaffare &thorn;e child payed erres,</L>
<L>Dropes rede as ripe cherrees,<MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at fro his flesshe gan lave.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; God cam not to fordo &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>Ij lawes fulfill he wolde;</L>
<L>Goddis sone was leyde ful lawe,</L>
<L N="224">Whan he was maydenys childe on molde.</L>
<L>&para; Holy writte sei&thorn; &thorn;is sawe,</L>
<L>For mannys goost he &yogh;af no golde;
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>Hys dere blood was oute-drawe</L>
<L N="228">To helpe vs to hys heuenes holde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e childe lay flat vnfolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e riche prince was &thorn;ere aprised,</L>
<L>He suffred to be circumcised;</L>
<L N="232">Euery man &thorn;at is well avised</L>
<L>&THORN;is feest preyse he scholde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Festyng vs fedde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bloode ri&yogh;t &thorn;at a brid bledde,</L>
<L N="236">Lordys and ladde</L>
<L>Preyse&thorn; &thorn;e lord &thorn;at vs ladde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; The Epiphanye I preyse in prees,</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;e kyngis clenly come,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;ei made her hors rennen in rees,</L>
<L>To stonde stille &thorn;ei had no tome.</L>
<L>&para; With dromedaryes &thorn;ei droue fro dees,</L>
<L>Many a hundred myle fro home,</L>
<L N="244">To seche a childe &thorn;at choisly chees</L>
<L>In maydenes blode to blome.</L>
<L>&para; Swych a rose roos neuere in Rome,</L>
<L>As &thorn;an was clad in flesshli cloke;</L>
<L N="248">Goddis sone a mayden soke,</L>
<L>Milk ran by &thorn;e childys choke,</L>
<L>Swetter &thorn;an hony on gome.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIV.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Gold and myrre and frank ensens,<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="252">&THORN;ei brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e born brid,</L>
<L>Of riche gold one &yogh;af hym pens,</L>
<L>For richest kyng he scholde be kyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;er clerkis synge her sequens.</L>
<L N="256">Frank ensens &thorn;er is sone hid,
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e fende it is defens,</L>
<L>And dryue&thorn; hym vnder daunger lyd.</L>
<L>&para; And after it betyd</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at god was grettest preest,</L>
<L>&THORN;an was frank ensens hym nest,</L>
<L>And bitter mirre bote is brest,</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e Iewes him chyd.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXV.</HEAD>
<L N="264">&para; At &thorn;e feest of Architriclyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e lord &thorn;at bou&yogh;t vs oute of bonde,</L>
<L>Turned water in-to wyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;orowe blessyng of hys holy honde;</L>
<L N="268">I hope &thorn;at blessyng schal be myn,</L>
<L>Whan I lete lyfe in londe;</L>
<L>And gode man it schal be &thorn;ine,</L>
<L>To folwe god fast &yogh;if &thorn;ou fonde.</L>
<L N="272">&para; In writ I vndirstonde,</L>
<L>Foure feestis faire and fre,</L>
<L>Epiphanye be set on &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Epiphanye blessyd &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;ou kepest man fro schonde!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXVI.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Of fyue loves of barley greyn,</L>
<L>And ij fyssches in rwle is rad,</L>
<L>God made a feest faire and pleyn.</L>
<L N="280">V M<SUP>l</SUP> folk &thorn;er-with he fad,</L>
<L>With v lovys and fysshes tweyn,</L>
<L>Greet cumpany &thorn;er-with was glad;</L>
<L>&THORN;es woordys my&yogh;t &thorn;ou so&thorn;ely seyn,</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;e lord of plent&eacute; &thorn;e pepil fad;</L>
<L>&para; Riche relef &thorn;ei had,</L>
<L>Xij baskettis full of broke mete;</L>
<L>To preyse god we are depe in dete,
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="220"></L>
<L N="288">To preyse hym no man for&yogh;ete</L>
<L>With speches gode and glad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXVII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Foure festys in one be set,</L>
<L>By diuers dayes it fell;</L>
<L N="292">But at &thorn;e feest of mesure met,</L>
<L>Wyn of water god wrou&yogh;t well,</L>
<L>Neuer festour fedde better.<MILESTONE N="134b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>V M<SUP>l</SUP> folk &thorn;an crist gan fede,</L>
<L N="296">To flum Iordan &thorn;e kyng gan fle,</L>
<L>And Iohan ba&thorn;ed hym in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>&para; Iohan weissch his faire fell</L>
<L>And crystened crist in water colde,</L>
<L N="300">Whan crist was xxx wynter olde;</L>
<L>Thus iiij feestis to-gedir folde,</L>
<L>To stroye &thorn;e fende so fell.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXVIII.</HEAD>
<L>&para; Estren is oure ful fode,</L>
<L N="304">Whan cristis flesshe freendys schal fede;</L>
<L>All festis arn full gode,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at is dou&yogh;tiest at nede;</L>
<L>We ete &thorn;e duke &thorn;at died on rode,</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;at all deueles in helle drede;</L>
<L>Forsake &yogh;oure synnes wrecches wode,</L>
<L>Or mete of mercy &yogh;if &yogh;ou no mede.</L>
<L>&para; God his blood gan schede,</L>
<L N="312">His riche ribbes weren rent all rede,</L>
<L>For mannys love he &thorn;oled dede;</L>
<L>Now is hys body in forme of brede,</L>
<L>To stroye &thorn;e prince of pride.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXIX.</HEAD>
<L N="316">&para; &THORN;e kyng ha&thorn; sent foure somouns,</L>
<L>Est and west in euery ende,
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>For clerkis with clere corounes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mete of mercy haue in mynde;</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;e godspelleres with benysouns,</L>
<L>To fest &thorn;ei bid euery freende,</L>
<L>As well beggers as barouns;</L>
<L>To goddis borde &thorn;ei bid hem bende</L>
<L N="324">&para; Ihesus holt vp his ende,</L>
<L>To defende vs with a fowle (egle) in fly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A dere oxe luk ha&thorn;e di&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Mark a lyoun fell in fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="328">Mathew a man ful kende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>XXX.</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Egle is frikest fowle in flye,</L>
<L>Ouer all fowles to wawe hys wenge;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is ensaumple Iohan say eslye,</L>
<L N="332">As he slombrid in slepynge,</L>
<L>In goddis godhed he say full hy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hey&yogh;tes of hys hy&yogh;e kynge.</L>
<L>With-oute any . . . . .<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>The rest is lacking.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>


</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000254.tif" N="222">
<HEAD>II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="miscellany">
<HEAD>HORAE DE CRUCE<NOTE PLACE="foot">Only the <I>English</I> parts are here given, with the beginnings of the Latin prayers, &amp;c. preceding them.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS Miscell. Liturg. 104. (Bodl. Libr.) temp. Edw. III. or Edw. II. and Isabella (?).]</NOTE>.</HEAD>
<HEAD><I>Hic incipiunt matutine de passione domini nostri ihesu cristi antiphona.</I></HEAD>
<P>Patris sapiencia ueritas diuina deus [&amp;c.]<MILESTONE N="50" UNIT="folio">
<I>Versiculus.</I> Adoramus te criste [&amp;c.]
DOmine ihesu criste filii dei uini pone passionem<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio">
crucem et mortem tuam [&amp;c.] Amen.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Swete ihesu cryst goddis sone of lyue.<MILESTONE N="51" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;in <MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio">passion &thorn;in croys &thorn;in ded &thorn;in wondes five.</L>
<L>Beelde us houre sinful soules and &thorn;in iugement.</L>
<L N="4">Nou and in tyme of ded &thorn;at we ne be y-schent.</L>
<L>[D]eyne to &yogh;eue my[&yogh;]t an[d] grace to hem &thorn;at moten lyuen.</L>
<L>And to dare reste here sinnes &thorn;ou for yyue.</L>
<L>Mo holi chirche and <MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="folio">kyndom loue and pes &thorn;ou sende.</L>
<L N="8">And to vs wreche sinful. lif wyt-outen ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;at leuest kyng god and man wyt-outin endingge.</L>
<L>Fader and sone and holy gost to &thorn;ulke bl[is]se us bringge.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Ad primam horam.</I> [&amp;c.]<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio">HOra prima dominum ducunt ad pilatum. [&amp;c.] Ado|ramus te. Domine ihesu criste.<MILESTONE N="61" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At prime ihesus was y-lad pilatus byfore.<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12">Many false witnesse on hym were i bore.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="223"></L>
<L>Hiis schines were y beten hiis honden weren y bonden.</L>
<L>Hiis face hy gonne on spete lyt of heuene &thorn;ey fonde.</L>
</LG>
<P><I>Ad terciam horam. amen</I> <NOTE PLACE="inter">[A leaf is wanting here.]</NOTE>Crucifige clamitant hora terciarum [&amp;c.] Adoramus [te]. Domine ihesu criste.<MILESTONE N="66" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At hondren day on wde &thorn;e giwes gonne grede.</L>
<L N="16">In schorn he was i.-wonden in purpil palle wede.</L>
<L>On his schulder he bar &thorn;e crois to &thorn;e piningge</L>
</LG>
<P>Sicut oculi ancille in manibus domine sue [&amp;c.]<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="folio"> Hora sexta ihesus est cruce conclauatus [&amp;c.] Adoramus [te]. Domine ihesu criste filij.<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE N="71" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At midday was ihesus crist y-nailed to &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L>Bitwixe tweye &thorn;eues he hongid for houre gode.</L>
<L N="20">For &thorn;uurst of stronge pine y-fuld he was wy[&thorn;] galle.<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ve holi louird so god y-wrout &thorn;er bui&yogh;t houre sinnes alle.</L>
</LG>
<P>DEus in adiutorium [&amp;c.] Hora nona dominus ihesus expirauit [&amp;c.] Adoramus. Domine ihesu criste filij.<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At none houre louerd crist of &thorn;ysse lif he wende.</L>
<L>He gradde hely &thorn;e holi gost to his fader he sende.</L>
<L N="24">A knyt wit a kene spere &thorn;erlede his syde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e herye quakede &thorn;e sonne bi-com swart &thorn;at erer <MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio">schon wel wide.</L>
</LG>
<P>Deus in adiutorium [&amp;c.]. De cruce deponitur hora uespertina fortitudo [&amp;c.]<MILESTONE N="82" UNIT="folio"> Adoramus te. Domine ihesu criste filij.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At euensong he was i-nome a doun &thorn;at dere us hadde ibou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>His mytte hys his streg&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lotede in hei&yogh;e holi &thorn;out.<MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="28">Swech de&thorn; he under feng hele of alle wo.</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;e croune of worschepe to lowe hy leide &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<P>COnuerte nos deus salutaris noster. [&amp;c.]
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="224"> HOra completorii. datur sepulture corpus [&amp;c.] Ado|ramus [te]. Domine ihesu criste.<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE N="90" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was y-&yogh;eue to beryyng ate laste tyde.</L>
<L>Cristes body noble hope of liue to byde.</L>
